        $('#instructionsIFrame').contents().find("#tabHolder > a:nth-child(1)").html("MD100");
        $('#instructionsIFrame').contents().find("#pages").html('<div class="page selected" id="page0"> <h1 id="practice-lab-setup">Practice Lab Setup</h1> <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2> <p>In this lab, you set up your machines.</p> <h3 id="task-1-Setup-your-lon-cl1-machine">Task 1: Set up your LON-CL1 machine</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum\Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click <strong>Start</strong>, and then select <strong>Windows Terminal (Admin)</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Administrator: Windows PowerShell window, type the following commands and press <strong>Enter</strong> after each command:</p> </li> <pre> <code>Invoke-WebRequest -Uri &quot;https://raw.githubusercontent.com/AqStudio1/Scripts/main/LON-CL1.ps1&quot; -OutFile &quot;LabSetup.ps1&quot;</code> </pre> <pre> <code>.\LabSetup.ps1</code> </pre> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-Setup-your-lon-cl2-machine">Task 2: Set up your LON-CL2 machine</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(3)&quot;).click()">LON-CL2</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum\Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click <strong>Start</strong>, and then select <strong>Windows Terminal (Admin)</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Administrator: Windows PowerShell window, type the following commands and press <strong>Enter</strong> after each command:</p> </li> <pre> <code>Invoke-WebRequest -Uri &quot;https://raw.githubusercontent.com/AqStudio1/Scripts/main/LON-CL2.ps1&quot; -OutFile &quot;LabSetup.ps1&quot;</code> </pre> <pre> <code>.\LabSetup.ps1</code> </pre> </ol> <h3 id="task-3-Setup-your-lon-dc1-machine">Task 3: Set up your LON-DC1 machine</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(1)&quot;).click()">LON-DC1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum\Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click <strong>Start</strong>, and then select <strong>Windows Terminal (Admin)</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Administrator: Windows PowerShell window, type the following commands and press <strong>Enter</strong> after each command:</p> </li> <pre> <code>Invoke-WebRequest -Uri &quot;https://raw.githubusercontent.com/AqStudio1/Scripts/main/LON-DC1.ps1&quot; -OutFile &quot;LabSetup.ps1&quot;</code> </pre> <pre> <code>.\LabSetup.ps1</code> </pre> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise, you will have successfully set up your machines.</p> <p><strong>END OF LAB</strong></p> </div> <div class="page" id="page1"> <h1 id="practice-lab-managing-local-user-and-microsoft-account-authentication">Practice Lab 01: Managing Local User and Microsoft Account Authentication</h1> <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2> <p>In this lab you configure and manage local accounts and assign a Microsoft account to a Windows device.</p> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>You need to create two new local user accounts on LON-CL1. User1 will be a local administrator and User2 will be a standard user. User1 will also assign a Microsoft account to LON-CL1 and configure Windows Hello with a PIN.</p> <p><em>Note: To complete Task 2, you need to have a Microsoft account to add to LON-CL1. You can create a free Microsoft account at <a href="https://outlook.live.com">https://outlook.live.com</a>. Your instructor can guide you on how to create an account if required.</em></p> <h3 id="task-1-configure-and-manage-local-accounts">Task 1: Configure and manage local accounts</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">.&bsol;Admin</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong>, and then select <strong>Settings</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Settings</strong> page, select <strong>Accounts</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the details pane, select <strong>Other users</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Other users</strong> section, select <strong>Add someone else to this PC</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Microsoft account</strong> dialog box, select <strong>I don&#39;t have this person&#39;s sign-in information</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Create account</strong> dialog box, select <strong>Add a user without a Microsoft account</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Create a user for this PC</strong> page, in the <strong>User name</strong> box, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">User1</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Enter password</strong> and <strong>Re-enter password</strong> boxes, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select three security questions, provide appropriate answers and then select <strong>Next</strong>. The User1 local account is created and listed under <strong>Other users</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>User1</strong> and then select <strong>Change account type</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Change account type</strong> dialog box, select the drop-down menu and then select <strong>Administrator</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>OK</strong> to return to the <strong>Other users</strong> page. Notice that User1 is now listed as an Administrator.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click the <strong>Start</strong> button and select <strong>Computer Management</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under <strong>System Tools</strong>, expand <strong>Local Users and Groups</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select the <strong>Users</strong> node. Notice that User1 is listed along with other local accounts. Accounts with an arrow pointing downwards are disabled accounts.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click <strong>User1</strong>. Notice the <strong>Set Password</strong> command, used to set a new password for the account.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Properties</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select the <strong>Member Of</strong> tab and take note of the default group memberships. Notice that User1 is a member of the <strong>Administrators</strong> group as configured previously.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>OK</strong> to close the <strong>User1 Properties</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click the <strong>Users</strong> node and then select <strong>New User</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>New User</strong> dialog box, enter the following and then select <strong>Create</strong>:</p> <ul> <li>User name: <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">User2</strong></li> <li>Password: <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong></li> <li>Confirm password: <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong></li> <li>User must change password at next logon: <strong>not selected</strong></li> </ul> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Close</strong> to close the <strong>New User</strong> dialog box. Notice that User2 is now included in the list of users.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of LON-CL1.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">.&bsol;User1</strong> with the password of <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>. Notice that it takes several minutes for the user profile to be created.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the <strong>Choose privacy settings for your device</strong> page, scroll down to the bottom of the page, and then select <strong>Accept</strong>. The Windows 10 desktop displays.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the taskbar, select <strong>File Explorer</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In <strong>File Explorer</strong>, browse to <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">C:&bsol;Users</strong>. Take note of the user profiles that have been created on this device.</p> </li> <li> <p>Double-click <strong>User1</strong> to display the profile content and folders.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close <strong>File Explorer</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-configure-a-microsoft-account-on-windows-11">Task 2: Configure a Microsoft Account on Windows 10</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Verify that you are signed in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">.&bsol;User1</strong> with the password of <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong> and then select <strong>Settings</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Settings</strong> page, select <strong>Accounts</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Accounts</strong> page, select <strong>Your info</strong>. Notice that User1 is currently signed in as a Local Account.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select the link that states <strong>Sign in with a Microsoft account instead</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Microsoft account Sign in</strong> page, enter your Microsoft account email address and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Enter password</strong> page, enter your Microsoft account password and then select <strong>Sign in</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Sign into this computer using your Microsoft account</strong> page, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong> and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Create a PIN</strong> page, select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Set up a PIN</strong> dialog box, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">1029</strong> in both the <strong>New PIN</strong> and <strong>Confirm PIN</strong> boxes. Select <strong>OK</strong>. Notice that your Microsoft account is now listed on the Your info page.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of LON-CL1.</p> </li> <li> <p>From the Sign-in page, select your Microsoft account and enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">1029</strong> for the PIN. Your account signs in to the desktop.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-3-remove-a-microsoft-account-on-windows-11">Task 3: Remove a Microsoft Account on Windows 10</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Verify that you are signed in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> with your Microsoft account.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong> and then select <strong>Settings</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Settings</strong> page, select <strong>Accounts</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Accounts</strong> page, select <strong>Your info</strong>. Notice that User1 is currently signed in with your Microsoft account.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select the link that states <strong>Sign in with a local account instead</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Are you sure you want to switch to a local account</strong> page, select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On Windows Security page, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">1029</strong> for your PIN.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Enter your local account info page, configure the following and then select <strong>Next</strong>:</p> <ul> <li>User name: <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">User1</strong></li> <li>New password: <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong></li> <li>Confirm password: <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong></li> <li>Password hint: <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">default</strong></li> </ul> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Sign out and finish</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise you have successfully configured and managed local accounts and assigned a Microsoft account to a Windows device.</p> <p><strong>END OF LAB</strong></p> </div> <div class="page" id="page2"> <h1 id="practice-lab-managing-domain-authentication">Practice Lab 02: Managing Domain Authentication</h1> <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2> <p>In this lab you will join a device to an Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain.</p> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>You need to join LON-CL2 to the Adatum.com AD DS domain. This will enable central management of the device and enable users to sign in using their domain credentials.</p> <h3 id="task-1-join-a-device-to-an-ad-ds-domain">Task 1: Join a device to an AD DS domain</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(3)&quot;).click()">LON-CL2</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Admin</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong>, and then select the <strong>Settings</strong> icon.</p> </li> <li> <p>In <strong>Settings</strong>, select <strong>Accounts</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Access work or school</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Access work or school</strong> page, select <strong>Connect</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Join this device to a local Active Directory domain</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Join a domain</strong> prompt, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum.com</strong> and select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Type as User name <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong>, type as Password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>, and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Add an account</strong> dialog box, under User account, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Ben</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under <strong>Account type</strong>, ensure that <strong>Standard User</strong> is selected and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Restart now</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-verify-that-the-device-is-joined-properly">Task 2: Verify that the device is joined properly</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(3)&quot;).click()">LON-CL2</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Ben</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>. It will take several minutes for the profile to be provisioned on LON-CL2.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong>, and then select the <strong>Settings</strong> icon.</p> </li> <li> <p>In <strong>Settings</strong>, select <strong>Accounts</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Access work or school</strong>. Notice that the device is connected to Adatum AD domain.</p> </li> <li> <p>From the taskbar, open <strong>File Explorer</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click <strong>This PC</strong> and then select <strong>Properties</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>About</strong> page, take note of the <strong>Device name</strong> and <strong>Full device name</strong>. The Domain shows <strong>Adatum.com</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close the About and File Explorer windows.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click the <strong>Start</strong> button and then select <strong>Computer Management</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Expand <strong>Local Users and Groups</strong>, and then select <strong>Users</strong>. Notice that Ben is not added to the local users list because Ben is a domain account.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select the <strong>Groups</strong> node.</p> </li> <li> <p>Double-click the <strong>Users</strong> group. Notice the <strong>Adatum&bsol;Ben</strong> is added to the local Users group. This allows Ben to sign in to the device. Select <strong>Cancel</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Double-click the <strong>Administrators</strong> group. </p> <blockquote> <p>Notice that Ben is not a local administrator. However, the <strong>Adatum&bsol;Domain Admins</strong> Active Directory group is added as a local administrator. Any user that is a member of the <strong>Adatum&bsol;Domain Admins</strong> group will be a local administrator on this device. </p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Cancel</strong>, and sign out of LON-CL2.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise you have successfully joined a device to an AD DS domain.</p> <p><strong>END OF LAB</strong></p> </div> <div class="page" id="page3"> <h1 id="practice-lab-managing-password-and-account-options">Practice Lab 03: Managing password and account options</h1> <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2> <p>In this lab you create and manage domain password policies, account options, and User Account Control.</p> <h2 id="exercise-1-managing-domain-password-policies">Exercise 1: Managing Domain Password Policies</h2> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>You have been delegated the task to configure the domain password policy for Adatum.com. Part of your task is to implement a new security requirement that specifies a longer password and a 20 minute account lockout if a user incorrectly enters their password more than three times in succession.</p> <p><em>Note: You will use LON-DC1 which includes all Windows Administrative Tools for remotely managing LON-DC1 and to perform Active Directory management tasks.</em></p> <h3 id="task-1-configure-password-and-account-options">Task 1: Configure password and account options</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(1)&quot;).click()">LON-DC1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> <blockquote> <p><strong>Server Manager</strong> opens.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>In Server Manager, select <strong>Tools</strong> and then select <strong>Group Policy Management.</strong></p> </li> <li> <p>In the Group Policy Management console, expand <strong>Forest:Adatum.com&bsol;Domains&bsol;Adatum.com</strong>, and then select the <strong>Group Policy Objects</strong> node.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Group Policy Objects in Adatum.com</strong> window, right‑click the <strong>Default Domain Policy</strong> policy, and then select <strong>Edit</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Group Policy Management Editor, expand the <strong>Computer Configuration&bsol;Policies&bsol;Windows Settings&bsol;Security Settings&bsol;Account Policies</strong> node, and then select <strong>Password Policy.</strong></p> </li> <li> <p>In the list of policies, double-click the <strong>Minimum password length</strong> policy.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Minimum password length Properties</strong> page, set the <strong>Password must be at least</strong> value to <strong>12</strong> characters, and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the console tree, select the <strong>Account Lockout Policy</strong> node.</p> </li> <li> <p>Double-click the <strong>Account lockout duration</strong> policy.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Account Lockout Duration Properties</strong> dialog box, select <strong>Define this policy setting</strong>, and then set the <strong>Account is locked out for</strong> value to <strong>20</strong> minutes. Select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Suggested Value Changes</strong> dialog box, select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Double-click the <strong>Account lockout threshold</strong> policy.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Account lockout threshold Properties</strong> dialog box, set the <strong>Account will lock out after</strong> setting to <strong>3</strong> invalid logon attempts, and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close the <strong>Group Policy Management Editor</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close the <strong>Group Policy Management console</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In Server Manager, in the <strong>Tools</strong> list, select <strong>Active Directory Users and Computers</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Expand the <strong>Adatum.com</strong> node, and then select the <strong>IT</strong> OU.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click the <strong>Jane Dow</strong> user account, and then select <strong>Properties</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Jane Dow Properties</strong> dialog box, select the <strong>Account</strong> tab.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the list of <strong>Account Options</strong>, clear the <strong>Password never expires</strong> check box, and then select the <strong>User must change password at next logon</strong> check box. select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-refresh-gpos">Task 2: Refresh GPOs</h3> <ol> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(1)&quot;).click()">LON-DC1</a></strong>, right-click <strong>Start</strong>, and then select <strong>Windows PowerShell (Admin)</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Administrator: Windows PowerShell window, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>:</p> </li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-attribute">Invoke-Gpupdate -force</span></code> </pre> <ol> <li>Close the <strong>Active Directory Users and Computers</strong> and the <strong>Windows PowerShell</strong> window.</li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise you created a password policy that will affect the password settings for all domain users.</p> <h2 id="exercise-2-testing-password-policy-settings">Exercise 2: Testing Password Policy Settings</h2> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>After configuring a more strict set of password policies you will then ask Jane Dow to test the policy settings.</p> <h3 id="task-1-verify-password-settings">Task 1: Verify password settings</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Switch to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> and sign in as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Jane</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>When the message appears that indicates the user’s password must be changed before signing in, select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the New password box and the Confirm password box, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd12</strong>, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>When the message displays that indicates that the new password does not meet the length, complexity, or history requirements of the domain, select <strong>OK</strong>. Type the old password, <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the New password box and the Confirm password box, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd1234</strong>, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>When a message displays that indicates that the password has been changed, select <strong>OK</strong>. Wait as the user profile is created for Jane.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of <strong>LON-CL1</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-attempt-repeated-sign-ins">Task 2: Attempt repeated sign-ins</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Attempt to sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Jane</strong> with the incorrect password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">password1</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>When a message displays that indicates that the password is incorrect, select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Attempt again to sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Jane</strong> with the incorrect password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">password1</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>When a message displays that indicates that the password is incorrect, select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Attempt again to sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Jane</strong> with the incorrect password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">password1</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>When the message displays that indicates that the referenced account is locked out, select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-3-unlock-a-locked-account">Task 3: Unlock a locked account</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Switch to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(1)&quot;).click()">LON-DC1</a></strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(1)&quot;).click()">LON-DC1</a></strong>, in Server Manager, in the <strong>Tools</strong> list, select <strong>Active Directory Users and Computers</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Expand the <strong>Adatum.com</strong> node, and then select the <strong>IT</strong> OU.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click the <strong>Jane Dow</strong> user account, and then select <strong>Properties</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Jane Dow Properties</strong> dialog box, select the <strong>Account</strong> tab.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select the check box next to <strong>Unlock account</strong>. This account is currently locked out on this Active Directory Domain Controller.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>OK</strong> to close the <strong>Jane Dow Properties</strong> box.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close <strong>Active Directory Users and Computers</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise you verified that the password policy works as expected.</p> <h2 id="exercise-3-configuring-uac">Exercise 3: Configuring UAC</h2> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>You need to configure UAC so that when the UAC dialog box prompts a standard user, he or she can enter the credentials of an administrator account to gain elevated privileges. You also need to restrict the execution of unsigned applications.</p> <h3 id="task-1-modify-uac-prompts">Task 1: Modify UAC prompts</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong> and then enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">gpedit.msc</strong>, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Local Group Policy Editor</strong>, expand <strong>Computer Configuration</strong>, expand <strong>Windows Settings</strong>, expand <strong>Security Settings</strong>, expand <strong>Local Policies</strong>, and then select <strong>Security Options</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the results pane, double-click <strong>User Account Control: Behavior of the elevation prompt for standard users</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>User Account Control: Behavior of the elevation prompt for standard users</strong> dialog box, select the <strong>Prompt for credentials</strong> drop down list, select <strong>Prompt for credentials on the secure desktop</strong>, and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the results pane, double-click <strong>User Account Control: Only elevate executables that are signed and validated</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>User Account Control: Only elevate executables that are signed and validated</strong> dialog box, select <strong>Enabled</strong>, and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the results pane, double-click <strong>User Account Control: Behavior of the elevation prompt for administrators in Admin Approval Mode</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>User Account Control: Behavior of the elevation prompt for administrators in Admin Approval Mode</strong> dialog box, select the <strong>Prompt for consent for non-Windows binaries</strong> drop down list, select <strong>Prompt for consent on the secure desktop</strong>, and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close the <strong>Local Group Policy Editor</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of <strong>LON-CL1</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-test-the-uac-prompts-as-a-standard-user">Task 2: Test the UAC prompts as a standard user</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Jon</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong>, and then enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Windows PowerShell</strong>. </p> </li> <li> <p>Under <strong>Windows PowerShell</strong>, select <strong>Run as administrator</strong>.</p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: The Windows operating system displays the User Account Control prompt.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>User name</strong> box, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Administrator</strong>, and in the <strong>Password</strong> box, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>, and then select <strong>Yes</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close the <strong>Windows PowerShell</strong> window.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of <strong>LON-CL1</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-3-verify-the-uac-notifications-as-an-administrator">Task 3: Verify the UAC notifications as an administrator</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong>, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Control Panel</strong>, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In <strong>Control Panel</strong>, select <strong>System and Security</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In <strong>Security and Maintenance</strong>, select <strong>Change User Account Control settings</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Verify that the slider is configured for <strong>Always notify</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Cancel</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close all open windows and sign out of <strong>LON-CL1</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise you have configured the prompt behavior of UAC.</p> <p><strong>END OF LAB</strong></p> </div> <div class="page" id="page4"> <h1 id="practice-lab-troubleshooting-domain-authentication">Practice Lab 04: Troubleshooting Domain Authentication</h1> <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2> <p>In this lab you will identify, troubleshoot, and remediate authentication and connectivity issues between a Windows client and an Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) domain.</p> <h2 id="exercise-1-identifying-and-troubleshooting-domain-authentication">Exercise 1: Identifying and Troubleshooting Domain Authentication</h2> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>A user named Jon has reported that he can no longer sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>. He also noticed that the standard departmental desktop Group Policy settings were not applying as usual. You need to troubleshoot and identify the issue that is causing Jon&#39;s group policy and sign-in issues.</p> <h3 id="task-1-simulate-the-issue">Task 1: Simulate the issue</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Open <strong>File Explorer</strong>, and then browse to <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">E:&bsol;Labfiles&bsol;Mod02</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Run the <strong>Scenario1.vbs</strong> script.</p> </li> <li> <p>Wait while LON-CL1 restarts.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-identify-the-issue">Task 2: Identify the issue</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click <strong>Start</strong>, and then select <strong>Windows Terminal (Admin)</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Administrator: Windows PowerShell window, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>:</p> </li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-attribute">gpupdate</span> /force</code> </pre> <ol> <li> <p>Notice that Group Policy fails to update. Read the message for information on how to diagnose the failure.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Administrator: Windows PowerShell window, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>:</p> </li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-attribute">GPRESULT</span> /H GPReport.html</code> </pre> <ol> <li>In the Administrator: Windows PowerShell window, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>:</li> </ol> <pre> <code>.&bsol;<span class="hljs-selector-tag">gpreport</span><span class="hljs-selector-class">.html</span></code> </pre> <ol> <li> <p>In the html report, select the link that states 6 Errors Detected. Review the information for details on why Group Policy is failing.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close the html report windows.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click <strong>Start</strong>, and then select <strong>Event Viewer</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Event Viewer, expand <strong>Windows Logs</strong>, and then select <strong>System</strong>. Review events related to the GroupPolicy source with Event ID 1129 and 1006.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close Event Viewer and sign out of LON-CL1.</p> </li> <li> <p>Attempt to sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Jon</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>. Take note of the error message and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Discuss with your class on what might be the issue based upon your investigation.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-3-remediate-the-issue">Task 3: Remediate the issue</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click <strong>Start</strong>, and then select <strong>Windows Terminal (Admin)</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Administrator: Windows PowerShell window, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>:</p> </li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-keyword">Reset</span>-ComputerMachinePassword -<span class="hljs-keyword">Server</span> LON-DC1 -Credential Adatum&bsol;Administrator</code> </pre> <ol> <li> <p>At the Windows PowerShell credential request prompt, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong> for the password.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Administrator: Windows PowerShell window, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>:</p> </li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-attribute">gpupdate</span> /force</code> </pre> <ol> <li> <p>Notice that Group Policy now updated successfully.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of LON-CL1.</p> </li> <li> <p>Attempt to sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Jon</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>. Notice that the user can sign-in successfully.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of LON-CL1.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise you will have identified the issue that is causing Jon to have group policy and sign-in issues. You also remediated the issue by performing a PowerShell command that resets the machine password with the Active Directory domain controller.</p> <p><strong>END OF LAB</strong></p> </div> <div class="page" id="page5"> <h1 id="practice-lab-managing-windows-settings">Practice Lab 05: Managing Windows Settings</h1> <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2> <p>In this lab you will validate and configure Windows 10 by using Windows Settings, the Control Panel, and Windows PowerShell. </p> <h2 id="exercise-1-configuring-settings-using-windows-settings-and-control-panel">Exercise 1: Configuring Settings Using Windows Settings and Control Panel</h2> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>You need to validate device and Windows specifications, configure various Windows 10 settings, and determine which applications are slowing down the Windows startup process. You also need to modify Focus assist settings to change how app notifications are received during non-working hours. Finally, you need to create a new power plan that minimizes power usage, but does not impact multimedia presentations while the device is running on battery.</p> <h3 id="task-1-validate-and-configure-windows-settings">Task 1: Validate and configure Windows Settings</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong> and then select the <strong>Settings</strong> icon.</p> </li> <li> <p>In <strong>Settings</strong>, select <strong>System</strong>, and then select <strong>About</strong>. Take note of the Device specifications and Windows specifications.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>System</strong>, and then select <strong>Clipboard</strong>. Take note of the Clipboard options, such as enabling clipboard history, syncing across devices, and clearing the clipboard data.</p> </li> <li> <p>Next to <strong>Clipboard history</strong>, select the slider to enable the feature.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>System</strong>, and then select <strong>Storage</strong>. Take note of the storage information including how storage is used on the device and features to use for storage management.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under <strong>Storage</strong>, select <strong>Configure Storage Sense or run it now</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under <strong>Storage Sense</strong>, select the slider to enable the feature. Take note of the additional cleanup schedules for Storage Sense.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>System</strong>, and then select <strong>Multitasking</strong>. Take note of configuration options related to the Snap feature, Alt + Tab, and the use of multiple desktops.</p> </li> <li> <p>In <strong>Settings</strong>, select <strong>Apps</strong>, and then select <strong>Apps &amp; features</strong>. Take note of the Apps &amp; features installed on the device.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Apps</strong>, and then select <strong>Startup</strong>. Take note of the apps that are configured to start when you sign in to the device.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close <strong>Settings</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-configure-focus-assist-settings">Task 2: Configure Focus assist settings</h3> <ol> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>, select <strong>Start</strong> and then select the <strong>Settings</strong> icon.</p> </li> <li> <p>In <strong>Settings</strong>, select <strong>System</strong>, and then select <strong>Notifications</strong>. </p> </li> <li> <p>Expand <strong>Notifications</strong> and take notice of the options that are enabled.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Focus assist.</strong></p> </li> <li> <p>Under <strong>Focus assist</strong>, take note of the default setting. Focus assist is off except for when an Automatic rule is active.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select the check box next to <strong>Show a summary of what I missed with focus assist was on</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under <strong>Automatic rules</strong>, select the rule named <strong>During these times</strong>. </p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>During these hours</strong> page, enable the feature and select the check box next to <strong>Show a notification in action center when focus assist is turned on automatically</strong>. This will ensure that only Priority notifications are received during 11:00 PM and 7:00 AM and a notification is visible that the feature is active.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close <strong>Settings</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-3-configure-power-options-using-the-control-panel">Task 3: Configure Power Options using the Control Panel</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong> and type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Control Panel</strong>. Press <strong>Enter</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Control Panel window, select <strong>Hardware and Sound</strong> and then select <strong>Power Options</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Create a power plan.</strong></p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Plan name</strong> box, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Power Save - Presentation</strong> and select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Create</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under <strong>Preferred plans</strong>, next to <strong>Power Save - Presentation</strong>, select <strong>Change plan settings</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Change advanced power settings</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Expand <strong>Hard disk</strong> and then expand <strong>Turn off hard disk after</strong>. Change the setting to <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">60</strong> minutes.</p> </li> <li> <p>Scroll down and expand the <strong>Multimedia settings</strong> option.</p> </li> <li> <p>Expand the <strong>When playing video</strong> option and change the setting to <strong>Balanced</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>OK</strong> to close the <strong>Power Options</strong> dialog box.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close all open windows.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results:</strong> After finishing this exercise you will have configured settings using Windows Settings and the Control Panel.</p> <h2 id="exercise-2-using-powershell-to-configure-windows">Exercise 2: Using PowerShell to Configure Windows</h2> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>You need to use Windows PowerShell to test the scripting environment. To become familiar with PowerShell you will run several commands and the use PowerShell ISE to create a script to list all running services on the device.</p> <h3 id="task-1-use-windows-powershell-to-configure-a-device">Task 1: Use Windows PowerShell to configure a device</h3> <ol> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>, select <strong>Start</strong> and type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">PowerShell</strong>. Select <strong>Run as administrator</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the PowerShell window, type the following and then press <strong>Enter</strong>:</p> </li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-attribute">Get-ExecutionPolicy</span></code> </pre> <ol> <li> <p>Confirm the current setting of the PowerShell execution policy is set to <strong>Unrestricted</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>If the execution policy is set to <strong>Restricted</strong>, change it to <strong>Unrestricted</strong> by running the following command at the PowerShell window:</p> </li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-keyword">Set</span>-ExecutionPolicy <span class="hljs-comment">Unrestricted</span></code> </pre> <ol> <li> <p>At the confirmation prompt, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Y</strong> and then select <strong>Enter</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Confirm that the execution policy is now <strong>Unrestricted</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the PowerShell window, launch Notepad by typing the following command and then press <strong>Enter</strong>:</p> </li> </ol> <pre> <code>Start-<span class="hljs-built_in">Process</span> Notepad</code> </pre> <ol> <li>At the PowerShell window, type the following command and then press <strong>Enter</strong>:</li> </ol> <pre> <code>Get-<span class="hljs-built_in">Process</span></code> </pre> <ol> <li> <p>Review the list of all running processes. Identify that Notepad is running and note the Process ID.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the PowerShell window, type the following command and then press <strong>Enter</strong>. Replace [ID] with the Process ID identified in step 9.</p> </li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-keyword">Stop</span>-Process -<span class="hljs-keyword">Id</span> [<span class="hljs-keyword">ID</span>]</code> </pre> <ol> <li> <p>Verify that the Notepad window is no longer open.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the PowerShell window, list the event logs by typing the following command and then press <strong>Enter</strong>:</p> </li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-keyword">Get</span>-EventLog -<span class="hljs-keyword">List</span></code> </pre> <ol> <li>At the PowerShell window, list the application log entries by typing the following command and then press <strong>Enter</strong>:</li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-attribute">Get-EventLog -LogName Application</span></code> </pre> <ol> <li>At the PowerShell window, clear the application log entries with a confirmation by typing the following command and then press <strong>Enter</strong>:</li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-keyword">Clear</span>-EventLog -LogName Application -<span class="hljs-keyword">confirm</span></code> </pre> <ol> <li>At the PowerShell window, verify that the application log entries have been removed by typing the following command and then press <strong>Enter</strong>:</li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-attribute">Get-EventLog -LogName Application</span></code> </pre> <ol> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong> and type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Telnet</strong>. Select <strong>Turn Windows features on and off</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Windows Features</strong> window, verify that <strong>Telnet Client</strong> is not selected.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the PowerShell Window, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>:</p> </li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-attribute">Enable-WindowsOptionalFeature -Online -FeatureName TelnetClient</span></code> </pre> <p><em>Note: This will install the Telnet Client windows feature.</em></p> <ol> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong> and type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Telnet</strong>. Select <strong>Open</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close all open windows.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-use-a-windows-powershell-script">Task 2: Use a Windows PowerShell Script</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong> and then in the <strong>Type here to search</strong> box, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">&bsol;&bsol;LON-DC1&bsol;Labfiles</strong> and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the content pane, double-click the <strong>Configure</strong> folder.</p> </li> <li> <p>Copy the <strong>Services.ps1</strong> file into the <strong>E:&bsol;Labfiles</strong> folder on LON-CL1.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong> and type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Powershell ISE</strong>. Press <strong>Enter</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Windows PowerShell ISE, open the script file <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">E:&bsol;Labfiles&bsol;Services.ps1</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Review the script and note the formatting as follows:</p> <ul> <li>Comments are green.</li> <li>Variables are red.</li> <li>Cmdlets are bright blue.</li> <li>Text in quotation marks is dark red.</li> </ul> </li> <li> <p>Review the script and note that after the script runs, all services that have the status of <strong>Running</strong> will display in green color. All services that do not have a status of Running will display in red color.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select line 3 in the script, and then select <strong>Run selection (F8)</strong>.</p> <p><em>Note: Only the command in line 3 will be executed.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Run script (F5)</strong>, and then read the output.</p> <p><em>Note: The output does not have multiple colors, because the script needs to be modified to provide that information.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>At the end of line 14, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">–ForegroundColor $color</strong></p> </li> <li> <p>On the toolbar, select <strong>Run script (F5)</strong> in the Windows PowerShell ISE window. Select <strong>OK</strong> to save the file, and then read the output.</p> <p><em>Note: Running services are green, and services that are not running are red.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>On line 16, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Write-Host &quot;A total of&quot; $services.count &quot;services were evaluated&quot;</strong></p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Run script (F5)</strong>, and in the Windows PowerShell ISE window select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>If necessary, select <strong>Show Command Add-on</strong> in the PowerShell ISE toolbar.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Commands</strong> pane, select the <strong>Write-Host</strong> cmdlet and then configure the following options:</p> <ul> <li> <p>BackgroundColor: <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Gray</strong></p> </li> <li> <p>ForegroundColor: <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Black</strong></p> </li> <li> <p>Object: <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">&quot;Script execution is complete&quot;</strong></p> </li> </ul> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Copy</strong> and paste the command to line 17 of the script.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Run script (F5)</strong>, and in the Windows PowerShell ISE window select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong> and type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">PowerShell</strong>. Press <strong>Enter</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the PowerShell window, type the following command and then press <strong>Enter</strong>:</p> </li> </ol> <pre> <code>Set-<span class="hljs-keyword">Location</span> <span class="hljs-title">D</span>:&bsol;Labfiles</code> </pre> <ol> <li>At the PowerShell window, type the following and then press <strong>Enter</strong>:</li> </ol> <pre> <code>.&bsol;<span class="hljs-selector-tag">Services</span><span class="hljs-selector-class">.ps1</span></code> </pre> <ol> <li>Close all open windows and sign out of LON-CL1.</li> </ol> <p><strong>Results:</strong> After completing the exercise you will have managed Windows using PowerShell and PowerShell scripts.</p> <p><strong>END OF LAB</strong></p> </div> <div class="page" id="page6"> <h1 id="practice-lab-customize-windows-start-and-taskbar-layouts">Practice Lab 06: Customize Windows Start Layout</h1> <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2> <p>In this lab you will customize and deploy a custom Windows 10 Start page layout.</p> <h2 id="exercise-1-customizing-the-start-layout-in-windows-10">Exercise 1: Customizing the Start Layout in Windows 10</h2> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>You need to ensure that Windows 10 devices contain the Adatum utilities apps on the Start menu. To do this, you decide to create and export a custom Start layout that only locks down the specified groups in the XML file. Users will still be able to customize other areas of the Start menu as needed.</p> <h3 id="task-1-customize-the-start-screen">Task 1: Customize the Start screen</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">.&bsol;Admin</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>. This signs in as the local administrator on the device.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong>, and right-click each tile and then select <strong>Unpin from Start</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>From the Start menu, right-click each of the following apps and then select <strong>Pin to Start:</strong></p> <ul> <li>Snip &amp; Sketch</li> <li>Sticky Notes</li> <li>Voice Recorder</li> <li>Calculator</li> <li>Alarms &amp; Clock</li> <li>Maps</li> </ul> </li> <li> <p>In the Start screen, just above the tiles, click and select <strong>Name group</strong> and then replace the text with <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum Utilities</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close the Start menu.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-export-the-start-layout">Task 2: Export the Start layout</h3> <ol> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>, right-click the Start menu and then select <strong>Windows PowerShell (Admin)</strong>. Select <strong>Yes</strong> at the User Account Control.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the PowerShell window, type the following command and then press <strong>Enter</strong>:</p> </li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-keyword">Export</span>-StartLayout -UseDesktopApplicationID -<span class="hljs-keyword">Path</span> <span class="hljs-keyword">E</span>:&bsol;Labfiles&bsol;AdatumLayout.xml</code> </pre> <ol> <li> <p>Open <strong>File Explorer</strong> and then browse to <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">E:&bsol;Labfiles</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click <strong>AdatumLayout.xml</strong>, point to <strong>Open with</strong> and then select <strong>Notepad</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the first instance of <strong>DefaultLayoutOverride</strong>, type the following:</p> </li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-tag">&lt;<span class="hljs-name">DefaultLayoutOverride</span> <span class="hljs-attr">LayoutCustomizationRestrictionType</span>=<span class="hljs-string">"OnlySpecifiedGroups"</span>&gt;</span></code> </pre> <ol> <li> <p>Save the <strong>AdatumLayout.xml</strong> file and then close Notepad.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close all open windows.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-3-deploy-the-start-layout-using-local-group-policy">Task 3: Deploy the Start layout using Local Group Policy</h3> <ol> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>, select <strong>Start</strong>, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">gpedit.msc</strong> and then press <strong>Enter</strong>. The Local Group Policy Editor opens.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the console tree, under <strong>User Configuration</strong>, expand <strong>Administrative Templates</strong>, and then select <strong>Start Menu and Taskbar</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Double-click <strong>Start Layout</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Start Layout</strong> box, select <strong>Enabled</strong> and under <strong>Start Layout File</strong> enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">E:&bsol;Labfiles&bsol;AdatumLayout.xml</strong>. Click <strong>OK</strong> and then close the <strong>Local Group Policy Editor</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of LON-CL1.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-4-verify-the-windows-10-start-layout">Task 4: Verify the Windows 10 Start layout</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Reda</strong> with the password of <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong> and then take note of the Start page. The <strong>Adatum Utilities</strong> group displays a lock icon that specifies that the group cannot be modified.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Start menu, right-click <strong>Calendar</strong> and then select <strong>Pin to Start</strong>. Notice that you can still customize other sections of the Start page.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of LON-CL1.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results:</strong> After completing the exercise you will have customized and deployed a custom Windows 10 Start layout.</p> <p><strong>END OF LAB</strong></p> </div> <div class="page" id="page7"> <h1 id="practice-lab-configuring-windows-settings-using-group-policy">Practice Lab 07: Configuring Windows Settings using Group Policy</h1> <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2> <p>In this lab you will create, validate, and troubleshoot Active Directory Group Policy Objects used to configure settings on Windows clients.</p> <h2 id="exercise-1-creating-a-group-policy-object">Exercise 1: Creating a Group Policy Object</h2> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>You have been delegated the task to create Group Policy Objects for the Adatum.com domain. Your first task create a group policy object that will display a warning message to anyone signing into a Research workstation. The message will warn the user that only authorized members of the research department are permitted to sign into the workstation. You will also create a second group policy object that will place a shortcut on the Windows desktop to write.exe for all members of the Marketing department.</p> <h3 id="task-1-create-a-group-policy-object-to-configure-security-settings">Task 1: Create a Group Policy Object to configure security settings</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(1)&quot;).click()">LON-DC1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password of <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>If necessary, select <strong>Start</strong>, and then select <strong>Server Manager</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Tools</strong> and then select <strong>Group Policy Management</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Maximize the Group Policy Management window. In the console tree, expand <strong>Forest:Adatum.com</strong>, expand <strong>Domains</strong>, and then expand <strong>Adatum.com</strong>. Select the <strong>Group Policy Objects</strong> node.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click the <strong>Group Policy Objects</strong> node, and then select <strong>New</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>New GPO</strong> dialog box, in the <strong>Name</strong> box, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Security Settings Policy</strong>, and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the details pane, right-click <strong>Security Settings Policy</strong>, and then select <strong>Edit</strong>. Maximize the <strong>Group Policy Management Editor</strong> window.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the console tree, under <strong>Computer Configuration</strong>, expand <strong>Policies</strong>, expand <strong>Windows Settings</strong>, expand <strong>Security Settings</strong>, expand <strong>Local Policies</strong>, and then select <strong>Security Options</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the details pane, double-click <strong>Interactive logon: Message text for users attempting to log on</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Interactive logon box, select the check box next to <strong>Define this policy setting in the template</strong> and then enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Only members of the Research department are authorized to sign in to Research workstations</strong>. </p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>OK</strong> to close the dialog box.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the details pane, double-click <strong>Interactive logon: Message title for users attempting to log on</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Interactive logon box, select the check box next to <strong>Define this policy setting</strong> and then enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Warning</strong>. </p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>OK</strong> to close the dialog box.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close the <strong>Group Policy Management Editor</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Double-click the <strong>Security Settings Policy</strong> and review the details for the group policy object. </p> <blockquote> <p>Take note that security filtering is configured to apply to all authenticated users by default.</p> </blockquote> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-create-a-group-policy-object-to-configure-preferences">Task 2: Create a Group Policy Object to configure Preferences</h3> <ol> <li> <p>In the Group Policy Management console, right-click the <strong>Group Policy Objects</strong> node, and then select <strong>New</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>New GPO</strong> dialog box, in the <strong>Name</strong> box, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Desktop Shortcut Policy</strong>, and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the details pane, right-click <strong>Desktop Shortcut Policy</strong>, and then select <strong>Edit</strong>. Maximize the <strong>Group Policy Management Editor</strong> window.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the console tree, under <strong>User Configuration</strong>, expand <strong>Preferences</strong>, expand <strong>Windows Settings</strong>, and then select <strong>Shortcuts</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click <strong>Shortcuts</strong>, point to <strong>New</strong>, and then select <strong>Shortcut</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>New Shortcut Properties</strong> dialog box, in the <strong>Name</strong> box, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Write</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Location</strong> drop-down menu, select <strong>Desktop</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Target path</strong> text box, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">C:&bsol;Windows&bsol;write.exe</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Icon file path</strong> section, select the ellipse button and select an icon to represent the app.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Common</strong> tab, select the check box next to <strong>Remove this item when it is no longer applied.</strong> Select <strong>OK</strong> at the warning message.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>OK</strong> to close the <strong>New Shortcut Properties</strong> box.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close the <strong>Group Policy Management Editor</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Double-click the <strong>Desktop Shortcut Policy</strong> and review the details for the group policy object. </p> <blockquote> <p>Take note that security filtering is configured to apply to all authenticated users by default.</p> </blockquote> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise, you will have successfully created Group Policy Objects.</p> <h2 id="exercise-2-assigning-and-validating-a-group-policy-object">Exercise 2: Assigning and Validating a Group Policy Object</h2> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>You have created two group policy objects. The <strong>Security Settings Policy</strong> GPO must be assigned to a new Organizational Unit named <strong>ResearchLab</strong>. LON-CL2 will then be moved to ResearchLab for you to test out the new policy assignment. The Desktop Shortcut Policy GPO must be assigned to members of the Marketing OU.</p> <p>You need to create the additional Active Directory objects and link the GPOs. You will then validate that the GPOs apply as required.</p> <h3 id="task-1-configure-the-security-settings-policy-gpo">Task 1: Configure the Security Settings Policy GPO</h3> <ol> <li> <p>In the <strong>Group Policy Management</strong> console, right-click <strong>Adatum.com</strong> and then select <strong>Active Directory Users and Computers</strong>. </p> </li> <li> <p>In <strong>Active Directory Users and Computers</strong>, right-click <strong>Adatum.com</strong>, point to <strong>New</strong>, and then select <strong>Organizational Unit</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>New Object - Organizational Unit</strong> box, under <strong>Name</strong>, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">ResearchLab</strong> and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select the <strong>Seattle Clients</strong> OU.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click <strong>LON-CL2</strong>, and then select <strong>Move</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Move box, select <strong>ResearchLab</strong>, and then select <strong>OK</strong>. </p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>ResearchLab</strong> and validate that LON-CL2 is now a member of the ResearchLab OU.</p> </li> <li> <p>Minimize <strong>Active Directory Users and Computers</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Maximize the Group Policy Management window. In the console tree, expand <strong>Forest:Adatum.com</strong>, expand <strong>Domains</strong>, and then expand <strong>Adatum.com</strong>. Select the <strong>Group Policy Objects</strong> node.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click the <strong>ResearchLab</strong> OU, and then select <strong>Link an existing GPO</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Security Settings Policy</strong> and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-configure-the-desktop-shortcut-policy-gpo">Task 2: Configure the Desktop Shortcut Policy GPO</h3> <ol> <li> <p>In the Group Policy Management console, right-click the <strong>Marketing</strong> OU, and then select <strong>Link an existing GPO</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Desktop Shortcut Policy</strong> and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close all open windows on LON-DC1.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-3-validate-the-group-policy-object-settings">Task 3: Validate the Group Policy Object settings</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Switch to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(3)&quot;).click()">LON-CL2</a></strong> and from the sign-in screen select the <strong>Power</strong> button and then select <strong>Restart</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>After LON-CL2 restarts, attempt to sign in. Notice the Warning message that displays.</p> </li> <li> <p>Switch to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> and sign in as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Alice</strong> with the password of <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the LON-CL1 desktop, take note of the shortcut to <strong>Write.exe</strong>. Alice is a member of the Marketing OU.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of LON-CL1 and then sign in as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Scott</strong> with the password of <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the LON-CL1 desktop, notice that there is no shortcut. Scott is a member of the Research OU which does not have the policy applied.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of LON-CL1.</p> </li> <li> <p>Switch to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(1)&quot;).click()">LON-DC1</a></strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Restore <strong>Active Directory Users and Computers</strong>. </p> </li> <li> <p>Select the <strong>ResearchLab</strong> OU.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click <strong>LON-CL2</strong>, and then select <strong>Move</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Move box, select <strong>Seattle Clients</strong>, and then select <strong>OK</strong>. </p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Seattle Clients</strong> and validate that LON-CL2 is now a member.</p> </li> <li> <p>Switch to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(3)&quot;).click()">LON-CL2</a></strong> and from the sign-in screen, select <strong>OK</strong> at the warning, select the <strong>Power</strong> button and then select <strong>Restart</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise, you will have successfully assigned and validated the Group Policy Object settings.</p> <h2 id="exercise-3-troubleshooting-group-policy">Exercise 3: Troubleshooting Group Policy</h2> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>Adatum Sales Managers have requested that a shortcut to a Contacts app be placed on the desktop of their workstations. An administrator has created a Group Policy Object that applies the setting. However, Paul Koch, who is one of the Sales Managers, reports that the shortcut does not display on his workstation named LON-CL1. You have been asked to troubleshoot the issue and ensure that the Contacts app shortcut appears for only members of the Sales Managers group.</p> <blockquote> <p>Note: You may want to try to address the issue on your own before completing the following tasks. The following tasks provide the steps and reveal the issues to be addressed and can be used as an answer key if needed. Hint: There are two issues you will need to fix.</p> </blockquote> <h3 id="task-1-verify-current-settings">Task 1: Verify current settings</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Paul</strong> with the password of <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>. Notice that there is no shortcut to the Contacts app.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong>, and then enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">cmd</strong>. Under <strong>Command Prompt</strong>, select <strong>Run as administrator</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the User Account Control, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Administrator</strong> with the password of <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the command prompt type the following command and press <strong>Enter</strong>:</p> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-attribute">gpresult</span> /R</code></pre> </li> <li> <p>Review the information to validate which GPOs were applied, which GPOs were filtered, and if there are any errors reported.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the command prompt type the following commands and press <strong>Enter</strong> after each command:</p> <pre> <code>gpresult /H GPReport<span class="hljs-selector-class">.html</span></code> </pre> <pre> <code>GPReport.html</code> </pre> </li> <li> <p>An HTML report displays. Review the information to validate which GPOs were applied, which GPOs were filtered, and if there are any errors reported. </p> </li> <li> <p>You will notice in both reports that the Contacts App Policy has not been applied to Paul. You will now use the Group Policy Management console to verify your findings.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close all open windows and sign out of LON-CL1.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-modify-group-policy-object-settings">Task 2: Modify Group Policy Object settings</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Switch to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(1)&quot;).click()">LON-DC1</a></strong> and select <strong>Start</strong>, and then select <strong>Server Manager</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Tools</strong> and then select <strong>Group Policy Management</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Maximize the Group Policy Management window. In the console tree, expand <strong>Forest:Adatum.com</strong>, expand <strong>Domains</strong>, and then expand <strong>Adatum.com</strong>. Select the <strong>Group Policy Objects</strong> node. Notice the <strong>Contacts App Policy</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Double-click the <strong>Contacts App Policy</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Review the Scope tab for two issues related to the policy setting. Can you identify the issues? </p> <blockquote> <p>Not only is the policy not linked to the Sales OU, but the security filtering is not configured correctly. Security Filtering must be applied to the Sales Managers group.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>In the details pane, under <strong>Security Filtering</strong>, select <strong>Add</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Select User, Computer, or Group</strong> box, under <strong>Enter the object name to select (examples)</strong> enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Sales Managers</strong>, click <strong>Check Names</strong> and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Group Policy Management console, right-click the <strong>Sales</strong> OU, and then select <strong>Link an existing GPO</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Contacts App Policy</strong> and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close all open windows on LON-DC1.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-3-validate-the-group-policy-object-settings">Task 3: Validate the Group Policy Object settings</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Switch to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> and sign in as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Paul</strong> with the password of <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the LON-CL1 desktop, take note of the shortcut to Contact Apps. </p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of LON-CL1 and then sign in as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Ben</strong> with the password of <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> <blockquote> <p>On the LON-CL1 desktop, notice that there is no shortcut. Ben is a member of the Sales OU, but is not a member of the Sales Managers group. The Sales Managers group is the only group that is filtered for the Contact Apps policy GPO.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of LON-CL1.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise, you will have successfully addressed the Sales Managers GPO issue.</p> <p><strong>END OF LAB</strong></p> </div> <div class="page" id="page8"> <h1 id="practice-lab-managing-local-and-network-printers">Practice Lab 08: Managing local and network printers</h1> <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2> <p>In this exercise, you will perform basic printer configuration. You will add a local printer by using Devices and Printers. You then will configure printer security, and use the Print Management tool to add a printer on a remote computer. You also will connect to a remote printer, and then manage a print job.</p> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>The Adatum Marketing department has purchased a new printer that uses a Microsoft PCL6 Class Driver that’s attached to LON-DC1. Marketing wants to share the printer but restrict use to just the Managers group. There is a another printer attached to LON-DC1 that uses the Microsoft PS Class Driver, which is also to be shared with access for everyone to print. You need to configure these printers as requested. After you configure the printers you will have a user named Terry test that she can only print to the printer on LON-DC1, and that print jobs initiated from LON-DC1 can be seen in the queue on LON-DC1.</p> <h3 id="task-1-add-and-share-a-local-printer">Task 1: Add and share a local printer</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(1)&quot;).click()">LON-DC1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong> and then select <strong>Control Panel</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In Control Panel, select <strong>View devices and printers</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In Devices and Printers, select <strong>Add a printer</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Add a device</strong> dialog box, select <strong>The printer that I want isn’t listed</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Find a printer by other options</strong> page, select the <strong>Add a local printer or network printer with manual settings</strong> option, and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Choose a printer port</strong> page, verify that <strong>Use an existing port</strong> is selected, and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Install the printer driver</strong> page, in the <strong>Manufacturer</strong> list, select <strong>Microsoft</strong>. In the <strong>Printers</strong> list, select <strong>Microsoft PCL6 Class Driver</strong>, and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Type a printer name</strong> page, in the <strong>Printer name</strong> field, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Managers Printer</strong>, and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Printer Sharing</strong> page, select <strong>Next</strong>, and then select <strong>Finish</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-configure-printer-security">Task 2: Configure printer security</h3> <ol> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(1)&quot;).click()">LON-DC1</a></strong>, in Devices and Printers, right-click <strong>Managers Printer</strong>, select <strong>Printer properties</strong>, and then select the <strong>Security</strong> tab.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Managers Printer Properties</strong> dialog box, verify that <strong>Everyone</strong> is selected, and then select <strong>Remove</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Add</strong>, in the <strong>Enter the object names to select (examples)</strong> box, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Managers</strong>, and then select <strong>OK</strong>. In the <strong>Permissions for Managers</strong> section, verify that <strong>Print</strong> check box is selected in the <strong>Allow</strong> column, and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close the Devices and Printers window.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-3-use-print-management-to-manage-a-remote-printer">Task 3: Use Print Management to manage a remote printer</h3> <ol> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(1)&quot;).click()">LON-DC1</a></strong>, select <strong>Start</strong> and then select <strong>Server Manager</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Manage</strong> and then select <strong>Add Roles and Features</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Before you begin page, select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Select installation type page, select <strong>Role-based or feature-based installation</strong>, and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Server Selection page, select <strong>LON-DC1.Adatum.com</strong> and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Server Roles page, select <strong>Print and Document Services</strong>, select <strong>Add Features</strong>, and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Features page, select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Print and Document Services page, select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Role Services page, select the check box next to <strong>Print Server</strong> and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Confirmation page, select <strong>Install</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Results page, select <strong>Close</strong> and then close Server Manager.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong>, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">print</strong>, and then select <strong>Print Management</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In Print Management, in the navigation pane, expand <strong>Print Servers</strong>, and then verify that LON-DC1 is listed.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click <strong>LON-DC1</strong>, and then select <strong>Add Printer</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Printer Installation</strong> page, select <strong>Add a new printer using an existing port</strong>, and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Printer Driver</strong> page, verify that the <strong>Install a new driver</strong> option is selected, and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Printer Installation</strong> page, in the <strong>Manufacturer</strong> list, select <strong>Microsoft</strong>. In the <strong>Printers</strong> list, select <strong>Microsoft PS Class Driver</strong>, and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Printer Name and Sharing Settings</strong> page, in the <strong>Printer Name</strong> box, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">PostScript Printer</strong>, then in the <strong>Share Name</strong> box, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">PostScript Printer</strong>, select <strong>Next</strong> twice, and then select <strong>Finish</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under the <strong>LON-DC1</strong> node, select <strong>Printers</strong> and verify that <strong>PostScript Printer</strong> is installed and ready.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-4-connect-to-a-remote-printer">Task 4: Connect to a remote printer</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Switch to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>, and sign in as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Terry</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> <p><em>Note: Terry is member of the IT group, but she is not a member of the Managers group.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong>, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">control</strong>, and then select <strong>Control Panel</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In Control Panel, select <strong>View devices and printers</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Add a printer</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Add a device</strong> dialog box, select <strong>The printer that I want isn’t listed</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Find a printer by other options</strong> page, select <strong>Select a shared printer by name</strong>, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">&bsol;&bsol;LON-DC1&bsol;Managers Printer</strong> in the box, and then select <strong>Next</strong>. </p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Connect to LON-DC1</strong> dialog box, select <strong>Cancel</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the box, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">&bsol;&bsol;LON-DC1&bsol;PostScript Printer</strong>, select <strong>Next</strong> twice, and then select <strong>Finish</strong>.</p> <p><em>Note: Because Terry is not a member of the Managers group, and she does not have permissions to &bsol;&bsol;LON-DC1&bsol;Managers Printer, you were asked to type credentials that have the appropriate permissions.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>In Devices and Printers, verify that <strong>PostScript Printer on LON-DC1</strong> was added.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click <strong>PostScript Printer on LON-DC1</strong>, and then select <strong>Set as default printer</strong>. In the <strong>Printers</strong> dialog box, select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Verify that the printer has a green check mark next to it, which indicates that it is the default printer.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-5-print-a-document-and-manage-a-print-job">Task 5: Print a document, and manage a print job</h3> <ol> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>, select <strong>Start</strong> and then select <strong>Notepad</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In Notepad, type your name, select the <strong>File</strong> menu, and then select <strong>Print</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Print</strong> dialog box, select <strong>PostScript Printer on LON-DC1</strong>, and then select <strong>Print</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Switch to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(1)&quot;).click()">LON-DC1</a></strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(1)&quot;).click()">LON-DC1</a></strong>, in Print Management, expand <strong>Custom Filters</strong> and then select <strong>Printers With Jobs</strong>. In the details pane, view that <strong>PostScript Printer</strong> is listed and that it has one job in the queue.</p> </li> <li> <p>Switch to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>, in the notification area, select <strong>Show hidden icons</strong>, right-click the printer icon, and then select <strong>PostScript Printer on LON-DC1</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>PostScript Printer on LON-DC1</strong> window, verify that you can see a single document called <strong>Untitled – Notepad</strong>. Right-click <strong>Untitled – Notepad</strong>, review its properties, and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click <strong>Untitled-Notepad</strong>, select <strong>Cancel</strong>, and then select <strong>Yes</strong>.</p> <p><em>Note: You now have canceled Terry&#39;s print job.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out from LON-CL1.</p> </li> <li> <p>Switch to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(1)&quot;).click()">LON-DC1</a></strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(1)&quot;).click()">LON-DC1</a></strong>, in Print Management, verify that there are no longer any printers listed under the <strong>Printers With Jobs</strong> node.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close all open windows.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of LON-DC1.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercises you will have performed basic printer configuration like adding and sharing a printer, configuring printer security, managing and connecting a remote printer and managing a print job.</p> <p><strong>END OF LAB</strong></p> </div> <div class="page" id="page9"> <h1 id="practice-lab-configuring-network-connectivity">Practice Lab 09: Configuring Network Connectivity</h1> <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2> <p>In this lab, you will identify IPv4 settings and validate connectivity on a Windows device. You will also configure a Windows device to automatically obtain IPv4 settings from a DHCP service.</p> <h2 id="exercise-1-verifying-and-testing-ipv4-settings">Exercise 1: Verifying and Testing IPv4 Settings</h2> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>You need to identify the current static IPv4 settings on LON-CL1. You also need to test connectivity from LON-CL1 to LON-DC1.</p> <h3 id="task-1-verify-ipv4-settings-from-settings-and-the-network-and-sharing-center">Task 1: Verify IPv4 settings from Settings and the Network and Sharing Center</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select the <strong>Start</strong> button, and then select <strong>Settings</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Settings</strong> window, select <strong>Network &amp; internet</strong> and then in the status area select <strong>Properties</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Identify the <strong>IP settings</strong> and <strong>Properties</strong> for the network adapter. The following information should be available:</p> <ul> <li>IP assignment</li> <li>IPv4 address</li> <li>IPv4 subnet prefix length</li> <li>IPv4 gateway</li> <li>IPv4 DNS servers</li> </ul> <p><em>Also take note that the IP assignment is set to Manual, which indicates that this is a static IP address assignment.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>Under <strong>IP settings</strong>, select <strong>Edit</strong>. Notice that you can modify the IPv4 and IPv6 settings.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Cancel</strong> to close the <strong>Edit IP settings</strong> window.</p> </li> <li> <p>Click <strong>Back</strong> to return to the <strong>Settings</strong> page, select <strong>Network &amp; internet</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Status details pane, under <strong>Advanced network settings</strong>, select <strong>Change adapter options</strong>. The Network Connections window opens.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Network Connections window, right-click <strong>Ethernet 3</strong> and then select <strong>Status</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Ethernet 3 Status</strong> dialog box, select <strong>Details</strong>. This window displays the same configuration information for this adapter as the Settings status page.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Network Connection Details</strong> window, select <strong>Close</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Ethernet 3 Status</strong> dialog box, select <strong>Properties</strong>. You can configure protocols in this window.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Internet Protocol Version 4 (TCP/IPv4)</strong>, and then select <strong>Properties</strong>.</p> <p><em>Note: You can configure the IP address, subnet mask, default gateway, and Domain Name System (DNS) servers in this window.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Cancel</strong> and then close all open windows without modifying any settings.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-verify-ipv4-settings-from-the-command-line">Task 2: Verify IPv4 settings from the command line</h3> <ol> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>, select <strong>Start</strong>, and then type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">PowerShell</strong>. Windows PowerShell displays in the search results.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under Windows PowerShell, select <strong>Run as administrator</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the Windows PowerShell command prompt, type following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-meta">Get</span>-NetIPAddress</code> </pre> <p><em>Note: The IPv4 address from the Ethernet interface should match what you identified earlier.</em></p> <ol> <li>At the Windows PowerShell command prompt, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</li> </ol> <pre> <code>netsh <span class="hljs-class"><span class="hljs-keyword">interface</span> <span class="hljs-title">ipv4</span> <span class="hljs-title">show</span> <span class="hljs-title">config</span></span></code> </pre> <p><em>Note: The current IPv4 configuration is displayed and should match what you identified earlier.</em></p> <ol> <li>At the Windows PowerShell command prompt, type the following command, and then press Enter.</li> </ol> <pre> <code>ipconfig /<span class="hljs-keyword">all</span></code> </pre> <p><em>Note: Again, the information should match what you identified earlier.</em></p> <ol> <li>Leave the <strong>Administrator: Windows PowerShell</strong> window open.</li> </ol> <h3 id="task-3-test-connectivity">Task 3: Test connectivity</h3> <ol> <li>At the Windows PowerShell command prompt, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-keyword">Test</span>-Connection LON-DC1</code> </pre> <ol> <li>At the Windows PowerShell command prompt, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-built_in">Ping</span> LON-DC1</code> </pre> <ol> <li>At the Windows PowerShell command prompt, type type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-attribute">PathPing</span> LON-DC1</code> </pre> <ol> <li> <p>Observe and describe the differences between the three connectivity tests performed.</p> <p><em>Note: Test-Connection and Ping provides information on time and success of connectivity directly to a target host. PathPing provides statistics on how many connections it takes to route to a target host.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>Close the Windows PowerShell window.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise you have verified the IPv4 settings of a windows device and used various tools to test connectivity.</p> <h2 id="exercise-2-configuring-automatic-ipv4-settings">Exercise 2: Configuring Automatic IPv4 Settings</h2> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>Your network administrative team has configured DNS and DHCP services located on LON-DC1. You need to reconfigure LON-CL1 to obtain its IPv4 settings using the DHCP service. You will then test and verify the connectivity between LON-CL1 and LON-DC1 using the newly obtained IPv4 address settings.</p> <h3 id="task-1-reconfigure-the-ipv4-settings">Task 1: Reconfigure the IPv4 settings</h3> <ol> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>, select the <strong>Start</strong> button, and then select <strong>Settings</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Settings</strong> window, select <strong>Network &amp; internet</strong> and then in the status area select <strong>Properties</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under <strong>IP settings</strong>, select <strong>Edit</strong>. Notice that you can modify the IPv4 and IPv6 settings.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under <strong>Edit IP settings</strong>, select the drop-down menu, select <strong>Automatic (DHCP)</strong>, and then select <strong>Save</strong>.</p> <blockquote> <p>Notice that the DNS server assignment also changes to Automatic (DHCP).</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>Click <strong>Back</strong> to return to the <strong>Settings</strong> page, select <strong>Network &amp; internet</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Status details pane, under <strong>Advanced network settings</strong>, select <strong>Change adapter options</strong>. The Network Connections window opens.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Network Connections window, right-click <strong>Ethernet 3</strong> and then select <strong>Status</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Ethernet 3 Status</strong> dialog box, select <strong>Details</strong>. Notice that DHCP is enabled, and that the IP address of the DHCP server displays.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close all open windows on LON-CL1.</p> </li> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>, select <strong>Start</strong>, and then type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">PowerShell</strong>. Windows PowerShell displays in the search results.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under Windows PowerShell, select <strong>Run as administrator</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the Windows PowerShell command prompt type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <pre> <code>ipconfig /<span class="hljs-keyword">all</span></code> </pre> <ol> <li>Verify that the IPv4 address is obtained from DHCP.</li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-test-connectivity">Task 2: Test connectivity</h3> <ol> <li>At the Windows PowerShell command prompt, type type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-keyword">Test</span>-Connection LON-DC1</code> </pre> <p><em>Note: You should receive four replies from LON-DC1.</em></p> <ol> <li>Close all open windows.</li> <li>Sign out of LON-CL1.</li> </ol> <h3 id="task-3-view-the-impact-on-the-dhcp-server">Task 3: View the impact on the DHCP server</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Switch to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(1)&quot;).click()">LON-DC1</a></strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(1)&quot;).click()">LON-DC1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong> and then select <strong>Server Manager</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In <strong>Server Manager</strong>, select <strong>All Servers</strong>, right-click <strong>LON-DC1</strong>, and then select <strong>DHCP Manager</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In <strong>DHCP</strong>, expand <strong>LON-DC1.Adatum.com</strong>, expand <strong>IPv4</strong>, expand <strong>Scope [172.16.0.0] Adatum</strong>, and then select <strong>Address Leases</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the details pane, you should see the address lease for the LON-CL1 Windows client.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close the DHCP window and then sign out of LON-DC1.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise you have configured a Windows device to automatically obtain IPv4 settings from a DHCP service.</p> <p><strong>END OF LAB</strong></p> </div> <div class="page" id="page10"> <h1 id="practice-lab-configuring-and-testing-name-resolution">Practice Lab 10: Configuring and Testing Name Resolution</h1> <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2> <p>In this lab, you will verify and manage name resolution for a Windows network client. You will also test name resolution by using command line tools, DNS, and a hosts file entry.</p> <h3 id="prerequisites">Prerequisites</h3> <p>The following lab(s) must be completed before this lab:</p> <ul> <li>0501-Configuring Network Connectivity - On LON-CL1, DHCP should be enabled for the Ethernet connection.</li> </ul> <h2 id="exercise-1-verify-and-manage-name-resolution">Exercise 1: Verify and Manage Name Resolution</h2> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>You need to check and verify current DNS settings on LON-CL1. You will also test out command line tools used to view and clear the DNS client cache.</p> <h3 id="task-1-verify-current-dns-settings">Task 1: Verify current DNS settings</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click <strong>Start</strong>, and then select <strong>Windows Terminal (Admin)</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the Windows PowerShell command prompt, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>. </p> </li> </ol> <pre> <code>ipconfig /<span class="hljs-keyword">all</span></code> </pre> <p><em>Note: DHCP should be enabled from the previous lab. Take note of the IP address of the DHCP server and the IP address of the DNS server.</em></p> <ol> <li>At the Windows PowerShell command prompt, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>. </li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-meta">Get</span>-NetIPConfiguration</code> </pre> <p><em>Note: The PowerShell command also provides IP address information.</em></p> <h3 id="task-2-view-and-clear-the-dns-resolver-cache">Task 2: View and clear the DNS resolver cache</h3> <ol> <li>At the Windows PowerShell command prompt, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>. This will resolve LON-DC1.adatum.com to an IP address and store the results in the DNS resolver cache.</li> </ol> <pre> <code>ping LON-DC1<span class="hljs-selector-class">.adatum</span><span class="hljs-selector-class">.com</span></code> </pre> <ol> <li>At the Windows PowerShell command prompt, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>. This will resolve LON-DC1.adatum.com to an IP address and store the results in the DNS resolver cache.</li> </ol> <pre> <code>Test-Connection LON-DC1<span class="hljs-selector-class">.adatum</span><span class="hljs-selector-class">.com</span></code> </pre> <ol> <li>At the Windows PowerShell command prompt, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>. This displays the current DNS resolver cache.</li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-built_in">ipconfig</span> /displaydns</code> </pre> <ol> <li>At the Windows PowerShell command prompt, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>. This displays the current DNS resolver cache using a PowerShell command.</li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-meta">Get</span>-DnsClientCache</code> </pre> <ol> <li>At the Windows PowerShell command prompt, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>. This flushes the current DNS resolver cache.</li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-built_in">ipconfig</span> /flushdns</code> </pre> <ol> <li>At the Windows PowerShell command prompt, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>. This flushes the current DNS resolver cache using a PowerShell command.</li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-attribute">Clear-DnsClientCache</span></code> </pre> <p><em>Note: It is not necessary to run this in addition to the preceding command.</em></p> <ol> <li>At the Windows PowerShell command prompt, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>. This verifies that you have no entries in the cache.</li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-built_in">ipconfig</span> /displaydns</code> </pre> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise you have verified current DNS settings on LON-CL1 and used command line tools to view and clear the DNS client cache.</p> <h2 id="exercise-2-testing-name-resolution">Exercise 2: Testing Name Resolution</h2> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>A user reports that LON-CL1 cannot connect to www.Adatum.com or intranet.Adatum.com. To address the issue, you decide to add www to the hosts file along with the LON-DC1.adatum.com IP address. You will also add an alias DNS record for intranet.Adatum.com that resolves to LON-CL2.adatum.com. Finally you will verify name resolution and connectivity.</p> <h3 id="task-1-create-and-test-a-hosts-file-entry">Task 1: Create and test a hosts file entry</h3> <ol> <li>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>, at the Windows PowerShell command prompt, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-built_in">ping</span> www</code> </pre> <ol> <li>At the Windows PowerShell command prompt, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-built_in">ping</span> intranet</code> </pre> <p><em>Note: Neither name is reachable because www and intranet cannot be resolved to a valid IP address.</em></p> <ol> <li>At the Windows PowerShell command prompt, type the following command, and then press Enter.</li> </ol> <pre> <code>notepad C:<span class="hljs-symbol">&bsol;w</span>indows<span class="hljs-symbol">&bsol;s</span>ystem32<span class="hljs-symbol">&bsol;d</span>rivers<span class="hljs-symbol">&bsol;e</span>tc<span class="hljs-symbol">&bsol;h</span>osts</code> </pre> <ol> <li>Scroll to the end of the file, type the following, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</li> </ol> <pre> <code>172<span class="hljs-selector-class">.16</span><span class="hljs-selector-class">.0</span><span class="hljs-selector-class">.10</span> <span class="hljs-selector-tag">www</span></code> </pre> <ol> <li> <p>Select <strong>File</strong>, and then select <strong>Save</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close Notepad.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the Windows PowerShell command prompt, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-keyword">Test</span>-Connection www</code> </pre> <ol> <li>At the Windows PowerShell command prompt, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-meta">Get</span>-DnsClientCache</code> </pre> <ol> <li> <p>View the www record in the cache.</p> </li> <li> <p>Leave PowerShell open.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-add-a-dns-record">Task 2: Add a DNS record</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(1)&quot;).click()">LON-DC1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong> and then select <strong>Server Manager</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In Server Manager, select <strong>All Servers</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click <strong>LON-DC1</strong>, and then select <strong>DNS Manager</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>LON-DC1.Adatum.com</strong>, expand the <strong>Forward Lookup Zones</strong> folder and select <strong>Adatum.com</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Action</strong> in the top menu, then select <strong>New Alias (CNAME)</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Alias Name</strong> field, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">intranet</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Fully Qualified domain name (FQDN) for target host:</strong> field, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">LON-CL2.Adatum.com</strong> and select <strong>OK.</strong></p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of LON-DC1.</p> </li> <li> <p>Switch to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the PowerShell window, type the following command, and press <strong>Enter</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <pre> <code>ping intranet<span class="hljs-selector-class">.Adatum</span><span class="hljs-selector-class">.com</span></code> </pre> <ol> <li> <p>Verify that intranet.Adatum.com is resolving to LON-CL2.adatum.com and IP Address 172.16.0.100.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of LON-CL1.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise you have added a hosts file entry, created a DNS record, and tested name resolution.</p> <p><strong>END OF LAB</strong></p> </div> <div class="page" id="page11"> <h1 id="practice-lab-troubleshooting-network-connectivity-issues">Practice Lab 11: Troubleshooting Network Connectivity Issues</h1> <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2> <p>In this lab, you will troubleshoot network connectivity and name resolution issues.</p> <h3 id="prerequisites">Prerequisites</h3> <p>The following lab(s) must be completed before this lab:</p> <ul> <li>0401-Configuring Network Connectivity - On LON-CL1, DHCP should be enabled for the Ethernet connection.</li> <li>0402 - Configuring and Testing Name Resolution - Create the intranet.adatum.com DNS alias record.</li> </ul> <h2 id="exercise-1-resolving-network-connectivity">Exercise 1: Resolving network connectivity</h2> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>A user named Paul has reported that after restarting LON-CL1, he is no longer able to connect to <strong>&bsol;&bsol;LON-DC1&bsol;Labfiles</strong>. You check with other users, and it seems that whenever anyone restarts their computer, connectivity to the network resource is affected. </p> <p>You need to investigate and resolve the issue.</p> <h3 id="task-1-simulate-the-issue">Task 1: Simulate the issue</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Open File Explorer and then browse to <strong>E:&bsol;Labfiles&bsol;Mod05</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Run the <strong>E:&bsol;Labfiles&bsol;Mod05&bsol;scenario1.vbs</strong> script.</p> </li> <li> <p>Wait for LON-CL1 to restart.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-resolve-the-issue">Task 2: Resolve the issue</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Attempt to resolve the issue by using your knowledge of the network services and the tools available for troubleshooting a network environment. If you are unable to resolve the problem, escalate it by asking your instructor for additional guidance. The following steps provide the troubleshooting steps and solution to the issue.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong>, and then type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">cmd</strong>. The Command prompt displays in the search results.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under Command Prompt, select <strong>Run as administrator</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the command prompt, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <pre> <code>ipconfig /<span class="hljs-keyword">all</span></code> </pre> <blockquote> <p>Notice that the IPv4 address has the prefix of 169.254.</p> </blockquote> <ol> <li>At the command prompt, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-built_in">ipconfig</span> /renew</code> </pre> <blockquote> <p>Note that the IP renewal is not successful.</p> </blockquote> <ol> <li> <p>Switch to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(1)&quot;).click()">LON-DC1</a></strong></p> </li> <li> <p>If necessary, select <strong>Start</strong> and then select <strong>Server Manager</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>All Servers</strong>, right-click <strong>LON-DC1</strong>, and then select <strong>DHCP Manager</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In DHCP Manager, select <strong>LON-DC1.Adatum.com</strong>.</p> <blockquote> <p>Notice that a message displays that the DHCP server cannot be located, and it seems the service is not running.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>Right-Click <strong>LON-DC1.Adatum.com</strong>, point to <strong>All Tasks</strong>, and then select <strong>Start</strong>. The DHCP service starts.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of LON-DC1.</p> </li> <li> <p>Switch to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the command prompt, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-built_in">ipconfig</span> /renew</code> </pre> <blockquote> <p>Notice that LON-CL1 can now renew the IPv4 address.</p> </blockquote> <ol> <li>Select <strong>File Explorer</strong> and then browse to <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">&bsol;&bsol;LON-DC1&bsol;Labfiles</strong>. You should now be able to access the network resource.</li> <li>Close File Explorer and sign out of LON-CL1.</li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise you have fixed network connectivity issues to a network resource.</p> <h2 id="exercise-2-resolving-network-name-resolution">Exercise 2: Resolving network name resolution</h2> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>Julia reports that she can no longer access <strong><a href="http://intranet.adatum.com">http://intranet.adatum.com</a></strong> or <strong>&bsol;&bsol;LON-DC1&bsol;Labfiles</strong> from LON-CL1. Other users in the department can successfully access the site. You need to investigate and resolve the issue. Note: The DNS server IP address is 172.16.0.10. The IP address for LON-DC1 is 172.16.0.11.</p> <h3 id="task-1-simulate-the-issue">Task 1: Simulate the issue</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Open File Explorer and then browse to <strong>E:&bsol;Labfiles&bsol;Mod05</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Run the <strong>E:&bsol;Labfiles&bsol;Mod05&bsol;scenario2.vbs</strong> script.</p> </li> <li> <p>Wait for LON-CL1 to restart.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-resolve-the-issue">Task 2: Resolve the issue</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Attempt to resolve the issue by using your knowledge of the network services and the tools available for troubleshooting a network environment. If you are unable to resolve the problem, escalate it by asking your instructor for additional guidance. The following steps provide the troubleshooting steps and solution to the issue.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong>, and then type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">PowerShell</strong>. The Windows PowerShell displays in the search results.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under Windows PowerShell, select <strong>Run as Administrator</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the prompt, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <pre> <code>ping intranet<span class="hljs-selector-class">.adatum</span><span class="hljs-selector-class">.com</span></code> </pre> <blockquote> <p>Notice that the request times out to confirm that connectivity to intranet.adatum.com has an issue.</p> </blockquote> <ol> <li>At the prompt, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</li> </ol> <pre> <code>test-connection LON-DC1<span class="hljs-selector-class">.adatum</span><span class="hljs-selector-class">.com</span></code> </pre> <blockquote> <p>Note that the command fails, which confirms that the connection to LON-DC1 has an issue.</p> </blockquote> <ol> <li>At the prompt, type the following commands, each followed by <strong>Enter</strong>.</li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-selector-tag">test-connection</span> 172<span class="hljs-selector-class">.16</span><span class="hljs-selector-class">.0</span><span class="hljs-selector-class">.10</span></code> </pre> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-selector-tag">ping</span> 172<span class="hljs-selector-class">.16</span><span class="hljs-selector-class">.0</span><span class="hljs-selector-class">.13</span></span></code> </pre> <blockquote> <p>Note that connectivity directly to the IP address of each resource is successful. You identify that the issue must be related to name resolution.</p> </blockquote> <ol> <li>At the prompt, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-meta">Get</span>-DnsClientCache</code> </pre> <blockquote> <p>Notice the records that are returned. Review the records related to intranet.adatum.com and LON-DC1. What do you notice about the IP address for both resources?</p> </blockquote> <ol> <li>At the prompt, type the following commands, each followed by <strong>Enter</strong>.</li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-keyword">Clear</span>-DnsClientCache</code> </pre> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-keyword">Get</span>-DnsClientCache</code> </pre> <blockquote> <p>Note that the DNS cache clears most records, however the intranet.adatum.com and the LON-DC1 records still remain with the incorrect IP addresses. What may be causing these records to maintain in the DNS client cache?</p> </blockquote> <ol> <li>At the prompt, type the following command and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</li> </ol> <pre> <code>notepad C:<span class="hljs-symbol">&bsol;w</span>indows<span class="hljs-symbol">&bsol;s</span>ystem32<span class="hljs-symbol">&bsol;d</span>rivers<span class="hljs-symbol">&bsol;e</span>tc<span class="hljs-symbol">&bsol;h</span>osts</code> </pre> <blockquote> <p>Note that incorrect entries are listed in the locals hosts file of LON-CL1.</p> </blockquote> <ol> <li> <p>Scroll to the end of the file, delete <strong>172.16.10.10 intranet.adatum.com</strong> and delete <strong>172.16.10.11 LON-DC1</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Save and close the file.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the prompt, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <pre> <code>ping intranet<span class="hljs-selector-class">.adatum</span><span class="hljs-selector-class">.com</span></code> </pre> <blockquote> <p>Notice that the request fails which confirms that connectivity to intranet.adatum.com still has an issue.</p> </blockquote> <ol> <li>At the prompt, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</li> </ol> <pre> <code>test-connection LON-DC1<span class="hljs-selector-class">.adatum</span><span class="hljs-selector-class">.com</span></code> </pre> <blockquote> <p>Note that the command fails, which confirms that the connection to LON-DC1 still has an issue.</p> </blockquote> <ol> <li>At the command prompt, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</li> </ol> <pre> <code>ipconfig /<span class="hljs-keyword">all</span></code> </pre> <blockquote> <p>Take note of the IP configuration for LON-CL1. What do you notice about the DNS Servers configuration? It should be 172.16.0.10.</p> </blockquote> <ol> <li>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>, select the <strong>Start</strong> button, and then select <strong>Settings</strong>.</li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Network &amp; internet</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In <strong>Network and internet</strong>, select <strong>Ethernet</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Next to <strong>IPv4 address</strong>, select <strong>Edit</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under <strong>Edit IP settings</strong>, select the drop-down menu, select <strong>Automatic (DHCP)</strong>, and then select <strong>Save</strong>.</p> <blockquote> <p>Notice that the DNS server assignment also changes to Automatic (DHCP).</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>Switch to the PowerShell window.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the Windows PowerShell command prompt type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <pre> <code>ipconfig /<span class="hljs-keyword">all</span></code> </pre> <blockquote> <p>Notice that the IP address for the DNS server is now correctly configured to 172.16.0.10. The DHCP server is configured to provide this information automatically. </p> </blockquote> <ol> <li>At the prompt, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</li> </ol> <pre> <code>ping intranet<span class="hljs-selector-class">.adatum</span><span class="hljs-selector-class">.com</span></code> </pre> <blockquote> <p>Notice that the ping request is now successful with four replies from the server.</p> </blockquote> <ol> <li>At the prompt, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</li> </ol> <pre> <code>test-connection LON-DC1<span class="hljs-selector-class">.adatum</span><span class="hljs-selector-class">.com</span></code> </pre> <blockquote> <p>Note that the command connects to LON-DC1 successfully.</p> </blockquote> <ol> <li>Close all open windows and sign out of LON-CL1.</li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise you have fixed network connectivity issues to a network resource.</p> <p><strong>END OF LAB</strong></p> </div> <div class="page" id="page12"> <h1 id="practice-lab-administering-windows-client-using-remote-management">Practice Lab 12: Administering Windows Client Using Remote Management</h1> <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2> <p>In this lab you perform remote Windows administration using Remote PowerShell, Remote Desktop, and Windows Admin Center.</p> <h2 id="exercise-1-administering-windows-using-remote-powershell-and-remote-desktop">Exercise 1: Administering Windows using Remote PowerShell and Remote Desktop</h2> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>Adatum is planning to open a new branch office. To manage the devices in the new branch office you need to use Remote PowerShell and Remote Desktop. You need to test remote administration by running remote PowerShell commands on LON-DC1 and you need to enable Remote Desktop on LON-CL1.</p> <h3 id="task-1-perform-remote-management-using-windows-powershell">Task 1: Perform remote management using Windows PowerShell</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password: <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong>, and then type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">PowerShell</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under the Windows PowerShell app, select <strong>Run as Administrator</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>To view all of the services that are stopped on LON-DC1, in the Windows PowerShell window, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>:</p> </li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-built_in">Get-Service</span> -ComputerName LON-DC1 | <span class="hljs-built_in">Where-Object</span> {<span class="hljs-variable">$_</span>.Status <span class="hljs-nomarkup">-eq</span> <span class="hljs-string">"Stopped"</span>}</code> </pre> <ol> <li>To view the the content of the C:&bsol;Program Files folder on LON-DC1, in the Windows PowerShell window, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>:</li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-built_in">Invoke-Command</span> -ComputerName LON-DC1 -ScriptBlock {<span class="hljs-built_in">Get-ChildItem</span> <span class="hljs-string">"C:&bsol;Program Files"</span>}</code> </pre> <ol> <li>To view the the System event log on LON-DC1, in the Windows PowerShell window, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>:</li> </ol> <pre> <code>Invoke-Command –ComputerName LON-DC1 –ScriptBlock {Get-EventLog –<span class="hljs-built-in">log</span> <span class="hljs-keyword">system</span>}</code> </pre> <ol> <li>To determine if the WinRM service is running on LON-DC1, in the Windows PowerShell window, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>:</li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-keyword">Test</span>-WsMan LON-DC1</code> </pre> <p><em>Note: The output on LON-DC1 validates that the WinRM service is running and it is ready to receive WS-Management requests. If it was not configured, you would have needed to run <strong>Winrm quickconfig</strong> on LON-DC1.</em></p> <ol> <li>In the Windows PowerShell window, type the following commands, and then press <strong>Enter</strong> after each one:</li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-built_in">Enter-PSSession</span> LON-DC1</code> </pre> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-built_in">Get-command</span></code> </pre> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-built_in">Add-Content</span> Remote.txt <span class="hljs-string">"Adding text to file on LON-DC1"</span></code> </pre> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-built_in">Exit-PSSession</span></code> </pre> <h3 id="task-2-enable-remote-desktop">Task 2: Enable Remote Desktop</h3> <ol> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>, select <strong>Start</strong>, and then select the <strong>Settings</strong> icon.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Settings</strong> page, select <strong>System</strong>, and then select <strong>Remote Desktop</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under <strong>Enable Remote Desktop</strong> select the switch to <strong>On</strong> and then in the Remote Desktop Settings window select <strong>Confirm</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Remote Desktop page, select <strong>Advanced settings</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Verify that <strong>Require computers to use Network Level Authentication to connect</strong> is selected. Also take note of the Current Remote Desktop Port, which is set to <strong>3389</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Click <strong>Back</strong> to return to the <strong>Remote Desktop</strong> page, under User accounts click <strong>Select users that can remotely access this PC</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Remote Desktop Users page, select <strong>Add</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Select Users or Groups box under <strong>Enter the object names to select (examples)</strong> enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Jon Cantrell</strong> and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>OK</strong> to close the Remote Desktop Users dialog box.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click the <strong>Start</strong> button and then select <strong>Computer Management</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Expand <strong>Local Users and Groups</strong> and then select <strong>Groups</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Double-click the <strong>Remote Desktop Users</strong> group.</p> <blockquote> <p>Notice that Adatum&bsol;Jon is a member of the Remote Desktop Users group as configured from the Settings app. Members of this group are granted rights to sign in remotely.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>Close all open Windows on LON-CL1 and sign out.</p> </li> <li> <p>Switch to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(3)&quot;).click()">LON-CL2</a></strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(3)&quot;).click()">LON-CL2</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Jon</strong> with the password of <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Start menu, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Remote Desktop Connection</strong> and then select Open.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Remote Desktop Connection app, select <strong>Show Options</strong> to expand additional settings.</p> </li> <li> <p>in the logon settings section enter the following information and then select <strong>Connect</strong>:</p> <ul> <li>Computer: <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">LON-CL1</strong></li> <li>User name: <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Jon</strong></li> </ul> </li> <li> <p>At the Windows Security prompt, enter the password of <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong> and then select <strong>OK</strong>. </p> <blockquote> <p>Jon signs into LON-CL1 in full screen mode.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>In the LON-CL1 remote desktop window, select <strong>Start</strong>, select the <strong>Power</strong> button, and then select <strong>Disconnect</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of LON-CL2.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise, you will have enabled and tested remote PowerShell and Remote Desktop.</p> <h2 id="exercise-2-administering-windows-using-windows-admin-center">Exercise 2: Administering Windows using Windows Admin Center</h2> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>You need to test remote administration capabilities of the Windows Admin Center. For this scenario, you install Windows Admin Center on LON-CL1 and then perform remote administration tasks on LON-DC1.</p> <h3 id="task-1-install-windows-admin-center">Task 1: Install Windows Admin Center</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password: <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the taskbar, select <strong>File Explorer</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In File Explorer, browse to <strong>E:&bsol;Labfiles&bsol;Tools</strong>, and then double-click <strong>WindowsAdminCenter2110.msi</strong>. Windows Installer begins the installation process.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Windows Admin Center Setup</strong> license page, select the check box next to <strong>I accept these terms</strong>, and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Send diagnostic data to Microsoft</strong> page, select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>I don&#39;t want to use Microsoft Update</strong>, and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Install Windows Admin Center on Windows 10</strong> page, select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Installing Windows Admin Center</strong> page, configure the following and then select <strong>Install</strong>:</p> <ul> <li>Select a port for the Windows Admin Center site: <strong>6516</strong></li> <li>Allow Windows Admin Center to modify this machine&#39;s trusted hosts settings: <strong>Selected</strong></li> <li>Create a desktop shortcut to launch Windows Admin Center: <strong>Selected</strong>.</li> <li>Automatically update Windows Admin Center: <strong>Not selected</strong></li> </ul> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>One more thing</strong> page, take note of the message and then select <strong>Finish</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close File Explorer.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-add-connections-to-windows-admin-center">Task 2: Add connections to Windows Admin Center</h3> <ol> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>, on the desktop, double-click the <strong>Windows Admin Center</strong> icon.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Select a certificate for authentication</strong> window, select the <strong>Windows Admin Center Client</strong> certificate, and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close the <strong>Read what&#39;s new</strong> page.</p> <blockquote> <p>Note that you receive notifications on extensions being updated. When the extension update is complete, select <strong>OK</strong> at the <strong>Successfully updated your extensions</strong> message.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>All connections</strong> page, select <strong>Add</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Add or create resources</strong> page, in the <strong>Servers</strong> pane, select <strong>Add</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Add one</strong> tab, under <strong>Server name</strong>, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">LON-DC1</strong>. Windows Admin Center queries Active Directory and then displays the server.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Add</strong> to add LON-DC1.Adatum.com to the All connections page.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-3-perform-remote-administration-using-windows-admin-center">Task 3: Perform Remote Administration using Windows Admin Center</h3> <ol> <li> <p>In the <strong>Windows Admin Center</strong>, select <strong>LON-DC1.Adatum.com</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Overview</strong> page, take note of the server information and performance statistics.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Tools</strong> pane, select <strong>Events</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Events</strong> pane, take note of the event logs that are available from LON-DC1 and then under <strong>Windows Logs</strong> select <strong>System</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Review the System log events and then select the <strong>Clear</strong> button.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Clear</strong> prompt, select <strong>Clear log</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Tools</strong> pane, select <strong>Files &amp; file sharing</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the details pane, on the <strong>Files</strong> tab, take note of the file structure from LON-DC1.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the details pane, select the <strong>File shares</strong> tab. Take note of the current shared folders.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Tools</strong> pane, select <strong>Local users &amp; groups</strong>. Take note of the Users and Groups tabs where you can manage local users and groups on LON-DC1.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Tools</strong> pane, select <strong>PowerShell</strong>. A remote PowerShell session is established to LON-DC1.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the PowerShell pane, type <code>Get-Service</code> and then press <strong>Enter</strong>. LON-DC1 services are displayed.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Tools</strong> pane, select <strong>Remote Desktop</strong>. On the <strong>Navigating away closes PowerShell</strong> box, select <strong>Continue</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Remote Desktop</strong> page, read the message and then select <strong>Go to settings</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Settings</strong> page, select <strong>Remote Desktop</strong> and then under <strong>Remote Desktop</strong> select <strong>Allow remote connections to this computer</strong>. Select <strong>Save</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Tools</strong> pane, select <strong>Remote Desktop</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Navigating away closes PowerShell</strong> message, select <strong>Continue</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Welcome to Remote Desktop</strong> page, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> as the Username with the Password of <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>. </p> </li> <li> <p>Select the check box next to <strong>Automatically connect with the certificate presented by this machine</strong>, select <strong>Confirm</strong>, and then select <strong>Connect</strong>. The LON-DC1 desktop displays in the Remote Desktop pane.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Disconnect</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Tools</strong> pane, select <strong>Roles &amp; features</strong>. Notice that you can remotely install or uninstall server roles and features on LON-DC1.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close Windows Admin center and then sign out of LON-CL1.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise, you will have installed Windows Admin Center on LON-CL1 and then performed remote administration tasks on LON-DC1.</p> <p><strong>END OF LAB</strong></p> </div> <div class="page" id="page13"> <h1 id="practice-lab-managing-storage">Practice Lab 13: Managing Storage</h1> <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2> <p>In this lab you will manage local disk storage using Disk Management and PowerShell.</p> <h2 id="exercise-1-creating-and-managing-a-simple-volume">Exercise 1: Creating and Managing a Simple Volume</h2> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>Create two new partitions to store data.</p> <h3 id="task-1-create-a-simple-volume-using-disk-management">Task 1: Create a simple volume using Disk Management</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Right-click the <strong>Unallocated space</strong> on Disk 0, and then select <strong>New Simple Volume</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the New Simple Volume Wizard window, select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Specify Volume Size page, next to Simple volume size in MB, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">5120</strong>, and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Assign Drive Letter or Path</strong> page, make sure that <strong>Assign the following drive letter: F</strong> is selected, and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Format partition</strong> page, in the Volume Label text box, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Data</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Ensure that the check box is selected next to <strong>Perform a quick format</strong>, and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Completing the New Simple Volume Wizard</strong> page, select <strong>Finish</strong>. </p> <p><em>Note: If prompted to format drive E:, select Cancel.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>From the taskbar, select <strong>File Explorer</strong>. Verify that you have a new <strong>E drive</strong> named Data.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close the <strong>File Explorer</strong> window.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-create-a-simple-volume-using-powershell">Task 2: Create a simple volume using PowerShell</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Right-click Start and then select <strong>Windows Terminal (Admin)</strong>. Select <strong>Yes</strong> at the User Account Control message.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the prompt, type the following and then press Enter:</p> </li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-keyword">New</span>-Partition -DiskNumber <span class="hljs-number">0</span> -<span class="hljs-keyword">Size</span> <span class="hljs-number">5</span>gb -AssignDriveLetter</code> </pre> <ol> <li> <p>Open <strong>File Explorer</strong> and verify that you have a new G drive named Local Disk.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select the <strong>G drive</strong>. A message is displayed that asks if you want to format the drive.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the Microsoft Windows prompt, select <strong>Format disk</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Format Local Disk (G:) dialog box, select <strong>Start</strong> and then <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>OK</strong> to close the Format Complete message.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Format Local Disk (G:) dialog box, select <strong>Close</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close the <strong>File Explorer</strong> window. </p> </li> <li> <p>Switch to Disk Management and verify that Drive G shows 5GB in size.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-3-extend-a-simple-volume">Task 3: Extend a simple volume</h3> <ol> <li> <p>In Disk Management, right-click <strong>(G:)</strong>, and then select <strong>Extend Volume</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Extend Volume Wizard</strong> window, select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Select Disks</strong> page, next to <strong>Select the amount of space in MB</strong>, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">8192</strong>, and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Completing the Extend Volume Wizard</strong> page, select <strong>Finish</strong>. Notice that Drive G is now 13 GB in size.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-4-shrink-a-simple-volume">Task 4: Shrink a simple volume</h3> <ol> <li> <p>In Disk Management, right-click <strong>(G:)</strong>, and then select <strong>Shrink Volume</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Shrink G: page, next to <strong>Enter the amount of space to shrink in MB</strong>, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">2048</strong>, and then select <strong>Shrink</strong>. Notice that Drive G is now 11 GB in size.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close all open windows and sign out of LON-CL1.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results:</strong> After completing this exercise, you will have managed local disk storage using Disk Management and PowerShell.</p> <p><strong>END OF LAB</strong></p> </div> <div class="page" id="page14"> <h1 id="practice-lab-configuring-and-managing-local-and-share-permissions">Practice Lab 14: Configuring and Managing Local and Share Permissions</h1> <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2> <p>In this lab you create folders and manage local and share permissions.</p> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>You need to create file shares for the Marketing and IT department to enable users to store their shared files. You have to ensure that only people from the specific departments have access to the files. You decide to create both shares on LON-CL1 in the C:&bsol;Data folder. The IT department requires that the share and local folder is only accessible to members of the IT group. You advise Bruce Keever and Briana Hernandez to test the file shares and local access to the files.</p> <h3 id="task-1-create-a-folder-structure">Task 1: Create a folder structure</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select the <strong>File Explorer</strong> icon on the taskbar.</p> </li> <li> <p>In File Explorer, in the navigation pane, expand <strong>This PC</strong>, and then select <strong>Local Disk (C:)</strong>. In the details pane, right-click the <strong>empty space</strong>, select <strong>New</strong>, select <strong>Folder</strong>, and then type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Data</strong> for the new folder’s name.</p> </li> <li> <p>In File Explorer, in the navigation pane, expand <strong>Local Disk (C:),</strong> and select <strong>Data</strong>. In the details pane, right-click the empty space, select <strong>New</strong>, select <strong>Folder</strong>, and then type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Marketing</strong> for the new folder’s name. </p> </li> <li> <p>In File Explorer, in the details pane, right-click the <strong>empty space</strong>, select <strong>New</strong>, select <strong>Folder</strong>, and then type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">IT</strong> for the new folder’s name.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-review-default-permissions">Task 2: Review default permissions</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Right-click the <strong>IT</strong> folder, and then select <strong>Properties</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>IT Properties</strong> window, select the <strong>Security</strong> tab, and then select <strong>Edit</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Permissions for IT</strong> dialog box, verify that <strong>Authenticated Users</strong> is selected in the Group or user names section, and then select <strong>Remove</strong>. </p> </li> <li> <p>Read the text in the <strong>Windows Security</strong> dialog box that appears, which explains why you cannot remove Authenticated Users. select <strong>OK</strong>, and then select <strong>Cancel</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>IT Properties</strong> window, on the Security tab, select <strong>Advanced</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Advanced Security Settings for IT</strong> dialog box, verify that all permissions entries are inherited from C:&bsol;. Also, verify that Users (LON-CL1&bsol;Users) have Read &amp; execute access, while Authenticated Users have Modify access. Select <strong>OK</strong> twice.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-3-configure-permissions-for-the-it-and-marketing-folders">Task 3: Configure permissions for the IT and Marketing folders</h3> <ol> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>, in File Explorer, right-click the <strong>IT</strong> folder.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Give access to</strong>, and then select <strong>Specific people</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Type a name and then select Add, or click the arrow to find someone</strong> text box, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">IT</strong>, and then select <strong>Add</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Verify that IT is added and selected. In the Permission Level column, select <strong>Read/Write</strong>, select <strong>Share</strong>, and then select <strong>Done</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click <strong>Marketing</strong>, and then select <strong>Properties</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Marketing Properties</strong> dialog box, select the <strong>Sharing</strong> tab. In the <strong>Network File and Folder Sharing</strong> section, verify that <strong>Marketing</strong> is not shared.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Advanced Sharing</strong> section, Select <strong>Advanced Sharing</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Advanced Sharing dialog box, select the <strong>Share this folder</strong> check box. Verify that the share name is <strong>Marketing</strong> (the same as the folder name), and that Limit the number of simultaneous users to is set to 20.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Permissions</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Permissions for Marketing</strong> dialog box, select the <strong>Everyone</strong> group and select <strong>Remove</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Add</strong>, in the Enter the object names to select (examples) box, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Marketing</strong>, and then select <strong>OK</strong>. </p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Permissions for Marketing</strong> section, select the <strong>Change</strong> check box in the Allow column, and then select <strong>OK</strong> twice.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Marketing Properties</strong> dialog box, in the Network File and Folder Sharing section, verify that Marketing is now shared as &bsol;&bsol;LON-CL1&bsol;Marketing, and then select <strong>Close</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong>, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">cmd</strong> and then select <strong>Command Prompt</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the command prompt, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-keyword">net</span> <span class="hljs-keyword">view</span> &bsol;&bsol;LON-CL1</code> </pre> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: This will show you all shares created on LON-CL1</em></p> <ol> <li> <p>Close the command prompt.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click <strong>Start</strong>, and then select <strong>Computer Management</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In Computer Management, in the navigation pane, expand <strong>Shared Folders</strong>, and then select <strong>Shares</strong>. In the details pane, verify that you see IT and Marketing shares, and the default Windows administrative shares.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close Computer Management.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-4-review-configured-permissions">Task 4: Review configured permissions</h3> <ol> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>, in File Explorer, right-click <strong>IT</strong>, and then select <strong>Properties</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the IT Properties window, select the <strong>Security</strong> tab, and then select <strong>Advanced</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Advanced Security Settings for IT dialog box, verify that all the permissions entries are set explicitly at this level, because their permission inheritance is set to None.</p> </li> <li> <p>Verify that only the Administrator, Administrators (LON-CL1&bsol;Administrators) group, SYSTEM and IT (Adatum&bsol;IT) group have access to the IT folder. These settings match the permissions that you configured in the File Sharing dialog box.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Advanced Security Settings for IT dialog box, select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the IT Properties dialog box, select the <strong>Sharing</strong> tab, in the Network File and Folder Sharing section, verify that IT now is shared as &bsol;&bsol;LON-CL1&bsol;it, and then select <strong>Advanced Sharing</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Advanced Sharing dialog box, select <strong>Permissions</strong>. In the Permissions for IT dialog box, verify that the Everyone and Administrators groups have Full Control permissions to the share, select <strong>OK</strong> twice, and then select <strong>Close</strong>.</p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: If you share a folder by using the File Sharing dialog box, you will modify the local file permissions to match your configuration, while the Everyone and Administrators groups will have the Full Control share permission.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>In File Explorer, right-click <strong>Marketing</strong>, and then select <strong>Properties</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Marketing Properties window, select the <strong>Security tab</strong>, and then select <strong>Advanced</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Advanced Security Settings for Marketing dialog box, verify that all of the permissions entries are inherited from C:&bsol;. Also verify that Users (LON-CL1&bsol;Users) have Read &amp; execute access, while Authenticated Users have Modify access, which are the same file permissions as before you shared the Marketing folder. Select <strong>OK</strong> twice.</p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: If you share a folder by using the Advanced Sharing feature, this does not modify local file permissions. You only modify share permissions if you use Advanced Sharing.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of <strong>LON-CL1</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-5-test-local-file-permissions">Task 5: Test local file permissions</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Bruce</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: Bruce is a member of the Marketing group, but is not a member of the IT group.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>Select the <strong>File Explorer</strong> icon on the taskbar.</p> </li> <li> <p>In File Explorer, in the navigation pane, expand <strong>This PC</strong>, expand <strong>Local Disk (C:)</strong>, expand <strong>Data</strong>, and then select <strong>Marketing</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the details pane, right-click the empty space, select <strong>New</strong>, select <strong>Text Document</strong>, and then type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">File10</strong> as the name of the file.</p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: Bruce has local file permissions to create a new file in the Marketing folder, because permissions were configured by using the Advanced Sharing feature. This modified only the share permissions, while the default local file permissions were not modified. By default, Authenticated Users have the Modify permission.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>In File Explorer, in the navigation pane, select <strong>IT</strong>, and then select <strong>Cancel</strong>.</p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: You will get an error, because Bruce does not have local file permissions to the IT folder. Permissions were configured by File Sharing,and only members of the IT group have local file permissions to the folder.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of <strong>LON-CL1</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Briana</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: Briana is member of the IT group, and she is not member of the Marketing group.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>Select the <strong>File Explorer</strong> icon on the taskbar.</p> </li> <li> <p>In File Explorer, in the navigation pane, expand <strong>This PC</strong>, expand <strong>Local Disk (C:)</strong>, expand <strong>Data</strong>, and then select <strong>Marketing</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the details pane, verify that you can see File10 that was created by Bruce.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click the empty space, select <strong>New</strong>, select <strong>Text Document</strong>, and then type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">File20</strong> as the name of the file.</p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: Briana has local file permissions to create a new file in the Marketing folder because you configured permissions by using the Advanced Sharing feature. This modified only the share permissions, while the default local file permissions were not modified. By default, Authenticated Users have the Modify permission.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>In File Explorer, in the navigation pane, select <strong>IT</strong>. In the details pane, right-click the empty space, select <strong>New</strong>, select <strong>Text Document</strong>, and then type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">File21</strong> as the name of the file.</p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: Briana is able to create a file, because you configured permissions by using File Sharing. Members of the IT group have local file permissions to the IT folder.</em></p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: Be aware that Network File and Folder Sharing modifies file permissions and share permissions. However, the Advanced Sharing feature does not modify file permissions, and only sets share permissions.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of <strong>LON-CL1</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-6-test-share-permissions">Task 6: Test share permissions</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Switch to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(3)&quot;).click()">LON-CL2</a></strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(3)&quot;).click()">LON-CL2</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Bruce</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: Bruce is a member of the Marketing group, but he is not a member of the IT group.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>Select the <strong>File Explorer</strong> icon on the taskbar.</p> </li> <li> <p>In File Explorer, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">&bsol;&bsol;LON-CL1</strong> in the Address bar, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Verify that you can see the IT and Marketing shares in the details pane.</p> </li> <li> <p>Double-click <strong>Marketing</strong>. Verify that you can see the files that Bruce and Briana created locally.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the details pane, right-click the empty space, select <strong>New</strong>, select <strong>Text Document</strong>, and then type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">File30</strong> as the name of the file. Bruce has permissions to create a new file in the Marketing share because he is a member of the Marketing group.</p> </li> <li> <p>In File Explorer, select <strong>LON-CL1</strong> in the address bar. In the details pane, double-click <strong>IT</strong>. Read the text in the Network Error dialog box, and then select <strong>Close</strong>.</p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: Bruce is not a member of the IT group, so he does not have permissions to the IT share.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of <strong>LON-CL2</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(3)&quot;).click()">LON-CL2</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Briana</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: Briana is a member of the IT group, but she is not a member of the Marketing group.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>Select the <strong>File Explorer</strong> icon on the taskbar.</p> </li> <li> <p>In File Explorer, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">&bsol;&bsol;LON-CL1</strong> in the Address bar, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Verify that you can see the IT and Marketing shares in the details pane.</p> </li> <li> <p>Double-click <strong>Marketing</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Read the text in the Network Error dialog box.</p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: Briana is not a member of the Marketing group, so she does not have permissions to the Marketing share.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Close</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the details pane, double-click <strong>IT</strong>. Right-click the empty space in the details pane, select <strong>New</strong>, select <strong>Text Document</strong>, and then type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">File40</strong> as the name of the file.</p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: Briana has permissions to create a new file in the IT share because she is a member of the IT group. Users can connect only to shares that were shared for groups in which they are members, regardless of whether they were shared by File Sharing or Advanced Sharing.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of <strong>LON-CL2</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise, you will have created a folder structure for the Marketing and IT departments, shared their folders, and tested local and share permissions.</p> <p><strong>END OF LAB</strong></p> </div> <div class="page" id="page15"> <h1 id="practice-lab-using-conditions-to-control-access-and-effective-permissions">Practice Lab 15: Using Conditions to Control Access and Effective Permissions</h1> <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2> <p>In this lab you will learn how to use conditions to dynamically control access to files based on specific criteria.</p> <h3 id="prerequisites">Prerequisites</h3> <p>The following lab(s) must be completed before this lab:</p> <ul> <li>0601-Configuring and Managing Local and Share Permissions</li> </ul> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>Members of the IT, Marketing, and Research departments all require access to file shares located on LON-CL1, but require different permissions for the data they use. You&#39;ve been instructed to create a new shared folder in E:&bsol;Data named Research. The Research shared folder should only be accessible by users in the Research Department. The IT shared folder should only by accessible by employees located in the United States who are members of the IT Department. The Active Directory administrator has already configured Dynamic Access Control to allow for you to assign Department and Country based Claim Types to permissions on shared folders.</p> <h3 id="task-1-configure-conditions-to-control-access">Task 1: Configure conditions to control access</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select the <strong>File Explorer</strong> icon on the taskbar.</p> </li> <li> <p>In File Explorer, in the navigation pane, expand <strong>Local Disk (C:)</strong>, and then select <strong>Data</strong>. In the details pane, right-click the empty space, select <strong>New</strong>, select <strong>Folder</strong>, and type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Research</strong> as the new folder name.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click <strong>Research</strong>, select <strong>Properties</strong>, select the <strong>Sharing</strong> tab, and then select <strong>Advanced Sharing</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Advanced Sharing dialog box, select the <strong>Share this folder</strong> check box, and then select <strong>Permissions</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Permissions for Research</strong> dialog box, in the <strong>Permissions for Everyone</strong> section, select the <strong>Change</strong> check box in the Allow column, and then select <strong>OK</strong> twice.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Research Properties dialog box, select the <strong>Security</strong> tab, select <strong>Advanced</strong>, and then verify that all permissions entries are inherited from C:&bsol;.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Advanced Security Settings for Research dialog box, select <strong>Users (LON-CL1&bsol;Users)</strong>, and then select <strong>Remove</strong>. Read the text in the Windows Security dialog box that appears, select <strong>OK</strong></p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Disable inheritance</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Block Inheritance dialog box, select <strong>Convert inherited permissions into explicit permissions on this object</strong>, and then verify that all permissions entries are set explicitly at this level because their permission inheritance is set to <strong>None</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Advanced Security Settings for Research dialog box, select <strong>Users (LON-CL1&bsol;Users)</strong>, and then select <strong>Remove</strong>.</p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: The entry for Users is now removed from the Permission entries because it was explicitly set at this level.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>Verify that <strong>Authenticated Users</strong> is selected, and then select <strong>Edit</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Permission Entry for Research dialog box, select <strong>Add a condition</strong>, and compose the following expression: <strong>User Department Equals Value Research</strong>. You will need to type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">research</strong> manually in the last box. Select <strong>OK</strong> twice, then select <strong>Close</strong>.</p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: A claim type for the department attribute was preconfigured for the purpose of this lab.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>In File Explorer, in the navigation pane, select <strong>Data</strong>, right-click <strong>IT</strong>, select <strong>Properties</strong>, select the <strong>Security</strong> tab, and then select <strong>Advanced</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Advanced Security Settings for IT dialog box, select <strong>IT (Adatum&bsol;it)</strong>, and then select <strong>Edit</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Permission Entry for IT dialog box, select <strong>Add a condition</strong>, and compose the following expression: <strong>User Country Equals Value US</strong>. You will need to type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">US</strong> manually in the last field. select <strong>OK</strong> three times.</p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: A claim type for the c (country) attribute was preconfigured for the purpose of this lab.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of LON-CL1.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-test-conditions-to-control-access">Task 2: Test conditions to control access</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Briana</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select the <strong>File Explorer</strong> icon on the taskbar.</p> </li> <li> <p>In File Explorer, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">&bsol;&bsol;LON-CL1</strong> in the Address bar, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the details pane, double-click <strong>Research</strong>. Read the text in the Network Error dialog box, and then select <strong>Close</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong>, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">cmd</strong> and then select <strong>Command Prompt</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the command prompt, type the command, <code>whoami /claims</code> and then press <strong>Enter</strong>. Review the output, and then <strong>close</strong> the command prompt.</p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: This will show the current claims for the user. Briana has a department claim value of IT and so she cannot connect to the Research share.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>In the details pane, double-click <strong>IT</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the details pane, right-click the empty space, select <strong>New</strong>, select <strong>Text Document</strong>, and then type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">File50</strong> as the name of the file.</p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: Briana has permissions to create a new file in the IT share because she is a member of the IT group and her Country claim has a value of US.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of <strong>LON-CL1</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(3)&quot;).click()">LON-CL2</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Mike</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: Mike is a member of the IT group.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>Select the <strong>File Explorer</strong> icon on the taskbar.</p> </li> <li> <p>In File Explorer, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">&bsol;&bsol;LON-CL1</strong> in the Address bar, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the details pane, double-click <strong>IT</strong>.</p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: Mike is a member of the IT group, but he cannot connect to the IT share.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Close</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong>, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">cmd</strong> and then select <strong>Command Prompt</strong></p> </li> <li> <p>At the command prompt, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong> <code>whoami /claims</code>. Review the output, and then close the command prompt.</p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: Mike has a Country claim with the value of GB, so he cannot connect to the IT share, even though he is a member of the IT group.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of <strong>LON-CL2</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(3)&quot;).click()">LON-CL2</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Davy</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong>, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">cmd</strong> and then select <strong>Command Prompt</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the command prompt, type the following command, <code>whoami /claims</code>, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Review the output, and then close the command prompt.</p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: Davy is in the Research department, and his department claim has the value of Research.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>Select the <strong>File Explorer</strong> icon on the taskbar.</p> </li> <li> <p>In File Explorer, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">&bsol;&bsol;LON-CL1</strong> in the Address bar, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the details pane, double-click <strong>Research</strong>, and then verify that Davy can view the contents of the Research folder.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the details pane, right-click the <strong>empty space</strong>, select <strong>New</strong>, select <strong>Text Document</strong>, and then type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">File60</strong> as the name of the file.</p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: Davy has permissions to create a new file in the Research share because his department claim has a value of Research.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of <strong>LON-CL2</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-3-view-effective-permissions">Task 3: View effective permissions</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Switch to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select the <strong>File Explorer</strong> icon on the taskbar.</p> </li> <li> <p>In File Explorer, browse to <strong>C:&bsol;Data</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In File Explorer, right-click <strong>Marketing</strong>, select <strong>Properties</strong>, select the <strong>Security</strong> tab, select <strong>Advanced</strong>, and then select the <strong>Effective Access</strong> tab.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Advanced Security Settings for Marketing dialog box, select <strong>Select a user</strong>, in the <strong>Enter the object names to select (examples)</strong> box, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Anders</strong>, click <strong>Check Names</strong> and then select <strong>OK</strong>, and then select <strong>View effective access</strong>. View the effective permissions, and then select <strong>OK</strong> twice.</p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: As Authenticated Users have the Modify permission to the Marketing folder, you can see that Anders has the most permissions allowed.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>In File Explorer, right-click <strong>Research</strong>, select <strong>Properties</strong>, select the <strong>Security</strong> tab, select <strong>Advanced</strong>, and then select the <strong>Effective Access</strong> tab.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Advanced Security Settings for Research dialog box, select <strong>Select a user</strong>, in the <strong>Enter the object names to select (examples)</strong> text box, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Brian Burke</strong>, click <strong>Check Names</strong> select <strong>OK</strong>, and then select <strong>View effective access</strong>.</p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: Brian is a member of Development group. Only users with the department claim value of Research have permissions to the folder, you can see that Brian has no permissions allowed.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>In the Advanced Security Settings for Research dialog box, select <strong>Include a user claim</strong>, select <strong>department</strong> in the drop-down list, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Research</strong> in the Enter value here text box, and then select <strong>View effective access</strong>.</p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: You can see that if Brian had the department user claim with the value of Research, he would have most permissions allowed.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>In the Advanced Security Settings for Research dialog box, select <strong>Select a user</strong>, in the <strong>Enter the object names to select (examples)</strong> box, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Aaron</strong>, click <strong>Check Names</strong> select <strong>OK</strong>, and then select <strong>View effective access</strong>. Review the effective permissions, and then select <strong>OK</strong> twice.</p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: If Aaron had the user claim of department with the value of Research, he would have the most permissions allowed.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of <strong>LON-CL1</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise, you will have configured and tested conditions to control access to file shares. You will have also viewed effective permissions.</p> <p><strong>END OF LAB</strong></p> </div> <div class="page" id="page16"> <h1 id="practice-lab-troubleshooting-file-access-issues">Practice Lab 16: Troubleshooting File Access Issues</h1> <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2> <p>In this lab, you will troubleshoot and resolve permissions needed to access file resources.</p> <h2 id="lab-setup">Lab Setup</h2> <h3 id="task-1-simulate-the-issue">Task 1: Simulate the issue</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(1)&quot;).click()">LON-DC1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Open <strong>File Explorer</strong> and then browse to <strong>E:&bsol;Labfiles&bsol;Mod07</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Run the <strong>E:&bsol;Labfiles&bsol;Mod07&bsol;Lab.cmd</strong> script.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close File Explorer.</p> </li> </ol> <h2 id="exercise-1-resolving-file-permissions">Exercise 1: Resolving file permissions</h2> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>Users in the Marketing department have a data folder to which they should have exclusive access. </p> <p>Alice Ciccu, a member of the Marketing department, reports that non-Marketing users have access to Marketing data in the <strong>&bsol;&bsol;LON-DC1&bsol;Marketing</strong> shared folder. </p> <p>Mike Ray, a member of the IT department, reports that he can review and open files in the Marketing share, but cannot modify the files in this share.</p> <p>You need to investigate and ensure that only members of the Marketing department can access the the <strong>&bsol;&bsol;LON-DC1&bsol;Marketing</strong> shared folder.</p> <h3 id="task-1-validate-the-issue">Task 1: Validate the issue</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Mike</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>From the taskbar, open the <strong>File Explorer</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In File Explorer, in the address bar, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">&bsol;&bsol;LON-DC1&bsol;Marketing</strong>, and then select Enter.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the details pane, open <strong>Report</strong>, and then verify that it opens in Notepad.</p> </li> <li> <p>In Notepad, enter your name. Select <strong>File</strong>, select <strong>Save</strong>, select <strong>Report</strong>, select <strong>Save</strong>, and then select <strong>Yes</strong>.</p> <blockquote> <p>You will receive a message that indicates “You do not have permission to open this file”, because Mike is not in the Marketing group and he cannot modify the files.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>In the message select <strong>OK</strong>, close <strong>Notepad</strong>, and then select <strong>Don’t Save</strong>.</p> <blockquote> <p>Mike is not in the Marketing group, so you should not be able to access the share. However, you were able to open share content. You need to diagnose and correct this improper configuration.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>Close File Explorer and sign out of LON-CL1.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-resolve-the-issue">Task 2: Resolve the issue</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Users who are not members of the Marketing group should not be able to access the Marketing share. Attempt to resolve the problem by using your knowledge of file permissions and shared folder access. If you are unable to resolve the problem, escalate it by asking your instructor for additional guidance. The following steps provide the troubleshooting steps and solution to the issue.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(1)&quot;).click()">LON-DC1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Open <strong>File Explorer</strong> and then browse to <strong>E:&bsol;</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click <strong>Marketing</strong> or activate its context menu, and then select <strong>Properties</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Marketing Properties dialog box, select the <strong>Sharing</strong> tab.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Sharing tab, select <strong>Advanced Sharing</strong> and then select <strong>Permissions</strong>. Verify that the permissions are granted to Everyone Change, and then select Cancel twice.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Marketing Properties dialog box, select the <strong>Security</strong> tab.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Security tab, select <strong>Advanced</strong>, and then select the <strong>Effective Access</strong> tab.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Effective Access tab, select <strong>Select a user</strong>. </p> </li> <li> <p>In the Select User, Computer, Service Account, or Group dialog box, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Mike</strong>, click <strong>Check Names</strong> and then select <strong>OK</strong>, and then select <strong>View effective access</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Verify that Mike has Read permissions, but he does not have Change or Delete permissions, and then select the <strong>Permissions</strong> tab.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Advanced Security Settings for Marketing dialog box, select <strong>Disable inheritance</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Convert inherited permissions into explicit permissions on this object,</strong> and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Marketing Properties</strong> dialog box, select <strong>Edit</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Permissions for Marketing dialog box, select <strong>Users</strong>, select <strong>Remove</strong>, and then select <strong>OK</strong>. </p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Advanced</strong>, and then select the <strong>Effective Access</strong> tab.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Effective Access tab, select <strong>Select a user</strong>. </p> </li> <li> <p>In the Select User, Computer, Service Account, or Group dialog box, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Mike</strong>, click <strong>Check Names</strong> and then select <strong>OK</strong>, and then select <strong>View effective access</strong>. Verify that Mike has no permissions.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Effective Access tab, select <strong>Select a user</strong>. </p> </li> <li> <p>In the Select User, Computer, Service Account, or Group dialog box, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Alice</strong>, click <strong>Check Names</strong> and then select <strong>OK</strong>, and then select <strong>View effective access</strong>. </p> </li> <li> <p>Verify that Alice is a member of the Marketing group, that she has Read and Write permissions, and that her access is limited only by share permissions. </p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>OK</strong>, and then select <strong>Close</strong>. </p> <blockquote> <p>The inherited permissions on E:&bsol;Marketing included the Users group having Read permissions. The Users group was removed, and now only members of the Marketing group have access.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>Close all open windows and sign out of LON-DC1.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise you have fixed file permission issues for the Marketing department.</p> <h2 id="exercise-2-resolving-file-access">Exercise 2: Resolving file access</h2> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>Some Marketing users can modify files in the Collected folder on the Marketing share and some Marketing users cannot. </p> <p>Bruce Keever, is a member of the Marketing department and located in London. He reports that he and some other Marketing users cannot modify the <strong>Survey.txt</strong> file in the Collected folder on the Marketing share. He can open the file and read its content.</p> <p>Alice Ciccu is also a member of Marketing department and located in Seattle. She reports that she is able to modify the Survey.txt file. </p> <p>You need to investigate and ensure that all users from the Marketing department from both Seattle and London offices be able to modify the files in the Collected folder.</p> <h3 id="task-1-validate-the-issue">Task 1: Validate the issue</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Alice</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>From the taskbar, open the <strong>File Explorer</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In File Explorer, in the address bar, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">&bsol;&bsol;LON-DC1&bsol;Marketing&bsol;Collected</strong>, and then select Enter.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the details pane, open <strong>Surveys</strong>, and then verify that it opens in Notepad.</p> </li> <li> <p>In Notepad, enter your name, close <strong>Notepad</strong>, and then select <strong>Save</strong>.</p> <blockquote> <p>You now have verified that Alice can modify the file.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>Close File Explorer and sign out of LON-CL1.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Bruce</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>From the taskbar, open the <strong>File Explorer</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In File Explorer, in the address bar, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">&bsol;&bsol;LON-DC1&bsol;Marketing&bsol;Collected</strong>, and then select Enter.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the details pane, open <strong>Surveys</strong>, and then verify that it opens in Notepad.</p> </li> <li> <p>In Notepad, enter some additional text, close <strong>Notepad</strong>, select <strong>Save</strong>, select <strong>Surveys</strong>, select <strong>Save</strong> again, and then select <strong>Yes</strong>.</p> <blockquote> <p>This message displays because Bruce does not have permission to modify the file.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>In Notepad, select <strong>OK</strong>. Select <strong>Cancel</strong>, close <strong>Notepad</strong>, and then select <strong>Don’t Save</strong></p> </li> <li> <p>Close File Explorer and sign out of LON-CL1.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-resolve-the-issue">Task 2: Resolve the issue</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Marketing users who are from offices in Seattle and London must be able to modify the files in the Collected folder. Attempt to resolve the problem by using your knowledge of file permissions and shared folder access. If you are unable to resolve the problem, escalate it by asking your instructor for additional guidance. The following steps provide the troubleshooting steps and solution to the issue.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(1)&quot;).click()">LON-DC1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Open <strong>File Explorer</strong> and then browse to <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">E:&bsol;Marketing&bsol;Collected</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the details pane, right-click <strong>Surveys.txt</strong> or activate its context menu, select <strong>Properties</strong>, select the <strong>Security</strong> tab, and then select <strong>Advanced</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In Advanced Security Settings for Surveys.txt, verify that there is a condition defined for Allow Write access for the Marketing group. Confirm that the condition requires that the user&#39;s city is Seattle.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select the <strong>Effective Access</strong> tab. Select <strong>Select a user</strong>, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Bruce</strong>, click <strong>Check Names</strong> and then select <strong>OK</strong>, and then select <strong>View effective access</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Review effective access for Bruce.</p> <blockquote> <p>Bruce has Read permissions, but permissions do not allow him to write data to the file. This is because you did not include a user claim yet, so the condition was not evaluated for Bruce.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Include a user claim</strong>, select the drop-down box arrow, and then select <strong>City</strong>. In the <strong>Enter value here</strong> text box, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Seattle</strong>, and then select <strong>View effective access</strong>. </p> </li> <li> <p>Verify that if Bruce has a user claim for city with the value Seattle, and that he can write data to the file.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Select a user</strong>, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Alice</strong>, click <strong>Check Names</strong> and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Verify that user claim City=Seattle is still included, and then select <strong>View effective access</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Verify that if Alice has a user claim for city with a value of Seattle, she would also be able to write data to the file. Select <strong>OK</strong> twice.</p> <blockquote> <p>You need to ensure that only Marketing users from offices in Seattle and London should be able to modify the file. Therefore, you must not remove the condition, but extend it to include Marketing users from London.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>In File Explorer, in the navigation pane, right-click <strong>Collected</strong> or activate its context menu, and then select <strong>Properties</strong>. </p> </li> <li> <p>Select the <strong>Security</strong> tab, and then select <strong>Advanced</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Advanced Security Settings for Collected dialog box, select the Allow Write entry access for the Marketing group that has the Condition, and then select <strong>Edit</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Permission Entry for Collected dialog box, select <strong>Add a condition</strong>. In the drop-down box, expand the <strong>And</strong> option, and then select <strong>Or</strong>. </p> </li> <li> <p>Compose the following expression: <strong>User city Equals Value London</strong>. You must enter London in the last text box, and then select <strong>OK</strong> three times.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close all open windows and sign out of LON-DC1.</p> </li> <li> <p>Switch to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Bruce</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>From the taskbar, open the <strong>File Explorer</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In File Explorer, in the address bar, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">&bsol;&bsol;LON-DC1&bsol;Marketing&bsol;Collected</strong>, and then select Enter.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the details pane, open <strong>Surveys</strong>, and then verify that it opens in Notepad.</p> </li> <li> <p>In Notepad, enter some additional text, close <strong>Notepad</strong>, select <strong>Save</strong>.</p> <blockquote> <p>Notice that Bruce can now modify the file, although he is from the London office.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>Close File Explorer and sign out of LON-CL1.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise you have fixed the file access issue for the Marketing department.</p> <p><strong>END OF LAB</strong></p> </div> <div class="page" id="page17"> <h1 id="practice-lab-synchronizing-files-with-onedrive">Practice Lab 17: Synchronizing files with OneDrive</h1> <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2> <p>In this lab you will learn how to synchronize content between devices using OneDrive.</p> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>Your organization would like to leverage OneDrive as a method for accessing user files from any device. You test this solution by signing in with your Microsoft account and creating a file on LON-CL2 and verifying that the file automatically synchronizes to LON-CL1. You will also enable OneDrive PC folder backup to redirect the local Desktop and Documents folder to OneDrive.</p> <p><em>Note: To complete this lab, you need to have a Microsoft account. You can obtain a free Microsoft account which can be created at <a href="https://outlook.live.com">https://outlook.live.com</a>. Your instructor can guide you on how to create an account if required.</em></p> <h3 id="task-1-connect-your-microsoft-account-to-LON-CL1-and-LON-CL2">Task 1: Connect your Microsoft account to LON-CL1 and LON-CL2</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Student</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong> and then select <strong>Settings</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Settings</strong> page, select <strong>Accounts</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Accounts</strong> page, select <strong>Your info</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select the link that states <strong>Sign in with a Microsoft account instead</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Microsoft account Sign in</strong> page, enter your Microsoft account email address and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Enter password</strong> page, enter your Microsoft account password and then select <strong>Sign in</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Sign into this computer using your Microsoft account</strong> page, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong> and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Create a PIN</strong> page, select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Set up a PIN</strong> dialog box, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">1029</strong> in both the <strong>New PIN</strong> and <strong>Confirm PIN</strong> boxes. Select <strong>OK</strong>. Notice that your Microsoft account is now listed on the Your info page.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of LON-CL1.</p> </li> <li> <p>Repeat steps 1-11 on <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(3)&quot;).click()">LON-CL2</a></strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-enable-onedrive-sync-on-LON-CL2">Task 2: Enable OneDrive sync on LON-CL2</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(3)&quot;).click()">LON-CL2</a></strong> with your Microsoft account and the PIN <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">1029</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the task bar, select <strong>File Explorer</strong>, and then select the <strong>OneDrive</strong> node.</p> </li> </ol> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: The OneDrive node in File Explorer might take several minutes to appear. Please wait for it to appear before proceeding. If it takes longer than 15 minutes, sign out, and then sign back in by using your Microsoft account. If you are prompted to provide your email address, use the Microsoft account that you signed in with.</em></p> <ol> <li> <p>In the File Explorer console tree, expand <strong>OneDrive</strong>, and then select the <strong>Documents</strong> folder.</p> <p><em>If the Documents folder is not visible, wait approximately 5 minutes for it to appear.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click the empty space in the <strong>Details pane</strong>, select <strong>New</strong>, and then select <strong>Text Document</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">File from LON-CL2</strong> in the <strong>Name</strong> box, and then press Enter.</p> </li> <li> <p>Double-click the document, and when Notepad opens, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">File on LON-CL2</strong>. Press <strong>Ctrl+S</strong>, and then close Notepad.</p> </li> <li> <p>Wait until OneDrive has synchronized the changes indicated by a green check mark symbol in the <strong>Status</strong> row.</p> </li> </ol> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: If OneDrive indicates it is paused, right-click on the OneDrive status icon, select Resume Syncing.</em></p> <h3 id="task-3-enable-onedrive-sync-on-LON-CL1">Task 3: Enable OneDrive sync on LON-CL1</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Switch to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> with your Microsoft account with the PIN <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">1029</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the task bar, select <strong>File Explorer</strong>, and then select the <strong>OneDrive</strong> node.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>File Explorer</strong> console tree, expand <strong>OneDrive</strong>, and then select the <strong>Documents</strong> folder. After a few minutes, the <strong>File from LON-CL2</strong> document should appear (it can take up to five minutes).</p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: By default OneDrive has the Files On-Demand feature enabled that will download files only on the first use on a device. Such cloud files that have been created Online or on another device are indicated by a cloud symbol in Status.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>Double-click the <strong>File from LON-CL2</strong> document. </p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: The file will now be downloaded to your device before it will open. If OneDrive indicates it is paused, right-click on the OneDrive status icon, select Resume Syncing.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Notepad</strong> window, directly under the <strong>File on LON-CL2</strong> line, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Also on LON-CL1</strong>, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Press <strong>Ctrl+S</strong>, and then close Notepad.</p> </li> <li> <p>Make a note of the date and time of the <strong>File from LON-CL2</strong> file.</p> </li> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>, close File Explorer.</p> </li> <li> <p>Switch to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(3)&quot;).click()">LON-CL2</a></strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Check the date and time of the <strong>File from LON-CL2</strong> document. When it changes to the date and time you noted on <strong>LON-CL1</strong>, double-click the file (it takes up to five minutes to change).</p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: You should now see the two lines in Notepad.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>Close Notepad.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click the <strong>File from LON-CL2</strong> document, and select <strong>Always keep on this device.</strong> </p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: The check mark symbol in Status will now change to a white check mark in a green circle indicating that this file is always available on your device.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click the <strong>File from LON-CL2</strong> document, and select <strong>Free up space.</strong> </p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: This will convert the file back to an online document indicated by the cloud symbol that needs to be downloaded on the first use. This is intended to free up space on your local hard disk.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(3)&quot;).click()">LON-CL2</a></strong>, close File Explorer.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-4-configure-onedrive-pc-folder-backup">Task 4: Configure OneDrive PC folder backup</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Switch to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>, select <strong>Start</strong> and then select <strong>Settings</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Settings</strong> page, select <strong>Accounts</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Accounts</strong> page, select <strong>Windows backup</strong>.</p> <blockquote> <p>Notice that OneDrive folder backup is not enabled.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>Next to OneDrive folder syncing, select <strong>Set up syncing</strong>. The Manage folder backup window opens.</p> <blockquote> <p>Notice that you can choose to have OneDrive back up the desktop, Documents, and Pictures folders.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>In the Manage folder backup dialog box, select <strong>Desktop</strong> and <strong>Documents</strong>. Remove the check mark next to <strong>Pictures</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start backup</strong> and then select <strong>View sync process</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the OneDrive app, select <strong>Open folder</strong>.</p> <blockquote> <p>Notice the folders synced to OneDrive.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>Close all open windows on LON-CL1.</p> </li> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>, on the desktop create a new Text document named <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">File1.txt</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Repeat steps 1-9 on <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(3)&quot;).click()">LON-CL2</a></strong>.</p> <blockquote> <p>Notice File1.txt is synchronized to the desktop on LON-CL2. Desktop and Documents are synchronized and available from both LON-CL1 and LON-CL2.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of both LON-CL1 and LON-CL2.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: During this lab you have synchronized files between different devices using OneDrive.</p> <p><strong>END OF LAB</strong></p> </div> <div class="page" id="page18"> <h1 id="practice-lab-installing-apps-in-windows-client">Practice Lab 18: Installing Apps in Windows Client</h1> <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2> <p>In this lab you will learn how install and update Microsoft Store Apps and how to discover and install packaged apps by using Windows Package Manager.</p> <h2 id="exercise-1-installing-and-updating-microsoft-store-apps">Exercise 1: Installing and updating Microsoft Store apps</h2> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>You need to test the download and update functionality of the Microsoft App Store. You will download and install an app named the <strong>Microsoft Remote Desktop</strong>. You also need to validate how Microsoft Store apps are updated and uninstalled.</p> <h3 id="lab-preparation">Lab preparation</h3> <p><em>Note: In some situations, the Windows Update service may be disabled. Use the following steps to validate and enable the Windows update service if needed. This is not necessary to run in typical Windows client scenarios.</em></p> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">.&bsol;Admin</strong> with the password of <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click <strong>Start</strong>, and then select <strong>Windows PowerShell (Admin)</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>User Account Control</strong> dialog box, select <strong>Yes</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Administrator: Windows PowerShell</strong> window, type <strong>the following command</strong> and then press <strong>Enter</strong>. </p> </li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-keyword">Set</span>-Service <span class="hljs-comment">wuauserv -Startuptype Manual</span></code> </pre> <ol> <li>Sign out of LON-CL1.</li> </ol> <h3 id="task-1-connect-your-microsoft-account-to-LON-CL1-and-LON-CL2">Task 1: Connect your Microsoft account to LON-CL1 and LON-CL2</h3> <blockquote> <p>Note: You only need to complete this task if you did not complete lab <strong>0704: Synchronizing Files with OneDrive</strong>, or if you ended or reverted the virtual environment after lab 0704. To complete this task, you need to have a Microsoft account. You can obtain a free Microsoft account which can be created at <a href="https://outlook.live.com">https://outlook.live.com</a>. Your instructor can guide you on how to create an account if required.</p> </blockquote> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Student</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong> and then select <strong>Settings</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Settings</strong> page, select <strong>Accounts</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Accounts</strong> page, select <strong>Your info</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select the link that states <strong>Sign in with a Microsoft account instead</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Microsoft account Sign in</strong> page, enter your Microsoft account email address and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Enter password</strong> page, enter your Microsoft account password and then select <strong>Sign in</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Sign into this computer using your Microsoft account</strong> page, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong> and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Create a PIN</strong> page, select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Set up a PIN</strong> dialog box, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">1029</strong> in both the <strong>New PIN</strong> and <strong>Confirm PIN</strong> boxes. Select <strong>OK</strong>. Notice that your Microsoft account is now listed on the Your info page.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of LON-CL1.</p> </li> <li> <p>Repeat steps 1-11 on <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(3)&quot;).click()">LON-CL2</a></strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-configure-app-updates-and-uninstall-an-app">Task 2: Configure app updates and uninstall an app</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> with your Microsoft account and the PIN <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">1029</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Click <strong>Start</strong>, and then select <strong>Microsoft Store</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Microsoft Store</strong> app, select the sign in icon on the menu bar, and then select <strong>Settings</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Next to <strong>App updates</strong>, verify that <strong>Update apps automatically</strong> is set to enabled.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Microsoft Store</strong> app, select the <strong>Library</strong> icon on the menu bar. Notice that there are several apps waiting to be updated.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Update all</strong>. All of the installed apps begin to download and install app updates as needed. </p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong>, right-click <strong>Tips</strong>, and then select <strong>Uninstall</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>This app and its related information will be removed</strong> message box, select <strong>Uninstall</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-3-install-a-microsoft-store-app">Task 3: Install a Microsoft Store app</h3> <ol> <li> <p>In the Microsoft Store app, select <strong>Search</strong>, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Microsoft Remote Desktop</strong>, and then press Enter.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Microsoft Remote Desktop</strong> search results, select <strong>Get</strong>. </p> </li> <li> <p>Close the Microsoft Store app.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong> and verify that Microsoft Remote Desktop is added to the Start page. It may take a while for the app to download and install. Continue with the next exercise and check back later.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise, you will have managed Microsoft Store app updates, uninstalled an app, and installed a Microsoft Store app, </p> <h2 id="exercise-2-installing-an-app-by-using-windows-package-manager">Exercise 2: Installing an app by using Windows Package Manager</h2> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>You have been asked to install an application by using the Windows Package Manager <strong>winget</strong> command-line tool built into Windows 11. You will search for and install an application named <strong>PowerToys</strong>.</p> <h3 id="lab-preparation">Lab preparation</h3> <p><em>Note: The Windows Package Manager <strong>winget</strong> is a command-line tool built into Windows 11. Since we are using Windows 10, we need to install it using the following command. This step is not necessary in typical Windows 11 client scenarios.</em></p> <ol> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>, select <strong>Start</strong> and then type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">PowerShell</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under Windows PowerShell, select <strong>Run as administrator</strong>. At the User Account Control message, select <strong>Yes</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Administrator: Windows PowerShell</strong> window, type <strong>the following command</strong> and then press <strong>Enter</strong>. </p> </li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-attribute">Invoke-WebRequest -Uri &quot;https://github.com/microsoft/winget-cli/releases/download/v1.9.25200/Microsoft.DesktopAppInstaller_8wekyb3d8bbwe.msixbundle&quot; -OutFile &quot;Microsoft.DesktopAppInstaller_8wekyb3d8bbwe.msixbundle&quot;</span></code> </pre> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-attribute">Add-AppxPackage -Path &quot;.\Microsoft.DesktopAppInstaller_8wekyb3d8bbwe.msixbundle&quot;</span></code> </pre> <h3 id="task-1-search-for-and-install-an-app-using-winget">Task 1: Search for and install an app using winget</h3> <ol> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>, select <strong>Start</strong> and then type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">PowerShell</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under Windows PowerShell, select <strong>Run as administrator</strong>. At the User Account Control message, select <strong>Yes</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>To review the commands available with winget, type the following command and then press Enter:</p> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-attribute">winget</span></code> </pre> </li> <li> <p>To display a list of applications installed on the device, type the following command and then press Enter:</p> <pre> <code>winget <span class="hljs-built_in">list</span></code> </pre> <p>At the message prompt, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Yes</strong> and then press Enter.</p> </li> <li> <p>To search for an available app to install from published online repositories, type the following comment and press Enter:</p> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-attribute">winget search</span></code> </pre> </li> <li> <p>To filter the search list, provide a search string. For example, to find all apps that have the word <strong>Reader</strong> associated with it, type the following command and press Enter:</p> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-attribute">winget search reader</span></code> </pre> </li> <li> <p>To search for the <strong>PowerToys</strong> app, type the following command and press Enter:</p> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-attribute">winget search powertoys</span></code> </pre> <p>Notice that information is returned with the name, ID, version, and source of the package.</p> </li> <li> <p>To install an app using winget, type the following command and press Enter:</p> <pre> <code>winget <span class="hljs-keyword">install</span> <span class="hljs-comment">--id Microsoft.Powertoys</span></code> </pre> <p>PowerToys downloads and installs on the local device.</p> </li> <li> <p>After PowerToys installs and opens, close the <strong>Welcome to PowerToys</strong> window.</p> </li> <li> <p>To search for additional information about the <strong>PowerToys</strong> app, type the following command and press Enter:</p> <pre> <code>winget <span class="hljs-keyword">show</span> <span class="hljs-comment">--id Microsoft.Powertoys</span></code> </pre> <p>Notice that detailed information is returned for the PowerToys package.</p> </li> <li> <p>To uninstall an app by using winget, type the following command and press Enter:</p> <pre> <code>winget <span class="hljs-keyword">uninstall</span> <span class="hljs-comment">--id Microsoft.Powertoys</span></code> </pre> </li> <li> <p>Close PowerShell and sign out of LON-CL1.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise, you will have used the Windows Package Manager <strong>winget</strong> command-line tool to list and search for packaged apps. You then installed and uninstalled the PowerToys app by using the winget command-line tool. </p> <p><strong>END OF LAB</strong></p> </div> <div class="page" id="page19"> <h1 id="practice-lab-configuring-microsoft-edge">Practice Lab 19: Configuring Microsoft Edge</h1> <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2> <p>In this lab you will learn how to configure the Internet Explorer Enterprise Mode to provide compatibility for Microsoft Edge to open legacy web sites.</p> <h3 id="prerequisites">Prerequisites</h3> <p>The following lab(s) must be completed before this lab:</p> <ul> <li>0402-Configuring and Testing Name Resolution - Exercise 2: Testing Name Resolution</li> </ul> <h2 id="exercise-1-configuring-microsoft-edge-to-support-internet-explorer-enterprise-mode">Exercise 1: Configuring Microsoft Edge to support Internet Explorer Enterprise Mode</h2> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>Adatum uses a web site located at intranet.adatum.com. This site currently only works properly using older Internet Explorer versions. As you recently upgraded all devices to the latest version of Microsoft Edge Chromium, you must ensure that this web site still opens and works with compatibility mode.</p> <p><em>Note: This Exercise requires that a DNS CNAME entry for intranet.Adatum.com be added which resolves to SEA-CFG1.Adatum.com. This task is performed in Module 5 lab 0502-Configuring and Testing Name Resolution. Also note that Microsoft Edge .admx templates have already been installed to allow for the creation of Microsoft Edge Chromium group policy settings.</em></p> <h3 id="task-1-verify-the-site-is-not-displayed-in-enterprise-mode">Task 1: Verify the site is not displayed in Enterprise Mode</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Cari</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the task bar, select <strong>Microsoft Edge</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Microsoft Edge window, select <strong>Start without your data</strong>, and then select <strong>Confirm and start browsing</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close Microsoft Edge.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the task bar, select <strong>Microsoft Edge</strong></p> </li> <li> <p>In the Microsoft Edge Address bar, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">edge://compat/enterprise</strong>, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>. Notice that the Enterprise Mode Site List does not contain any entries.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of <strong>LON-CL1</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-create-a-site-list-for-internet-explorer-enterprise-mode">Task 2: Create a Site list for Internet Explorer Enterprise Mode</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Switch to <strong>SEA-CFG1</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong>SEA-CFG1</strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select the <strong>File Explorer</strong> icon on the taskbar.</p> </li> <li> <p>In File Explorer, browse to <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">&bsol;&bsol;LON-DC1&bsol;Labfiles&bsol;Apps</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Double-click the <strong>EMIESiteListManager.msi</strong> file.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Enterprise Mode Site List Manager Setup window, select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the End-User License Agreement page, select the check box for <strong>I accept the terms in the License Agreement</strong>, and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Destination Folder page, select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Ready to install Enterprise Mode Site List Manager page, select <strong>Install</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Completed the Enterprise Mode Site List Manager Setup Wizard page, select <strong>Finish</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close File Explorer.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select the <strong>Start</strong> button, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Enterprise</strong>, right-click <strong>Enterprise Mode Site List Manager</strong> and select <strong>Run as administrator</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Enterprise Mode Site List Manager for v.2 schema window, select <strong>Add</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Add new website window, in the URL text box, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">intranet.adatum.com</strong>. In the Compat Mode drop-down list box, select <strong>IE9 Document Mode</strong>, and then select <strong>Save</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select the <strong>File</strong> menu, and then select <strong>Save to XML</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Save as… dialog box, navigate to <strong>C:&bsol;inetpub&bsol;wwwroot</strong>. In the File name text box, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">AdatumEnterpriseMode</strong>, and then select <strong>Save</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close Enterprise Mode Site List Manager.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the task bar, select <strong>Microsoft Edge</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Address bar, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button"><a href="http://Intranet.Adatum.com/AdatumEnterpriseMode.xml">http://Intranet.Adatum.com/AdatumEnterpriseMode.xml</a></strong>, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Verify that the XML file opens correctly.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close <strong>Microsoft Edge</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-3-create-a-policy-to-enable-internet-explorer-enterprise-mode">Task 3: Create a policy to enable Internet Explorer Enterprise Mode</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Switch to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(1)&quot;).click()">LON-DC1</a></strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(1)&quot;).click()">LON-DC1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(1)&quot;).click()">LON-DC1</a></strong>, switch to <strong>Server Manager</strong>, select <strong>Tools</strong>, and then select <strong>Group Policy Management</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Group Policy Management window, expand <strong>Forest: Adatum.com</strong>, expand <strong>Domains</strong>, expand <strong>Adatum.com</strong>, and select <strong>Group Policy Objects</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click <strong>Group Policy Objects</strong>, and then select <strong>New</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the New GPO dialog box, in the Name box, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Internet Explorer Enterprise Mode Policy</strong>, and then select <strong>OK</strong>. </p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click <strong>Internet Explorer Enterprise Mode Policy</strong>, and then select <strong>Edit</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Group Policy Management Editor window, in the left pane, expand <strong>Computer Configuration</strong>, expand <strong>Policies</strong>, expand <strong>Administrative Templates</strong>, and then select <strong>Microsoft Edge</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the content pane, double-click <strong>Configure Internet Explorer integration</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Enabled</strong>, and then from the <strong>Configure Internet Explorer integration</strong> drop down menu, select <strong>Internet Explorer mode</strong> and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the content pane, double-click <strong>Configure the Enterprise Mode Site List</strong>. (Be careful NOT to choose Configure the Enterprise Mode Cloud Site List.)</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Enabled</strong>, in the <strong>Configure the Enterprise Mode Site List</strong> text box, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button"><a href="http://Intranet.Adatum.com/AdatumEnterpriseMode.xml">http://Intranet.Adatum.com/AdatumEnterpriseMode.xml</a></strong>, and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close the Group Policy Management Editor window.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Group Policy Management window, right-click the <strong>Adatum.com</strong> domain, and then select <strong>Link an existing GPO</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Select GPO window, select <strong>Internet Explorer Enterprise Mode Policy</strong>, and select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close the Group Policy Management window.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-4-verify-the-site-is-now-in-enterprise-mode">Task 4: Verify the site is now in enterprise mode</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Switch to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> and sign in as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Cari</strong> with the password of <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong> and type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">cmd</strong>. Press <strong>Enter</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the command prompt, type the following command, and then press Enter.</p> <p><code>gpupdate /force</code></p> </li> <li> <p>On the task bar, select <strong>Microsoft Edge</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Microsoft Edge Address bar, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">edge://compat/enterprise</strong>, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>. Notice that the Enterprise Mode Site List contains <a href="http://intranet.adatum.com/AdatumEnterpriseMode.xml">http://intranet.adatum.com/AdatumEnterpriseMode.xml</a>. If it does not appear immediately, click <strong>Force update</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Microsoft Edge Address bar, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button"><a href="http://intranet.Adatum.com">http://intranet.Adatum.com</a></strong>, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Verify that the website displays correctly, and that the Internet Explorer mode icon appears in the address bar. Select the Internet Explorer mode icon to view information about how this site opens.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of <strong>LON-CL1</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise, you should have successfully configured the Internet Explorer Enterprise Mode for Microsoft Edge.</p> <h2 id="exercise-2-configuring-microsoft-edge-synchronization">Exercise 2: Configuring Microsoft Edge Synchronization</h2> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>You frequently use two devices, SEA-WS1 and SEA-WS2, and would like to ensure that Microsoft Edge favorites are synchronized between the two devices. You need configure Microsoft Edge synchronization settings between the devices.</p> <h3 id="task-1-connect-your-microsoft-account-to-sea-ws1-and-sea-ws2">Task 1: Connect your Microsoft account to SEA-WS1 and SEA-WS2</h3> <blockquote> <p>Note: You only need to complete this task if you did not complete lab <strong>0704: Synchronizing Files with OneDrive</strong>, or if you ended or reverted the virtual environment after lab 0704. To complete this task, you need to have a Microsoft account. You can obtain a free Microsoft account which can be created at <a href="https://outlook.live.com">https://outlook.live.com</a>. Your instructor can guide you on how to create an account if required.</p> </blockquote> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong>SEA-WS1</strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Student</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong> and then select <strong>Settings</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Windows Settings</strong> page, select <strong>Accounts</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Accounts</strong> page, select <strong>Your info</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select the link that states <strong>Sign in with a Microsoft account instead</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Microsoft account Sign in</strong> page, enter your Microsoft account email address and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Enter password</strong> page, enter your Microsoft account password and then select <strong>Sign in</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Sign into this computer using your Microsoft account</strong> page, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong> and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Create a PIN</strong> page, select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Set up a PIN</strong> dialog box, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">1029</strong> in both the <strong>New PIN</strong> and <strong>Confirm PIN</strong> boxes. Select <strong>OK</strong>. Notice that your Microsoft account is now listed on the Your info page.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of SEA-WS1.</p> </li> <li> <p>Repeat steps 1-11 on SEA-WS2.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-configure-synchronization-on-sea-ws1">Task 2: Configure synchronization on SEA-WS1</h3> <ol> <li> <p>On SEA-WS1, sign in with your Microsoft account using the PIN <strong>1029</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong>, then <strong>Settings</strong>, then select <strong>Accounts</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Windows backup</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Verify that <strong>Remember my apps</strong> is enabled.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Remember my preferences</strong> and verify that all options such as <strong>Passwords</strong>, <strong>Language preferences</strong>, and <strong>Other Windows settings</strong> are all enabled.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close <strong>Settings</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the taskbar, select <strong>Microsoft Edge</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the <strong>Sync your profile</strong> prompt, select <strong>Sync</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the end of the address bar, select the <strong>Settings and more</strong> ellipse button and then select <strong>Settings</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Profiles</strong> page, select <strong>Sync</strong>. Take note of the Edge settings that will be automatically synced. </p> </li> <li> <p>Enable both the <strong>History</strong> and <strong>Open tabs</strong> sync settings. </p> </li> <li> <p>On the Settings pane, select <strong>Appearance</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Scroll down to the <strong>Customize toolbar</strong> section and then next to <strong>Show favorites bar</strong> select <strong>Always</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In Microsoft Edge, navigate to <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button"><a href="http://www.microsoft.com/learn">http://www.microsoft.com/learn</a></strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the address bar, select the <strong>Add this page to favorites</strong> button to save as a favorite.</p> </li> <li> <p>Ensure that the <strong>Folder </strong>shows <strong>Favorites bar</strong>, and then select <strong>Done</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of SEA-WS1.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-3-configure-synchronization-on-sea-ws2">Task 3: Configure synchronization on SEA-WS2</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong>SEA-WS2</strong> with your Microsoft account using the PIN <strong>1029</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the taskbar, select <strong>Microsoft Edge</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the <strong>Sync your profile</strong> prompt, select <strong>Sync</strong>. Notice that the Favorites bar and the saved favorite is available in the browser on SEA-WS2.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Microsoft Edge browser, select <strong>Settings and more</strong>, and then select <strong>Settings</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Sync</strong> and then validate the sync settings for Microsoft Edge.</p> </li> <li> <p>Enable sync for both <strong>History</strong> and <strong>Open tabs</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the address bar, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button"><a href="https://docs.microsoft.com">https://docs.microsoft.com</a></strong> and press Enter.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the address bar, select the <strong>Add this page to favorites</strong> button to save as a favorite.</p> </li> <li> <p>Ensure that the <strong>Folder</strong> shows <strong>Favorites bar</strong>, and then select <strong>Done</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the address bar. select the <strong>Collections</strong> button and then in the Collections pane, select <strong>Next</strong> to complete the introduction.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under <strong>New collection</strong>, select <strong>Add current page</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Favorites</strong> bar, select <strong>Microsoft Learn</strong>, and then in the <strong>New collection</strong> pane, select <strong>Add current page</strong> to add this second page to the collection.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close <strong>Microsoft Edge</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of SEA-WS2.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-4-validate-synchronization">Task 4: Validate synchronization</h3> <ol> <li> <p>On SEA-WS1, sign in with your Microsoft account using the PIN <strong>1029</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the taskbar, select <strong>Microsoft Edge</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Verify that there are two favorites attached to the Favorites bar.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select the <strong>Collections</strong> button.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>New collection</strong> and verify that the two pages that you added in the previous task are available in the collection. If it is not visible, create another collection and verify that the collection syncs.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close <strong>Microsoft Edge</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of SEA-WS1.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results:</strong> After finishing this exercise, you will have added your Microsoft account to multiple devices and configure synchronization settings between the devices.</p> <p><strong>END OF LAB</strong></p> </div> <div class="page" id="page20"> <h1 id="practice-lab-managing-windows-update-settings">Practice Lab 20: Managing Windows Update Settings</h1> <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2> <p>In this lab you manage Windows Update settings for a single device and configure feature and quality update settings for multiple devices using Windows Update for Business Group Policy settings.</p> <h2 id="exercise-1-configuring-windows-update-for-a-single-device">Exercise 1: Configuring Windows Update for a Single Device</h2> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>You need to validate the Windows Update settings for LON-CL1. You have also been asked to ensure that the following Windows update settings are applied to the device:</p> <ul> <li>Updates for other Microsoft products should be enabled.</li> <li>A notification must be shown when the device requires a restart to finish updating.</li> <li>Delivery optimization must be configured to allow downloads from the internet and the local network.</li> <li>Active hours should be configured to be 7:00 AM to 8:00 PM.</li> <li>Updates should be paused for 2 weeks.</li> </ul> <h3 id="task-1-configure-windows-update">Task 1: Configure Windows Update</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">.&bsol;Admin</strong> with the password of <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong></p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong>, and then enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">PowerShell</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Search results, under Windows PowerShell, select <strong>Run as administrator</strong>. In the User Account Control dialog box, select <strong>Yes</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Administrator: Windows PowerShell window, type the following command, and then press Enter:</p> </li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-keyword">Set</span>-Service <span class="hljs-comment">wuauserv -StartupType Manual</span></code> </pre> <p><em>Note: For the lab setup, the Windows Update service is disabled. The above command is not necessary to run in typical Windows 10 scenarios.</em></p> <ol> <li> <p>Close Windows PowerShell.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong>, and then select the <strong>Settings</strong> icon.</p> </li> <li> <p>In <strong>Settings</strong>, select <strong>Update & Security</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Windows Update</strong> page, select <strong>Advanced options</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Advanced options</strong> page, enable the <strong>Receive updates for other Microsoft products when you update Windows </strong>option.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Advanced options</strong> page, enable the <strong>Show a notification when your PC requires a restart to finish updating</strong> option.</p> </li> <li> <p>Scroll down and then select <strong>Delivery Optimization</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Delivery Optimization page, verify that the <strong>Allow downloads from other PCs</strong> option is enabled.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>PCs on my local network, and PCs on the Internet</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Scroll down and then select <strong>Activity monitor</strong>. Take note of the Download Statistics and Upload Statistics and then click <strong>Back</strong> to return to the <strong>Delivery Optimization</strong> page.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the navigation pane, select <strong>Windows Update</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-change-active-hours-review-applied-updates-and-pause-updates">Task 2: Change active hours, review applied updates, and pause updates</h3> <ol> <li> <p>On the <strong>Windows Update</strong> page, select <strong>Change active hours</strong>.</p> <blockquote> <p>Verify that the current active hours are from 8:00AM to 5:00PM. </p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>Next to Current active hours: 8:00 AM to 5:00 PM, select <strong>Change</strong> and then change the <strong>Start time to 7:00AM</strong> and the <strong>End time to 8:00PM</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Click <strong>Back</strong> to return to the <strong>Windows Update</strong> page.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Windows Update</strong> page, select <strong>View update history</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Review the updates listed, and then select <strong>Uninstall updates</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Review the updates listed in <strong>Installed Updates</strong>. Close <strong>Installed Updates</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Click <strong>Back</strong> to return to the <strong>Windows Update</strong> page.</p> </li> <li> <p>Next to <strong>Pause updates</strong>, select the drop-down menu and select <strong>Pause for 2 weeks</strong>.</p> <blockquote> <p>Notice that the Windows Update indicator displays that updates are paused. You can also select <strong>Resume updates</strong> if needed.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>Close the <strong>Settings</strong> page.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of LON-CL1.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise, you will have successfully validated and configured Windows Update settings.</p> <h2 id="exercise-2-managing-feature-and-quality-updates-with-windows-update-for-business">Exercise 2: Managing Feature and Quality Updates with Windows Update for Business</h2> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>Adatum uses Windows Update for Business to manage the updates for Windows 10 devices.</p> <p>You have been delegated the task to create Group Policy Objects to configure Windows Update for Business for your Windows 10 devices. Your first task is to determine how many deployment rings you will need and the associated Windows update settings based upon business requirements. You then need to configure a Group Policy object for each deployment ring. The Group Policy Objects will then be linked to organizational units by the Active Directory administrators at a later time.</p> <h3 id="task-1-identify-windows-update-for-business-requirements">Task 1: Identify Windows Update for Business Requirements</h3> <p>Adatum currently configures each Windows 10 device to apply Windows updates based upon manual operating system settings. However a number of issues have come up that requires you to revisit and propose a new solution:</p> <ul> <li>Updates are not fully tested before they are installed on the all the computers in the organization. This is especially troublesome for when a new feature update is released.</li> <li>Some users have been pausing updates for an extended period of time.</li> <li>Some users have been enrolling into the Windows Insider Program, which has caused compatibility issues for some of the devices.</li> <li>It is difficult to maintain and manage the Windows 10 update settings using the current manual process.</li> </ul> <p>You have been asked to address these issues by:</p> <ul> <li>Ensuring that updates are tested at least 10 days before being deployed to everyone in the organization.</li> <li>Restricting standard users from configuring Windows Update settings.</li> <li>Implementing Windows Update for Business.</li> </ul> <p>You need to develop a plan to implement Windows Update for Business. Consider the following questions to help you with your solution:</p> <ol> <li>How will you ensure that an update has been tested properly before being deployed throughout the entire organization? <em>Answer: Create Active Directory Group Policy Objects that align with deployment rings. One possible solution is to create a pilot deployment ring that does not defer quality or feature updates. This will allow any device that has this policy to immediately obtain a released update and start its testing process. A second Broad deployment ring can be created that has a deferral for 10 days for both quality and feature updates. This second object would be applied to the rest of the organization and will not receive released updates until 10 days have passed.</em></li> <li>How will you ensure that standard users are restricted from configuring Windows Updates? <em>Answer: Using Group Policy settings will provide the ability to restrict various settings such as pausing updates and enrolling into the Windows Insiders Program.</em></li> <li>How will you manage and maintain Windows Updates for your organization? <em>Answer: Windows Update for Business uses Active Directory Group Policy. For more granular control and management, Microsoft Intune or Microsoft Endpoint Configuration Manager can also be used.</em></li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-use-group-policy-to-configure-windows-update-for-business">Task 2: Use Group Policy to configure Windows Update for Business</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(1)&quot;).click()">LON-DC1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password of <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In Server Manager, select <strong>Tools</strong> and then select <strong>Group Policy Management</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Maximize the Group Policy Management window. In the console tree, expand <strong>Forest:Adatum.com</strong>, expand <strong>Domains</strong>, and then expand <strong>Adatum.com</strong>. Select the <strong>Group Policy Objects</strong> node.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click the <strong>Group Policy Objects</strong> node, and then select <strong>New</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>New GPO</strong> dialog box, in the <strong>Name</strong> box, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pilot Release - Ring 1</strong>, and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the details pane, right-click <strong>Pilot Release - Ring 1</strong>, and then select <strong>Edit</strong>. Maximize the Group Policy Management Editor window.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the console tree, under <strong>Computer Configuration</strong>, expand <strong>Policies</strong>, expand <strong>Administrative Templates</strong>, expand <strong>Windows Components</strong>, and then select <strong>Windows Update</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the details pane, double-click <strong>Configure Automatic Updates</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Configure Automatic Updates</strong> window, configure the following and then select <strong>OK</strong>:</p> <ul> <li>Enabled: <strong>Selected</strong></li> <li>Configure automatic updating: <strong>4 - Auto download and schedule the install</strong></li> <li>Install updates for other Microsoft products: <strong>Selected</strong></li> </ul> </li> <li> <p>In the details pane, double-click <strong>Windows Update for Business</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the details pane, double-click <strong>Manage preview builds</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Manage preview builds</strong> window, select <strong>Disabled</strong>, and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the details pane, double-click <strong>Select when Preview Builds and Feature Updates are received</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Select when Preview Builds and Feature Updates are received</strong> window, configure the following and then select <strong>OK</strong>:</p> <ul> <li>Enabled: <strong>Selected</strong></li> <li>After a Preview Build or Feature Update is released, defer receiving it for this many days: <strong>0</strong></li> </ul> </li> </ol> <blockquote> <p>The Pilot Release - Ring 1 configuration will not have any updates deferred.</p> </blockquote> <ol> <li> <p>In the details pane, double-click <strong>Select when Quality Updates are received</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Select when Quality Updates are received</strong> window, configure the following and then select <strong>OK</strong>:</p> <ul> <li>Enabled: <strong>Selected</strong></li> <li>After a quality update is released, defer receiving it for this many days: <strong>0</strong></li> </ul> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-3-use-group-policy-to-configure-windows-update-experience-for-users">Task 3: Use Group Policy to configure Windows Update experience for users</h3> <ol> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(1)&quot;).click()">LON-DC1</a></strong>, ensure that you are still in the Group Policy Management Editor for the <strong>Pilot Release - Ring 1</strong> policy.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the console tree, under <strong>Computer Configuration</strong>, expand <strong>Policies</strong>, expand <strong>Administrative Templates</strong>, expand <strong>Windows Components</strong>, and then select <strong>Windows Update</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the details pane, double-click <strong>Remove access to &quot;Pause updates&quot; feature</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Remove access to &quot;Pause updates&quot; feature</strong> window, select <strong>Enabled</strong> and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the details pane, double-click <strong>Specify deadline before auto-restart for update installation</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Specify deadline before auto-restart for update installation</strong> window, configure the following and then select <strong>OK</strong>:</p> <ul> <li>Enabled: <strong>Selected</strong></li> <li>Specify the number of days before a pending restart will automatically be executed outside of active hours: Quality Updates (days): <strong>3</strong>; Feature Updates (days): <strong>3</strong></li> </ul> </li> <li> <p>Close the Group Policy Management Editor.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-4-use-group-policy-to-configure-the-broad-release-update-ring">Task 4: Use Group Policy to configure the Broad Release update ring</h3> <ol> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(1)&quot;).click()">LON-DC1</a></strong>, ensure that you are still in the Group Policy Management console.</p> </li> <li> <p>Maximize the Group Policy Management window. In the console tree, expand <strong>Forest:Adatum.com</strong>, expand <strong>Domains</strong>, and then expand <strong>Adatum.com</strong>. Select the <strong>Group Policy Objects</strong> node.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the details pane, right-click <strong>Pilot Release - Ring 1</strong>, and then select <strong>Copy</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click the <strong>Group Policy Objects</strong> node and then select <strong>Paste</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Copy GPO</strong> dialog box, ensure that <strong>Use the default permissions for new GPOs</strong> is selected and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the <strong>Copy</strong> dialog box, select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the details pane, select <strong>Copy of Pilot Release - Ring 1</strong> and then select <strong>Rename</strong>. Rename the object to <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Broad Release - Ring 2</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click <strong>Broad Release - Ring 2</strong> and then select <strong>Edit</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the console tree, under <strong>Computer Configuration</strong>, expand <strong>Policies</strong>, expand <strong>Administrative Templates</strong>, expand <strong>Windows Components</strong>, and then select <strong>Windows Update</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the details pane, double-click <strong>Windows Update for Business</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the details pane, double-click <strong>Select when Preview Builds and Feature Updates are received</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Select when Preview Builds and Feature Updates are received</strong> window, configure the following and then select <strong>OK</strong>:</p> <ul> <li>Enabled: <strong>Selected</strong></li> <li>After a Preview Build or Feature Update is released, defer receiving it for this many days: <strong>10</strong></li> </ul> </li> <li> <p>In the details pane, double-click <strong>Select when Quality Updates are received</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Select when Quality Updates are received</strong> window, configure the following and then select <strong>OK</strong>:</p> <ul> <li>Enabled: <strong>Selected</strong></li> <li>After a quality update is released, defer receiving it for this many days: <strong>10</strong></li> </ul> </li> <li> <p>Close the Group Policy Management Editor.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close the Group Policy Management console.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of LON-DC1.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise, you will have successfully configured Group Policy Objects to be later assigned to organizational units to manage Windows Update for Business settings.</p> <p><strong>END OF LAB</strong></p> </div> <div class="page" id="page21"> <h1 id="practice-lab-configuring-microsoft-defender-antivirus-and-windows-security">Practice Lab 21: Configuring Microsoft Defender Antivirus and Windows Security</h1> <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2> <p>In this exercise you will configure Microsoft Defender Antivirus and Windows Security settings.</p> <h2 id="exercise-1-detecting-threats-using-microsoft-defender-antivirus">Exercise 1: Detecting threats using Microsoft Defender Antivirus</h2> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>You&#39;ve been asked to configure and test Microsoft Defender Antivirus on LON-CL1. You need to configure protection settings to enable controlled folder access and ensure that Microsoft Defender can detect vulnerabilities. You&#39;ve decided to simulate a virus using a test file, sample.txt, located at C:&bsol;Files, to validate successful threat detection. You will also test out exclusions to see how adding an exclusion changes the behavior of the virus scanning process.</p> <h3 id="task-1-configure-microsoft-defender-antivirus">Task 1: Configure Microsoft Defender Antivirus</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong>, and then select the <strong>Settings</strong> icon.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Settings window, select <strong>Update &amp; Security</strong>, and then select <strong>Windows Security</strong>. Take note of the Protection areas listed under Windows Security.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Open Windows Security</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In Windows Security, select <strong>Virus &amp; threat protection</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Virus &amp; threat protection page, under Virus &amp; threat protection settings, select <strong>Manage settings</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under Controlled folder access, select <strong>Manage Controlled folder access</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Ransomware protection page, enable <strong>Controlled folder access</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under Controlled folder access, select <strong>Protected folders</strong> to view the default folders that are protected from unauthorized changes.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the navigation pane, select <strong>Virus &amp; threat protection</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-perform-a-scan">Task 2: Perform a scan</h3> <ol> <li> <p>On the Virus &amp; threat protection page, select <strong>Scan options</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Take note of the options available to configure and then select <strong>Quick scan</strong> and then select <strong>Scan now</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>The quick scan begins and provides information on the number of files scanned and estimated time remaining. The final result should state <strong>No current threats</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the navigation pane, select <strong>Virus &amp; threat protection</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close the Windows Security window and close Settings.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-3-introduce-suspicious-software">Task 3: Introduce suspicious software</h3> <ol> <li> <p>On the task bar, select the <strong>File Explorer</strong> icon.</p> </li> <li> <p>In <strong>File Explorer</strong> browse to <strong>C:&bsol;Files</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Files folder, double-click <strong>sample.txt</strong>. </p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: The sample.txt file contains a text string to test malware detection.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>In the sample.txt file, <strong>delete</strong> both instances of <strong>remove</strong> including the brackets and any extra lines or blank spaces.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Save</strong> and close Notepad.</p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: Microsoft Defender will immediately detect a potential threat and remove the file. It may take a minute for the file to automatically be removed.</em></p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-4-view-the-quarantined-file">Task 4: View the quarantined file</h3> <ol> <li> <p>In the notification area, select the <strong>Notifications</strong> icon, and then in the Action Center, select the notification that states that <strong>Threats found</strong>.</p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: This will open the <strong>Virus &amp; threat protection</strong> page in Windows security. The file is quarantined now.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>Under Current threats, select <strong>Protection history</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Take note of and select the <strong>Threat quarantined</strong> item.</p> </li> <li> <p>Read the information about the threat and then select the <strong>Actions</strong> button and then select <strong>Remove</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close all open windows.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-5-configure-exclusions">Task 5: Configure exclusions</h3> <ol> <li> <p>From the taskbar, open <strong>File Explorer</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Browse to <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">&bsol;&bsol;LON-DC1&bsol;Labfiles&bsol;Threat</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Copy the <strong>sample.txt</strong> file and paste it to <strong>C:&bsol;Files</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close File Explorer.</p> <blockquote> <p>The above task has replaced the sample virus file in the C:&bsol;Files folder. You will now configure an exclusion for the C:&bsol;Files folder and validate the behavior of the virus scan.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong>, and then select the <strong>Settings</strong> icon.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Settings window, select <strong>Update &amp; Security</strong>, and then select <strong>Windows Security</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Open Windows Security</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In Windows Security, select <strong>Virus &amp; threat protection</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Virus &amp; threat protection page, under Virus &amp; threat protection settings, select <strong>Manage settings</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under Exclusions, select <strong>Add or remove exclusions</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Exclusions page, select <strong>Add an exclusion</strong> and then select <strong>Folder</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Browse to <strong>C:&bsol;Files</strong> and then click <strong>Select Folder</strong>. The excluded folder is shown on the Exclusions page.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close <strong>Windows Security</strong> and then close <strong>Settings</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-6-validate-the-excluded-folder">Task 6: Validate the excluded folder</h3> <ol> <li> <p>On the task bar, select the <strong>File Explorer</strong> icon.</p> </li> <li> <p>In <strong>File Explorer</strong> browse to <strong>C:&bsol;Files</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Files folder, double-click <strong>sample.txt</strong>. </p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: The sample.txt file contains a text string to test malware detection.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>In the sample.txt file, <strong>delete</strong> both instances of <strong>remove</strong> including the brackets and any extra lines or blank spaces.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Save</strong> and close Notepad.</p> <blockquote> <p>Notice that you do not receive any notification from Microsoft Defender. Because this folder is excluded, it will not be protected by the antivirus process.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>Close all open windows.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise, you will have configured and tested Microsoft Defender Antivirus.</p> <h2 id="exercise-2-configuring-windows-security-settings">Exercise 2: Configuring Windows Security Settings</h2> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>You need to verify that Microsoft Defender SmartScreen has been enabled and is configured on LON-CL1. You also need to verify that Exploit Protection settings are On by default.</p> <h3 id="task-1-configure-windows-security">Task 1: Configure Windows Security</h3> <ol> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>, select <strong>Start</strong>, and then select the <strong>Settings</strong> icon.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Settings window, select <strong>Update &amp; Security</strong>, and then select <strong>Windows Security</strong>. </p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Open Windows Security</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In Windows Security, select <strong>App &amp; browser control</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the App &amp; browser control page, under Reputation-based protection, select <strong>Reputation-based protection settings</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Verify that Microsoft Defender SmartScreen has been enabled for apps, files, Microsoft Edge, and Microsoft Store apps.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under Potentially unwanted app blocking, select the check box to enable <strong>Block downloads</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Click <strong>Back</strong> to return to the App &amp; browser control page.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under Exploit protection, select <strong>Exploit protection settings</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Verify that System settings are all configured to <strong>Use default (On)</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close the Windows Security window.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of LON-CL1.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise, you will have verified settings related to Microsoft Defender SmartScreen and Exploit protection.</p> <p><strong>END OF LAB</strong></p> </div> <div class="page" id="page22"> <h1 id="practice-lab-configuring-firewall-and-connection-security">Practice Lab 22: Configuring Firewall and Connection Security</h1> <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2> <p>In this exercise you will create and configure firewall rules to block and allow specific service connections to a device. You will also create and configure connection security rules to encrypt network traffic between Windows devices.</p> <h2 id="exercise-1-creating-and-testing-inbound-firewall-rules">Exercise 1: Creating and Testing Inbound Firewall Rules</h2> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>Users that work on LON-CL2 are not allowed to remote desktop into LON-CL1. You need to verify that remote desktop currently is allowed and then configure a firewall rule on LON-CL1 that will block remote desktop connections. You will leave the Remote desktop service enabled to allow for other device connections to be configured at a later time.</p> <h3 id="task-1-validate-existing-functionality">Task 1: Validate existing functionality</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click Start and then select <strong>System</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the System page, select <strong>Advanced system settings</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the System Properties box, select the <strong>Remote</strong> tab.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Remote Desktop section, select <strong>Allow remote connections to this computer</strong> and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close the <strong>Settings</strong> window.</p> </li> <li> <p>Switch to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(3)&quot;).click()">LON-CL2</a></strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(3)&quot;).click()">LON-CL2</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong>, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">mstsc.exe</strong>, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>. The Remote Desktop Connection app opens.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Computer box, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">LON-CL1</strong>, and then select <strong>Connect</strong>. The Windows Security dialog box displays asking for credentials to connect to LON-CL1. This indicates successful connectivity to LON-CL1.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Windows Security dialog, select <strong>Cancel</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-create-an-inbound-rule">Task 2: Create an inbound rule</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Switch to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>, select <strong>Start</strong>, and type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Windows Firewall</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the results pane, select <strong>Windows Defender Firewall</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In Windows Defender Firewall, in the left pane, select <strong>Advanced settings</strong>, select <strong>Inbound Rules</strong>, and then select <strong>New Rule</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the New Inbound Rule Wizard window, select <strong>Predefined</strong>, select the <strong>drop-down list</strong>, select <strong>Remote Desktop</strong>, and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Predefined Rules page, select the check box next to all available rules, and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Action page, select <strong>Block the connection</strong>, and then select <strong>Finish</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Minimize the Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security window.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-3-test-the-rule">Task 3: Test the rule</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Switch to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(3)&quot;).click()">LON-CL2</a></strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>If necessary, select <strong>Start</strong>, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">mstsc.exe</strong>, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Computer box, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">LON-CL1</strong>, and then select <strong>Connect</strong>. Notice that the connection attempt fails and displays a Remote Desktop Connection error message.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Remote Desktop Connection error message window, select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close all open windows.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise, you will have created and verified inbound firewall rules.</p> <h2 id="exercise-2-creating-and-testing-outbound-firewall-rules">Exercise 2: Creating and Testing Outbound Firewall Rules</h2> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>LON-DC1 also needs to be configured to allow remote desktop connections, however LON-CL1&#39;s firewall configuration should not allow any user to use a remote desktop connection to LON-DC1 from LON-CL1. You will configure an outbound firewall rule on LON-CL1 to prevent remote desktop connections to the server.</p> <h3 id="task-1-test-existing-functionality">Task 1: Test existing functionality</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Switch to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(1)&quot;).click()">LON-DC1</a></strong> and sign in as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong></p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong>, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">control</strong>, and then select <strong>Control Panel</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Control Panel, select <strong>System and Security</strong>, and then under <strong>System</strong>, select <strong>Allow remote access</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Remote</strong> tab, under <strong>Remote Desktop</strong>, verify that <strong>Allow remote connections to this computer</strong> is selected.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>OK</strong> to close the <strong>System Properties</strong> window and then close the Control Panel.</p> </li> <li> <p>Switch to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong>, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">mstsc.exe</strong>, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Computer box, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">LON-DC1</strong>, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>. The Windows Security dialog box displays asking for credentials to connect to LON-DC1. This indicates successful connectivity to LON-DC1.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Windows Security dialog, select <strong>Cancel</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close Remote Desktop Connection.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-create-an-outbound-rule">Task 2: Create an outbound rule</h3> <ol> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>, on the taskbar, select the <strong>Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security</strong> window, and then select <strong>Outbound Rules</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Actions pane, select <strong>New Rule</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Rule Type page, verify that you are creating a <strong>Program</strong> rule, and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Program page, browse and select <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">C:&bsol;Windows&bsol;System32&bsol;mstsc.exe</strong>, select <strong>Open</strong>, and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Action page, verify that the action is <strong>Block the Connection</strong>, and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Profile page, verify that <strong>all profiles are checked</strong>, and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Name page, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Block Outbound RDP to LON-DC1</strong> in the Name box, and then select <strong>Finish</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security window, select the <strong>Block Outbound RDP to LON-DC1</strong> rule, and then in the Actions pane, select <strong>Properties</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select the <strong>Scope tab</strong>, and then under the <strong>Remote IP address heading</strong>, select the <strong>These IP addresses</strong> option.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under the Remote IP address heading, select <strong>Add</strong>, in the This IP address or subnet box, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">172.16.0.10</strong>, and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Block Outbound RDP to LON-DC1 Properties dialog box, select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-3-test-the-rule">Task 3: Test the rule</h3> <ol> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>, select <strong>Start</strong>, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">mstsc.exe</strong>, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Computer box, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">LON-DC1</strong>, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>. Notice that the connection attempt fails and displays a Remote Desktop Connection error message.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Remote Desktop Connection dialog box, select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p><strong>Close</strong> all open windows.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise, you will have created and tested outbound firewall rules.</p> <h2 id="exercise-3-creating-connection-security-rules">Exercise 3: Creating Connection Security Rules</h2> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>Your manager wants you to ensure that all network traffic between LON-CL1 and LON-CL2 is encrypted. You need to configure a connection security rule with the setting &quot;Require authentication for inbound connections and request authentication for outbound connections&quot; enabled on both devices.</p> <h3 id="task-1-verify-that-communications-are-not-secure">Task 1: Verify that communications are not secure</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(3)&quot;).click()">LON-CL2</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click <strong>Start</strong>, and then select <strong>Windows Terminal (Admin)</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Windows PowerShell window, type the following command and then press <strong>Enter</strong></p> </li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-built_in">ping</span> LON-CL1</code> </pre> <ol> <li> <p>Verify that the ping generated four Reply messages.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong>, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">firewall</strong> and select <strong>Windows Defender Firewall</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the left pane, select <strong>Advanced settings</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the left pane, expand <strong>Monitoring,</strong> and then expand <strong>Security Associations</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Main Mode</strong>, and then examine the information in the center pane.</p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: No information should be present.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Quick Mode</strong>, and then examine the information in the center pane. </p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: No information should be present.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>Switch to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>. If necessary, sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click <strong>Start</strong>, and then select <strong>Windows Terminal (Admin)</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>To examine the Main Mode Security Associations (SAs), at the Windows PowerShell prompt, type the following cmdlet, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>:</p> </li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-attribute">Get-NetIPsecMainModeSA</span></code> </pre> <ol> <li>To examine the Quick Mode SAs, at the Windows PowerShell prompt, type the following cmdlet, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>:</li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-attribute">Get-NetIPsecQuickModeSA</span></code> </pre> <p><strong>Note</strong>: Running each command should produce no result.</p> <h3 id="task-2-create-the-connection-security-rule">Task 2: Create the Connection Security Rule</h3> <ol> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>, select <strong>Start</strong>, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">firewall</strong> and select <strong>Windows Defender Firewall</strong>. </p> </li> <li> <p>In the left pane, select <strong>Advanced settings</strong>, and then select <strong>Connection Security Rules</strong>. </p> </li> <li> <p>In the Actions pane, select <strong>New Rule</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Rule Type page, verify that <strong>Isolation</strong> is selected, and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Requirements page, select <strong>Require authentication for inbound connections and request authentication for outbound connections</strong>, and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Authentication Method page, select <strong>Computer and user (Kerberos V5)</strong>, and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Profile page, select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Name page, in the Name text box, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Authenticate all inbound connections</strong>, and then select <strong>Finish</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close the Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security window.</p> </li> <li> <p>Switch to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(3)&quot;).click()">LON-CL2</a></strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security window, in the left pane select <strong>Connection Security Rules</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Actions pane, select <strong>New Rule</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Rule Type page, verify that <strong>Isolation is selected</strong>, and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Requirements page, select <strong>Require authentication for inbound connections and request authentication for outbound connections</strong>, and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Authentication Method page, select <strong>Computer and user (Kerberos V5)</strong>, and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Profile page, select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Name page, in the Name text box, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Authenticate all inbound connections</strong>, and then select <strong>Finish</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-3-verify-the-rule-and-monitor-the-connection">Task 3: Verify the rule, and monitor the connection</h3> <ol> <li>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(3)&quot;).click()">LON-CL2</a></strong>, in the Windows PowerShell window, type the following command and then press <strong>Enter</strong></li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-built_in">ping</span> LON-CL1</code> </pre> <ol> <li> <p>Verify that the ping generated four reply messages.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security window, in the left pane expand <strong>Monitoring,</strong> and then expand <strong>Security Associations</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Main Mode</strong>, and then examine the information in the center pane.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Quick Mode</strong>, and then examine the information in the center pane.</p> </li> <li> <p><strong>Close</strong> all open windows.</p> </li> <li> <p>Switch to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>To examine the Main Mode Security Associations (SAs), at the Windows PowerShell command prompt, type the following cmdlet, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>:</p> </li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-attribute">Get-NetIPsecMainModeSA</span></code> </pre> <ol> <li> <p>Review the result.</p> </li> <li> <p>To examine the Quick Mode SAs, at the command prompt, type the following cmdlet, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>:</p> </li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-attribute">Get-NetIPsecQuickModeSA</span></code> </pre> <ol> <li> <p>Review the result and then close all open windows.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of LON-CL1 and LON-CL2.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise, you will have created and tested connection security rules.</p> <p><strong>END OF LAB</strong></p> </div> <div class="page" id="page23"> <h1 id="practice-lab-configuring-and-troubleshooting-bitlocker">Practice Lab 23: Configuring and Troubleshooting BitLocker</h1> <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2> <p>In this lab you encrypt a local disk drive using BitLocker. You also troubleshoot access to a BitLocker encrypted drive when the user has forgot the password to unlock the drive.</p> <h2 id="exercise-1-configuring-bitlocker">Exercise 1: Configuring BitLocker</h2> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>You have a Windows 10 computer that has sensitive data stored on the E drive. You decide to configure and test BitLocker to see how it can be used to protect the data files that are stored on the local drive (E:).</p> <h3 id="task-1-configure-active-directory-group-policy-settings-to-support-bitlocker">Task 1: Configure Active Directory Group Policy settings to support BitLocker</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(1)&quot;).click()">LON-DC1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>From Server Manager, select <strong>Tools</strong> and then select <strong>Group Policy Management</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Expand <strong>Forest:Adatum.com</strong>, and then expand <strong>Domains</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click <strong>Adatum.com</strong> and then select <strong>Create a GPO in this domain, and Link it here.</strong></p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>New GPO</strong> box, under <strong>Name</strong> enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">BitLocker Policy</strong> and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Expand <strong>Adatum.com</strong>, right-click <strong>BitLocker Policy</strong>, and then select <strong>Edit</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Group Policy Management Editor, under <strong>Computer Configuration</strong>, expand <strong>Policies</strong>, expand <strong>Administrative Templates</strong>, expand <strong>Windows Components</strong>, and then select <strong>BitLocker Drive Encryption</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the navigation area, expand <strong>BitLocker Drive Encryption</strong> and then select <strong>Fixed Data Drives</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Double-click <strong>Choose how BitLocker-protected fixed drives can be recovered</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Enabled</strong>, and then ensure that the check box next to <strong>Save BitLocker recovery information to AD DS for fixed data drives</strong> is selected, and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the navigation area, expand <strong>BitLocker Drive Encryption</strong> and then select <strong>Operating System Drives</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Double-click <strong>Choose how BitLocker-protected operating system drives can be recovered</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Enabled</strong>, and then ensure that the check box next to <strong>Save BitLocker recovery information to AD DS for operating system drives</strong> is selected, and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the navigation area, expand <strong>BitLocker Drive Encryption</strong> and then select <strong>Removable Data Drives</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Double-click <strong>Choose how BitLocker-protected removable drives can be recovered</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Enabled</strong>, and then ensure that the check box next to <strong>Save BitLocker recovery information to AD DS for removable data drives</strong> is selected, and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close the <strong>Group Policy Management Editor</strong> and the <strong>Group Policy Management</strong> console.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-enable-bitlocker">Task 2: Enable BitLocker</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Switch to and then restart <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password of <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the taskbar, select the <strong>File Explorer</strong> icon.</p> </li> <li> <p>In File Explorer, in the navigation pane, expand <strong>This PC</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the navigation pane, right-click <strong>Allfiles (E:)</strong>, and then select <strong>Turn on BitLocker</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>BitLocker Drive Encryption (E:)</strong> dialog box, select <strong>Use a password to unlock the drive</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Enter your password</strong> and <strong>Reenter your password</strong> boxes, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>, and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>How do you want to back up your recovery key?</strong> page, select <strong>Save to a file</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Save BitLocker recovery key as</strong> dialog box, select <strong>Documents</strong> and then select <strong>Save</strong>. Select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Choose how much of your drive to encrypt</strong> page, ensure that <strong>Encrypt used disk space only (faster and best for new PCs and drives)</strong> is selected, and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Choose which encryption mode to use</strong> page, ensure that <strong>New encryption mode (best for fixed drives on this device)</strong> is selected, and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>BitLocker Drive Encryption (E:)</strong> page, select <strong>Start encrypting</strong>. Notice the lock icon next to the Allfiles (E:) node in the navigation bar, which indicates that the drive is currently unlocked.</p> </li> <li> <p>Restart LON-CL1.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-3-verify-bitlocker">Task 3: Verify BitLocker</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select the <strong>File Explorer</strong> icon on the taskbar.</p> </li> <li> <p>In File Explorer in the navigation pane expand <strong>This PC</strong>, and select <strong>Local Disk (E:)</strong>. Notice the lock icon next to Local Disk (E:). This indicates that the drive is protected by BitLocker.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the BitLocker (E:) window, enter the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>, press Enter to unlock the drive, and then verify access to the drive contents.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click <strong>Allfiles (E:)</strong>, select <strong>Manage BitLocker</strong>. Take note of the options available for managing BitLocker on Allfiles (E:).</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Turn off BitLocker</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the BitLocker Drive Encryption dialog box, select <strong>Turn off BitLocker</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close the BitLocker Drive Encryption window.</p> </li> <li> <p>In File Explorer, notice that that lock icon is no longer visible next to Allfiles (E:).</p> </li> <li> <p>Close all open windows and sign out of LON-CL1.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise, you will have configured BitLocker to encrypt a local disk drive.</p> <h2 id="exercise-2-troubleshooting-bitlocker">Exercise 2: Troubleshooting BitLocker</h2> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>Jon has a Windows 10 computer that has sensitive data stored on the E drive. He has enabled BitLocker on drive E but has forgot the password to access the data. You need to determine how to access the recovery key and use it to unlock access to the drive content.</p> <h3 id="task-1-enable-bitlocker">Task 1: Enable BitLocker</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Jon</strong> with the password of <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the taskbar, select the <strong>File Explorer</strong> icon.</p> </li> <li> <p>In File Explorer, in the navigation pane, expand <strong>This PC</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the navigation pane, right-click <strong>Allfiles (E:)</strong>, and then select <strong>Turn on BitLocker</strong>. At the User Account Control, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Administrator</strong> with the password of <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>BitLocker Drive Encryption (E:)</strong> dialog box, select <strong>Use a password to unlock the drive</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Enter your password</strong> and <strong>Reenter your password</strong> boxes, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>, and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>How do you want to back up your recovery key?</strong> page, select <strong>Save to a file</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Save BitLocker recovery key as</strong> dialog box, select <strong>Downloads</strong> and then select <strong>Save</strong>. Select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Choose how much of your drive to encrypt</strong> page, ensure that <strong>Encrypt used disk space only (faster and best for new PCs and drives)</strong> is selected, and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Choose which encryption mode to use</strong> page, ensure that <strong>New encryption mode (best for fixed drives on this device)</strong> is selected, and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>BitLocker Drive Encryption (E:)</strong> page, select <strong>Start encrypting</strong>. </p> </li> <li> <p>Restart LON-CL1.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-troubleshoot-bitlocker">Task 2: Troubleshoot BitLocker</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Jon&#39;s computer has the E: drive encrypted with BitLocker. He has returned from vacation and cannot remember the password to unlock and access the E drive. He needs to be able to access the files. You need to identify how to gain access to the locked drive and then change the password to one that he will remember. Attempt to resolve the problem by using your knowledge of BitLocker. If you are unable to resolve the problem, escalate it by asking your instructor for additional guidance. The following steps provide the troubleshooting steps and solution to the issue.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select the <strong>File Explorer</strong> icon on the taskbar.</p> </li> <li> <p>In File Explorer in the navigation pane expand <strong>This PC</strong>, and select <strong>Local Disk (E:)</strong>. </p> </li> <li> <p>In the BitLocker (E:) window, enter the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">password123</strong>, and then select <strong>Unlock</strong>. You receive a message that the password is incorrect.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the BitLocker (E:) box, select <strong>More options</strong>.</p> <blockquote> <p>Take note of the <strong>Enter recovery key</strong> link. Where can you find a copy of the recovery key? Hint: Group policy settings were configured to ensure you can have access to the recovery key.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>Switch to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(1)&quot;).click()">LON-DC1</a></strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>From Server Manager, select <strong>Tools</strong>, and then select <strong>Active Directory Users and Computers</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In Active Directory Users and Computers, expand <strong>Adatum.com</strong> and then select the <strong>Seattle Clients</strong> Organizational Unit.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click LON-CL1 and then select <strong>Properties</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the LON-CL1 Properties box, select the <strong>BitLocker Recovery</strong> tab.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click the most recent BitLocker Recovery Password, and then select <strong>Copy Details</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the taskbar, open <strong>File Explorer</strong> and then browse to <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">&bsol;&bsol;LON-CL1&bsol;C$</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Create a new text document and paste the BitLocker details into the document. Save the document.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close all open windows and then sign out of LON-DC1.</p> </li> <li> <p>Switch to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In File Explorer, select <strong>Local Disk (C:)</strong> and then open the text document that contains the Recovery password.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under Recovery Password, arrange the 48 numbers to ensure that the password is on a single line.</p> </li> <li> <p>Copy the 48 number recovery password.</p> </li> <li> <p>Switch to File Explorer and then select <strong>Allfiles (E:)</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the BitLocker (E:) box, select <strong>More options</strong> and then select <strong>Enter recovery key</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Paste the recovery key and then select <strong>Unlock</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Browse to E: Drive and verify that you can access the files.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click <strong>Allfiles (E:)</strong>, select <strong>Change BitLocker password</strong>. </p> </li> <li> <p>On the BitLocker Drive Encryption box, select <strong>Reset a forgotten password</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the BitLocker Drive Encryption box, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong> for both the Enter your password and Reenter your password fields.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Finish</strong> and then select <strong>OK</strong>. The drive has now been recovered and you have reset the password.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-3-turn-off-bitlocker">Task 3: Turn off BitLocker</h3> <ol> <li> <p>In File Explorer in the navigation pane expand <strong>This PC</strong>, and select <strong>Allfiles (E:)</strong>. </p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click <strong>Allfiles (E:)</strong>, select <strong>Manage BitLocker</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Turn off BitLocker</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the BitLocker Drive Encryption dialog box, select <strong>Turn off BitLocker</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close the BitLocker Drive Encryption window.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close all open windows and sign out of LON-CL1.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise, you will have configured BitLocker and recovered access using a recovery key.</p> <p><strong>END OF LAB</strong></p> </div> <div class="page" id="page24"> <h1 id="practice-lab-monitoring-events-using-event-viewer">Practice Lab 24: Monitoring Events using Event Viewer</h1> <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2> <p>In this lab, you manage Windows event logs and configure Event log subscriptions.</p> <h2 id="exercise-1-manage-windows-event-logs">Exercise 1: Manage Windows Event Logs</h2> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>You need to identify and review any system errors reported on LON-CL1. You will use Event Viewer to review the event log entries for the Application, Security, and System logs, and filter out the Warning and Error events. You will then configure the Maximum log size for the Application and System event logs. Finally, you will configure the Security event log to Archive the log when full and do not overwrite events.</p> <h3 id="task-1-review-event-log-entries">Task 1: Review Event Log entries</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password: <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong>, and then type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Event Viewer</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the search results, select the <strong>Event Viewer</strong> app. The Event Viewer opens.</p> </li> <li> <p>Maximize the Event Viewer window.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under Event Viewer (Local), expand <strong>Windows Logs</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under Windows Logs, select <strong>Application</strong> and then scroll through the reported events. Take note of the various events listed for the Application log. You may have a combination of Information, Warning, and Error events.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under Windows Logs, select <strong>Security</strong> and then scroll through the reported events. Take note of the events listed for the Security log. Most of these events are security related based upon Microsoft Windows security auditing.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under Windows Logs, select <strong>System</strong> and then scroll through the reported events. Take note of the various events listed for the System log. You may have a combination of Information, Warning, and Error events related to internal Windows system services.</p> </li> <li> <p>With the <strong>System</strong> log selected, in the Actions pane select <strong>Filter Current Log</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Filter Current Log dialog box, on the Filter tab, next to Event level, select the check box next to <strong>Warning</strong> and select the check box next to <strong>Error</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>OK</strong> to return to the System log events. Notice that only Warning and Error events are now displayed, since you have filtered out the Information events.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Actions pane, select <strong>Clear Filter</strong>. All System events are now displayed.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select the <strong>Application</strong> log, and then in the Actions pane select <strong>Filter Current Log</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Filter Current Log dialog box, on the Filter tab, next to Event level, select the check box next to <strong>Warning</strong> and select the check box next to <strong>Error</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>OK</strong> to return to the Application log events. Review the filtered events.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Actions pane, select <strong>Clear Filter</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the navigation pane, expand <strong>Applications and Services Logs</strong>. These logs relate to specific services or applications installed on the local machine.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under Applications and Services Logs, expand <strong>Microsoft</strong>, and then expand <strong>Windows</strong>. Notice the variety of log information related to Windows features and services.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under the Windows node, expand <strong>GroupPolicy</strong> and then select the <strong>Operational</strong> log. Take note of the various events listed for the Group Policy Operational log. You may have a combination of Information, Warning, and Error events related to Group Policy processing for the local machine.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the navigation pane, close the <strong>Applications and Services Logs</strong> branch.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-configure-event-log-properties">Task 2: Configure Event Log Properties</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Under Windows Logs, select <strong>Application</strong> and then in the Actions pane, select <strong>Properties</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Log Properties - Application dialog box, on the General tab, change the <strong>Maximum log size (KB)</strong> to <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">2048</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the General tab, select <strong>Clear log</strong> and then in the Event Viewer prompt select <strong>Clear</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>OK</strong> to close the Log Properties - Application dialog box.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under Windows Logs, select <strong>Security</strong> and then in the Actions pane, select <strong>Properties</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Log Properties - Security dialog box, on the General tab, change the <strong>Maximum log size (KB)</strong> to <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">30464</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under When maximum event log size is reached, select <strong>Archive the log when full, do not overwrite events</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>OK</strong> to close the Log Properties - Security dialog box.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close the Event Viewer.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise, you will have successfully reviewed event log entries and configured property settings for event logs.</p> <h2 id="exercise-2-configure-and-manage-event-subscriptions">Exercise 2: Configure and Manage Event Subscriptions</h2> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>LON-CL2 is a critical workstation that needs to be monitored and maintained on a regular basis. To efficiently monitor LON-CL2, you decide to collect its event log entries so that you can review them on your workstation named LON-CL1. To perform this task, you need to assign permissions on LON-CL2. You will then create a &quot;Collector Initiated&quot; event log subscription on your workstation that connects to LON-CL2 and collects the last 30 days of event log entries.</p> <h3 id="task-1-configure-event-log-subscriptions">Task 1: Configure Event Log Subscriptions</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(3)&quot;).click()">LON-CL2</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click <strong>Start</strong>, and then select <strong>Windows Terminal (Admin)</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the PowerShell command prompt, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>:</p> </li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-attribute">winrm quickconfig</span></code> </pre> <ol> <li> <p>At the PowerShell command type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Y</strong> when prompted. You will be prompted to configure the WinRM service and the WinRM firewall exception.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close Windows PowerShell.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click <strong>Start</strong>, and then select <strong>Computer Management</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Expand <strong>System Tools</strong>, expand <strong>Local Users and Groups</strong>, and then select <strong>Groups</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the results pane, double-click <strong>Event Log Readers</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Event Log Readers Properties</strong> dialog box, select <strong>Add</strong>, and then in the <strong>Select Users, Computers, Service Accounts, or Groups</strong> dialog box, select <strong>Object Types</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Object Types</strong> dialog box, select the <strong>Computers</strong> check box, and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Select Users, Computers, Service Accounts, or Groups</strong> dialog box, in the <strong>Enter the object names to select (examples)</strong> box, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">LON-CL1</strong>, and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Event Log Readers Properties</strong> dialog box, select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close the <strong>Computer Management</strong> window.</p> </li> <li> <p>Switch to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> and, if necessary, sign in as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click <strong>Start</strong>, and then select <strong>Windows Terminal (Admin)</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the PowerShell command prompt, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>:</p> </li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-attribute">wecutil qc</span></code> </pre> <ol> <li> <p>When prompted, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Y</strong>, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close the Windows PowerShell window.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-view-and-filter-events">Task 2: View and filter events</h3> <ol> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>, right-click <strong>Start</strong>, and then select <strong>Event Viewer</strong>. Maximize the Event Viewer window.</p> </li> <li> <p>In <strong>Event Viewer</strong>, in the navigation pane, select <strong>Subscriptions</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click <strong>Subscriptions</strong>, and then select <strong>Create Subscription</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Subscription Properties</strong> dialog box, in the <strong>Subscription name</strong> box, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">LON-CL2 Events</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Collector Initiated</strong>, and then select <strong>Select Computers</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Computers</strong> dialog box, select <strong>Add Domain Computers</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Select Computer</strong> dialog box, in the <strong>Enter the object name to select (examples)</strong> box, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">LON-CL2</strong>, and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Computers</strong> dialog box, select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Subscription Properties – LON-CL2 Events</strong> dialog box, select <strong>Select Events</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Query Filter</strong> dialog box, select the <strong>Critical</strong>, <strong>Warning</strong>, <strong>Error</strong>, <strong>Information</strong>, and <strong>Verbose</strong> Event level check boxes.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Logged</strong> dropdown list, select <strong>Last 30 days</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Event logs</strong> dropdown list, select <strong>Windows Logs</strong>, and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Subscription Properties – LON-CL2 Events</strong> dialog box, select <strong>OK</strong>. A subscription entry named LON-CL2 events displays with a green circle and white check mark. This indicates that the subscription is active.</p> </li> <li> <p>In <strong>Event Viewer</strong>, in the navigation pane, expand <strong>Windows Logs</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Forwarded Events</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click <strong>Forwarded Events</strong>, and then select <strong>Create Custom View</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Create Custom View</strong> dialog box, select the <strong>Critical</strong> and <strong>Error</strong> check boxes, and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Save Filter to Custom View</strong> dialog box, in the <strong>Name</strong> box, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">LON-CL2 errors</strong>, and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Examine any listed events. The list may be empty.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close all open windows and then sign out of LON-CL1.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise, you will have successfully configured Event subscriptions by using Event Viewer.</p> <p><strong>END OF LAB</strong></p> </div> <div class="page" id="page25"> <h1 id="practice-lab-monitoring-reliability-and-performance">Practice Lab 25: Monitoring Reliability and Performance</h1> <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2> <p>In this lab, you use Task Manager and Reliability Monitor to review Windows client reliability and performance. You will also configure and use Performance Monitor to identify performance issues for a Windows device.</p> <h2 id="exercise-1-review-windows-performance-using-task-manager-and-reliability-monitor">Exercise 1: Review Windows performance using Task Manager and Reliability Monitor</h2> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>A user reports performance issues with a client workstation named LON-CL1. Your first step is to review the Task Manager and Reliability Monitor on LON-CL1 to identify any noticeable or consistent issues that may be reported on the computer.</p> <h3 id="task-1-use-task-manager-to-review-performance">Task 1: Use Task Manager to review performance</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password: <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click <strong>Start</strong> and then select <strong>Task Manager</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Task Manager window, select <strong>More details</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Task Manager window, on the Processes tab, review the running processes.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the taskbar, select <strong>Start</strong>, and then on the Start menu select <strong>Paint 3D</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Minimize the <strong>Paint 3D</strong> window and then switch to the <strong>Task Manager</strong>. Take note of the <strong>Paint 3D</strong> process. Also take note of the CPU and Memory used by the application.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Task Manager, select the <strong>Performance</strong> tab. Take note of the real-time performance of the CPU, Memory and Disk resources.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Task Manager, select the <strong>App history</strong> tab. Take note of the resource usage and then select <strong>Delete usage history</strong> to reset the counters.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Task Manager, select the <strong>Startup</strong> tab. Take note of the apps that start up when Windows starts. This will help you identify if any startup apps may be contributing to the performance issues on LON-CL1.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Task Manager, select the <strong>Details</strong> tab. Take note of the specific executables running on the machine. This will allow you to identify CPU and Memory usage for specific executables. Which apps have a high impact to startup?</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Task Manager, select the <strong>Services</strong> tab. Take note of the services that are running and stopped. You can use this view to Start, Stop, and Restart services as needed.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Task Manager, select the <strong>Processes</strong> tab.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under Apps, right-click <strong>Paint 3D</strong> and then select <strong>End task</strong>. This will end the process and force the app to close.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close Task Manager.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-review-reliability-history-using-reliability-monitor">Task 2: Review reliability history using Reliability Monitor</h3> <ol> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>, on the taskbar, select <strong>Start</strong>, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">reliability</strong>, and then select <strong>View reliability history.</strong> The <strong>Reliability Monitor</strong> opens.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Reliability Monitor window, select any date that contains an information or warning notification.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Reliability details section, next to a Warning or Informational event, select <strong>View technical details</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Review the details and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close the Reliability Monitor.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of LON-CL1.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise, you will have successfully reviewed performance and reliability history using the Task Manager and Reliability Monitor.</p> <h2 id="exercise-2-monitor-windows-10-using-performance-monitor">Exercise 2: Monitor Windows 10 using Performance Monitor</h2> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>You need to use Performance Monitor to identify performance bottlenecks on the Windows 10 workstation named LON-CL1. You have developed a script named MonitorScenario.vbs that will simulate and provoke the decreased performance on LON-CL1. While the script runs you plan to monitor the values for Network Interface Packets per second, PhysicalDisk % Disk Time, PhysicalDisk Avg. Disk Queue Length, Processor % Processor Time and System Processor Queue Length.</p> <h3 id="task-1-use-performance-monitor-to-gather-a-baseline">Task 1: Use Performance Monitor to gather a baseline</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password: <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong>, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">performance</strong>, and then select <strong>Performance Monitor</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In <strong>Performance Monitor</strong>, in the navigation pane, expand <strong>Data Collector Sets</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>User Defined</strong>, right-click <strong>User Defined</strong>, point to <strong>New</strong>, and then select <strong>Data Collector Set</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Create new Data Collector Set</strong> wizard, on the <strong>How would you like to create this new data collector set?</strong> page, in the <strong>Name</strong> text box, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">LON-CL1 Baseline</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Create manually (Advanced)</strong>, and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>What type of data do you want to include?</strong> page, select the <strong>Performance counter</strong> check box, and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Which performance counters would you like to log?</strong> page, in the <strong>Sample interval</strong> field, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">1</strong>, and then select <strong>Add</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Available counters</strong> list, expand <strong>Network Interface</strong>, select <strong>Packets/sec</strong>, and then select <strong>Add</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Available counters</strong> list, expand <strong>PhysicalDisk</strong>, select <strong>% Disk Time</strong>, and then select <strong>Add</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under <strong>PhysicalDisk</strong>, select <strong>Avg. Disk Queue Length</strong>, and then select <strong>Add</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Available counters</strong> list, expand <strong>Processor</strong>, select <strong>% Processor Time</strong>, and then select <strong>Add</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Available counters</strong> list, expand <strong>System</strong>, select <strong>Processor Queue Length</strong>, select <strong>Add</strong>, and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Which performance counters would you like to log?</strong> page, select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Where would you like the data to be saved?</strong> page, select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Create the data collector set?</strong> page, select <strong>Finish</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In <strong>Performance Monitor</strong>, in the details pane, right-click <strong>LON-CL1 Baseline</strong>, and then select <strong>Start</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong>, and then select <strong>Paint 3D</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close Paint 3D app, and then switch to <strong>Performance Monitor</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the navigation pane, right-click <strong>LON-CL1 Baseline</strong>, and then select <strong>Stop</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In <strong>Performance Monitor</strong>, in the navigation pane, expand <strong>Reports</strong>, expand <strong>User Defined</strong>, expand <strong>LON-CL1 Baseline</strong>, and then select the report that has a name beginning with <strong>LON-CL1</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>View the chart. On the menu bar, select the drop-down arrow, and then select <strong>Report</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Record the following values:</p> <ul> <li> <p>Network Interface Packets per second</p> </li> <li> <p>PhysicalDisk % Disk Time</p> </li> <li> <p>PhysicalDisk Avg. Disk Queue Length</p> </li> <li> <p>Processor % Processor Time</p> </li> <li> <p>System Processor Queue Length</p> </li> </ul> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-simulate-load-using-the-load-generator-script">Task 2: Simulate load using the load generator script</h3> <ol> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>, open File Explorer, and browse to <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">&bsol;&bsol;LON-DC1&bsol;labfiles&bsol;Support&bsol;</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the content pane, double-click <strong>CopyMonitor.bat</strong> to copy lab files to the local client.</p> </li> <li> <p>Click Start, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">cmd</strong>. In the results pane, under <strong>Command Prompt</strong>, select <strong>Run as administrator</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: The following step initiates a script which generates a resource load. Be sure to continue on to Task 3 <strong>immediately</strong>, before the script completes.</em></p> <ol> <li>In the Command Prompt Window, type each of the following commands and press <strong>Enter</strong>:</li> </ol> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-built_in">cd</span>&bsol;Monitor</code> </pre> <pre> <code>MonitorScenario.vbs</code> </pre> <h3 id="task-3-use-performance-monitor-to-identify-possible-bottlenecks">Task 3: Use Performance Monitor to identify possible bottlenecks</h3> <ol> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>, switch to <strong>Performance Monitor</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under <strong>Data Collector Sets</strong>, select <strong>User Defined</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click <strong>LON-CL1 Baseline</strong>, and then select <strong>Start</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In Performance Monitor, select <strong>Performance</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Open Resource Monitor</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In <strong>Resource Monitor</strong>, which components are under strain?</p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: Answers will vary depending upon the usage scenario and host configuration, although Disk and Network are likely to be used heavily.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>After a few minutes, in the <strong>Windows Script Host</strong> prompt, select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: Check the taskbar to see if this dialog may be hidden.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>Wait for the instance of the Command Prompt windows launched by the script to close.</p> </li> <li> <p>Switch to <strong>Performance Monitor</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the navigation pane, right-click <strong>LON-CL1 Baseline</strong>, and then select <strong>Stop</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In <strong>Performance Monitor</strong>, in the navigation pane, expand <strong>Reports</strong>, expand <strong>User Defined</strong>, expand <strong>LON-CL1 Baseline</strong>, and then select the <strong>second report</strong> that has a name beginning with <strong>LON-CL1</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>View the chart.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the menu bar, select the drop-down arrow, and then select <strong>Report</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Record the component details:</p> <ul> <li> <p>Network Interface Packets per second</p> </li> <li> <p>PhysicalDisk % Disk Time</p> </li> <li> <p>PhysicalDisk Avg. Disk Queue Length</p> </li> <li> <p>Processor % Processor Time</p> </li> <li> <p>System Processor Queue Length</p> </li> </ul> </li> <li> <p>In your opinion, which components is the script affecting the most?</p> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: The script is affecting the Processor and Network, but it is also affecting all counters.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>Close all open windows and sign out of LON-CL1.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise, you will have successfully use Performance Monitor to determine the cause of a performance bottleneck.</p> <p><strong>END OF LAB</strong></p> </div> <div class="page" id="page26"> <h1 id="practice-lab-modifying-registry-settings-using-registry-editor">Practice Lab 26: Modifying Registry Settings Using Registry Editor</h1> <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2> <p>In this lab, you use Registry Editor to modify the Windows Registry.</p> <h2 id="exercise-1-modifying-registered-owner-and-registered-organization-information-by-using-the-registry-editor">Exercise 1: Modifying Registered Owner and Registered Organization Information by using the Registry Editor</h2> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>You have noticed that the Registered Owner and Registered Organization information on LON-CL1 is incorrect. You need to change the information to reflect Administrator as the Owner and Adatum Corp as the Organization.</p> <h3 id="task-1-review-the-current-information">Task 1: Review the current information</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password: <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong> and then type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">winver</strong> and then press Enter.</p> <blockquote> <p>Notice that the product is licensed to Student. You will use the Registry editor to change this to use Adatum references.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>OK</strong> to close the <strong>About Windows</strong> box.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-use-registry-editor-modify-windows-settings">Task 2: Use Registry Editor modify Windows settings</h3> <ol> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>, select <strong>Start</strong> and then type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">regedit</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under <strong>Registry Editor</strong>, select <strong>Run as administrator</strong>. The Registry Editor opens.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Registry Editor, expand and then select <strong>HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE&bsol;SOFTWARE&bsol;Microsoft&bsol;Windows NT&bsol;CurrentVersion</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the CurrentVersion key, double-click the <strong>RegisteredOrganization</strong> string value.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Edit String box, under Value data, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum Corp</strong> and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the CurrentVersion key, double-click the <strong>RegisteredOwner</strong> string value.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Edit String box, under Value data, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Administrator</strong> and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close the Registry Editor.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-3-validate-the-registry-change">Task 3: Validate the Registry change</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong> and then type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">winver</strong> and then press Enter.</p> <blockquote> <p>Notice that the product is now licensed to Administrator with the organization set to Adatum Corp.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>OK</strong> to close the <strong>About Windows</strong> box.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of LON-CL1.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise, you will have successfully changed the Registered Owner to Administrator and the Registered Organization as Adatum Corp.</p> <p><strong>END OF LAB</strong></p> </div> <div class="page" id="page27"> <h1 id="practice-lab-using-file-history-to-recover-files">Practice Lab 27: Using File History to Recover Files</h1> <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2> <p>In this exercise you configure File History and use it to restore previous versions of a file or folder.</p> <h2 id="exercise-1-configuring-file-history">Exercise 1: Configuring File History</h2> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>You need to ensure that users can recover deleted files stored in the Documents library on their local workstations. You decide to validate the File History feature using LON-CL1. You will first create a shared folder on LON-DC1 named FileHistory to be used as a central storage location. You will then configure the File History feature on LON-CL1 to store file history data.</p> <h3 id="task-1-create-a-shared-folder-to-store-file-history-data">Task 1: Create a shared folder to store File History data</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(1)&quot;).click()">LON-DC1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>From the taskbar, select <strong>File Explorer</strong> and in the navigation pane, select <strong>Local Disk (C:)</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In File Explorer, in the details pane, right-click an empty space, point to <strong>New</strong>, and then select <strong>Folder</strong>. type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">FileHistory</strong> as the folder name, and then press Enter.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click the <strong>FileHistory</strong> folder, and then select <strong>Properties</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>FileHistory Properties</strong> dialog box, on the <strong>Security</strong> tab, select <strong>Edit</strong>. Select <strong>Add</strong>, in the <strong>Enter the object names to select</strong> box, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Domain Users</strong>, and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Domain Users</strong>, and in the <strong>Permissions for Domain Users</strong> section, in the Allow column, select the <strong>Full control</strong> check box, and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Sharing</strong> tab, select <strong>Advanced Sharing</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select the <strong>Share this folder</strong> check box, and then select <strong>Permissions</strong>. In the <strong>Permissions for Everyone</strong> section, in the Allow column, select <strong>Full Control</strong>, and then select <strong>OK</strong> twice.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>FileHistory Properties</strong> dialog box, select <strong>Close</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close File Explorer.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of LON-DC1.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-configure-and-test-file-history">Task 2: Configure and test File History</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Switch to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> and sign in as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong>, with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>, on the taskbar, select <strong>File Explorer</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In File Explorer, in the navigation pane, expand <strong>This PC</strong>, and then select <strong>Documents</strong>. In the details pane, right-click an empty space, point to <strong>New</strong>, select <strong>Text Document</strong>, and then enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Report</strong> as the name of the file.</p> </li> <li> <p>Double-click <strong>Report.txt</strong>, and in Notepad, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">This is a report</strong>. Close the Notepad file, and then select <strong>Save</strong> to save the changes.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong>, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">file history</strong>, and then select <strong>Restore your files with File History</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Home – File History</strong> window, select <strong>Configure File History settings</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>File History</strong> window, in the navigation pane, select <strong>Select drive</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Select Drive</strong> dialog box, select <strong>Add network location</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Folder</strong> box, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">&bsol;&bsol;LON-DC1&bsol;FileHistory</strong>, select <strong>Select Folder</strong>, and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>File History</strong> window, in the details pane, select <strong>Turn on</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the navigation pane, select <strong>Advanced settings</strong>, review the default values for how often to save copies of files and how long to keep saved versions, and then select <strong>Cancel</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In File Explorer, in the navigation pane, select <strong>Documents</strong>, right-click <strong>Report.txt</strong>, and then select <strong>Delete</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In File Explorer, in the navigation pane, right-click <strong>Documents</strong>, select <strong>Restore previous versions</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Documents Properties window, select the <strong>Previous Versions</strong> tab.</p> <blockquote> <p>Notice that the Previous Versions tab displays the Documents file that was previously deleted. </p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>On the Previous Versions tab, select the document and then click the arrow next to <strong>Open</strong> and then select <strong>Open in File History</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Documents-File History window, right-click <strong>Report.txt</strong> and then select <strong>Preview</strong>. Verify that the file contains the text you entered when the file was created.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Documents-File History window, select the <strong>Restore to original location</strong> button.</p> </li> <li> <p>File Explorer opens. Verify that Report.txt has been restored to the original location and then close File Explorer.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Report.txt – File History window, on the left of the address box, select the upward-pointing arrow twice.</p> </li> <li> <p>Review the folders and libraries that File History is protecting, and confirm that the a folder named Data and a folder named Reports are not among them.</p> <blockquote> <p>File history protects a number of default folders and libraries. For custom folders you need to include them in the library as shown in the next exercise.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>Close the <strong>Home – File History</strong> window.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close all open windows on LON-CL1.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise, you will have successfully configured File History and validated a successful recovery of a protected file.</p> <h2 id="exercise-2-protecting-custom-folders-using-file-history">Exercise 2: Protecting Custom Folders using File History</h2> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>A request has been made to use File History to protect two custom folders on LON-CL1 named Data and Reports. Both folders need to be added to the Documents library to be protected by File History.</p> <h3 id="task-1-configure-the-lab-environment">Task 1: Configure the lab environment</h3> <blockquote> <p>This task is needed to create the folder structure to be used in the lab scenario.</p> </blockquote> <ol> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>, open File Explorer, and then browse to <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">&bsol;&bsol;LON-DC1&bsol;labfiles&bsol;Support&bsol;</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the content pane, double-click <strong>CopyUserData.bat</strong> to copy lab files to the local client.</p> </li> <li> <p>In File Explorer, in the navigation pane, expand <strong>Local Disk (C:)</strong>, and then select <strong>Data</strong>. In the details pane, right-click <strong>Sales.txt</strong>, select <strong>Properties</strong>, select the <strong>Previous Versions</strong> tab, confirm that there are no previous versions available, and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-configure-file-history-to-protect-custom-folders">Task 2: Configure File History to protect custom folders</h3> <ol> <li> <p>In the navigation pane, right-click <strong>Data</strong>, point to <strong>Include in library</strong>, and then select <strong>Documents</strong>. </p> <blockquote> <p>As File History protects the Documents library, File History is now also protecting the Data folder.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>In File Explorer, in the navigation pane, select <strong>Reports</strong>. In the details pane, right-click <strong>Report.txt</strong>, select <strong>Properties</strong>, select the <strong>Previous Versions</strong> tab, confirm that there are no previous versions available, and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the navigation pane, right-click <strong>Reports</strong>, point to <strong>Include in library</strong>, and then select <strong>Documents</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong>, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">file history</strong>, and then select <strong>File History</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>File History</strong> window, in the <strong>File History is on</strong> section, select <strong>Run now</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In File Explorer, in the details pane, right-click <strong>Report.txt</strong>, select <strong>Properties</strong>, select the <strong>Previous Versions</strong> tab, verify that there is now one previous version, and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the navigation pane, right-click <strong>Data</strong>, select <strong>Properties</strong>, select the <strong>Previous Versions</strong> tab, and then select <strong>Data</strong> in the <strong>Folder versions</strong> section.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select the arrow near the <strong>Restore</strong> button, and then verify that you can restore the previous version either to the original location or to a custom location.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Data Properties</strong> dialog box, select the arrow near the <strong>Open</strong> button, and then select <strong>Open in File History</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Data – File History window, on the left of the address box, select the upward-pointing arrow once. </p> <blockquote> <p>Notice that File History is protecting the Data and Reports folders, in addition to the Users folder, which is protected by default.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>In the C:&bsol; - File History window, select the upward-pointing arrow again to view all folders and libraries that File History is protecting.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close the Home – File History window, in the <strong>Data Properties</strong> dialog box, select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close all open windows and sign out of LON-CL1.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise, you will have successfully added additional folders to be protected by using File History.</p> <p><strong>END OF LAB</strong></p> </div> <div class="page" id="page28"> <h1 id="practice-lab-using-windows-re-and-advanced-startup-to-recover-from-boot-failures">Practice Lab 28: Using Windows RE and Advanced Startup to recover from Boot Failures</h1> <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2> <p>In this lab you work with the Windows Recovery Environment (RE) and use System Configuration and Startup Settings to access advanced startup options.</p> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>You need to test and validate the features available for when you need to recover from boot failures on a Windows client. You will access Windows RE to identify the recovery options that are available. You will also use System Configuration and Startup Settings to access the advanced startup options.</p> <h3 id="task-1-use-windows-recovery-environment">Task 1: Use Windows Recovery Environment</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Switch to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the sign-in page, hold down the SHIFT key on your keyboard, select the <strong>Power</strong> button, and then select <strong>Restart</strong>.</p> <blockquote> <p>Windows restarts in the Windows recovery environment</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Choose an option</strong> page, select <strong>Troubleshoot</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Troubleshoot</strong> page, select <strong>Advanced options</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Advanced options</strong> page, notice the six tools that are available.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Command Prompt</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the command prompt, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">diskpart</strong>, and then select Enter.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the command prompt, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">list disk</strong>, and then select Enter.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the command prompt, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">list volume</strong>, and then select Enter. </p> <blockquote> <p>Notice that Drive E is the 100 GB NTFS volume. This is the volume that contains the Windows files.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>At the command prompt, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">exit</strong>, and then select Enter.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the command prompt, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">E:</strong>, and then select Enter.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the command prompt, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">dir</strong>, and then select Enter. This is the system drive.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the command prompt, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">cd&bsol;windows&bsol;system32</strong>, and then select Enter.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the command prompt, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">net start</strong>, and then select Enter. A list of running services is returned.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the command prompt, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">sc query</strong>, and then select Enter. A list of services and their current status is returned.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the command prompt, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">regedit</strong>, and then select Enter. The Registry Editor opens.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close the Registry Editor.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the command prompt, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">exit</strong>, and then select Enter.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Choose an option page, select <strong>Troubleshoot</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Troubleshoot</strong> page, select <strong>Advanced options</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Advanced options page, select <strong>Startup Repair</strong>. Automatic startup repair begins.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Startup Repair page, notice the log file (E:&bsol;Windows&bsol;System32&bsol;Logfiles&bsol;Srt&bsol;SrtTrail.txt) mentioned in the message.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Advanced options</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Choose an option page, select <strong>Continue</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign in as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> by using the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the taskbar, select <strong>File Explorer</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In File Explorer, navigate to <strong>E:&bsol;Windows&bsol;System32&bsol;Logfiles&bsol;Srt</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Srt</strong> folder, open <strong>SrtTrail.txt</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Examine the file for any errors. (ignore any errors for this lab scenario.)</p> </li> <li> <p>Close the file, and then close File Explorer.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-use-system-configuration-to-modify-boot-options">Task 2: Use System Configuration to modify boot options</h3> <ol> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>, select <strong>Start</strong>, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">msconfig.exe</strong>, and then select Enter. The System Configuration application opens.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the System Configuration dialog box, select the <strong>Boot</strong> tab.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Boot tab, select the <strong>Safe boot</strong> check box, and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the System Configuration dialog box, select <strong>Restart</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>When the computer restarts, sign in as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> by using the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>. </p> <blockquote> <p>Notice that the desktop now displays Safe Mode in each corner.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>Right-click <strong>Start</strong> or activate its context menu, and then select <strong>Run</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Run box, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">msconfig.exe</strong>, and then select Enter.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the System Configuration dialog box, on the General tab, select <strong>Normal startup</strong>, and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the System Configuration dialog box, select <strong>Restart</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>When the computer restarts, sign in as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> by using the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>. </p> <blockquote> <p>Notice that the Windows operating system starts normally.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>, select <strong>Start</strong>, and then select <strong>Settings</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In <strong>Settings</strong>, select <strong>System</strong> and then select <strong>Recovery</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the results pane, next to <strong>Advanced startup</strong>, select <strong>Restart now</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the message prompt, select <strong>Restart now</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Choose an option page, select <strong>Troubleshoot</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Troubleshoot page, select <strong>Advanced options</strong>.</p> </li> </ol> <ol> <li> <p>On the Advanced options page, select <strong>Startup Settings</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Startup Settings page, select <strong>Restart</strong>. </p> <blockquote> <p>Notice the Startup Settings are similar to what was available in the System Configuration tool.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>On the Startup Settings page, press <strong>Enter</strong> to start normally.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise, you should have started Windows RE and used System Configuration and Startup Settings to access advanced startup options.</p> <p><strong>END OF LAB</strong></p> </div> <div class="page" id="page29"> <h1 id="practice-lab-troubleshooting-boot-failure-with-the-bcd-store">Practice Lab 29: Troubleshooting Boot Failure with the BCD store</h1> <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2> <p>In this lab, you will troubleshoot startup issues with the Windows Boot Configuration Data (BCD) store.</p> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>A user named Jim has reported that while attempting to configure a dual-boot Windows environment, LON-CL1 will no longer boot into any operating system. You need to identify and resolve the issue so that Jim can have a functioning Windows 11 device.</p> <h3 id="task-1-simulate-the-issue">Task 1: Simulate the issue</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Open File Explorer and then browse to <strong>E:&bsol;Labfiles&bsol;Mod12</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Run the <strong>E:&bsol;Labfiles&bsol;Mod12&bsol;scenario1.vbs</strong> script.</p> </li> <li> <p>Wait for LON-CL1 to restart.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-resolve-the-issue">Task 2: Resolve the issue</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Attempt to resolve the issue by using your knowledge of boot failure troubleshooting . If you are unable to resolve the problem, escalate it by asking your instructor for additional guidance. The following steps provide the troubleshooting steps and solution to the issue.</p> </li> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>, read the information presented on the <strong>Recovery</strong> screen.</p> </li> <li> <p>Press <strong>F1</strong> on your keyboard to boot into the Recovery Environment.</p> <blockquote> <p>Note: If you take too long to press F1, the machine will automatically turn off. At this point select Start to start the machine and then press F1 to enter the Recovery Environment.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>At the <strong>Choose your keyboard</strong> layout, select <strong>US</strong>.</p> <blockquote> <p>The Windows recovery environment starts.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>On the Choose an option page, select <strong>Troubleshoot</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Advanced options page, select <strong>Command Prompt</strong>. </p> </li> <li> <p>At the command prompt, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">bcdedit /enum</strong>, and then select Enter. </p> <blockquote> <p>This lists the available boot options in the store. Notice that there is no default entry to the C:&bsol;Windows environment.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>At the command prompt, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">bootrec /rebuildbcd</strong>, and then select Enter. </p> <blockquote> <p>This command attempts to rebuild the boot store automatically, however it cannot find a Windows installation to rebuild. We will use diskpart to verify that the original Windows installation is available.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>At the command prompt, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">diskpart</strong>, and then press Enter.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the diskpart command, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">list disk</strong> and press Enter. Notice there is only one disk on the system.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the diskpart command, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">select Disk 0</strong> and press Enter.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the diskpart command, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">list volume</strong>.</p> <p>This command lists the volumes on Disk 0. Notice that C is labeled on a Hidden drive. Also D is labeled for the DVD-ROM. Also notice that Volume 1 is a 126 GB NTFS partition. This is the original Windows installation. We need to give it a drive letter so that we can fix the BCD.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the diskpart command, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Select volume 1</strong> and press Enter.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the diskpart command, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Assign letter = E:</strong> and press Enter.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the diskpart command, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">list volume</strong>. Notice that Volume 1 now has a drive letter E.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the diskpart command, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">exit</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the command prompt, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">bootrec /scanos</strong>, and then press Enter. </p> <blockquote> <p>Notice that a Windows installation is now identified.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>At the command prompt, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">bcdboot E:&bsol;Windows</strong> and press Enter.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the command prompt, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Exit</strong> and press Enter.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the Choose an option screen, select <strong>Continue</strong> to exit and continue to Windows 11.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> <blockquote> <p>Notice that you can now start and sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>. </p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>Select Start, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">cmd</strong>, and then press Enter to open the command prompt.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the command prompt enter the following command and press Enter.</p> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-symbol">reagentc</span> /<span class="hljs-meta">info</span></code> </pre> <blockquote> <p>Notice that the Windows RE status is disabled. We will enable Windows RE for future troubleshooting.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>At the command prompt, enter the following command and press Enter.</p> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-symbol">reagentc</span> /enable</code> </pre> <pre> <code><span class="hljs-symbol">reagentc</span> /<span class="hljs-meta">info</span></code> </pre> <blockquote> <p>Notice that Windows RE is now enabled.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of LON-CL1.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise, you will have identified and fixed the BCD issue on LON-CL1. The device can now start and sign in to Windows 11 successfully.</p> <p><strong>END OF LAB</strong></p> </div> <div class="page" id="page30"> <h1 id="practice-lab-recovering-windows-using-reset-this-pc">Practice Lab 30: Recovering Windows using Reset This PC</h1> <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2> <p>During this lab you will recover a Windows client device using Reset This PC.</p> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>You discover that LON-CL1 is having intermittent issues. Repeated attempts have been made to correct the issues, but have been unsuccessful. You&#39;ve decided to try resetting the PC. You would like to still retain the user files on the PC.</p> <h3 id="task-1-use-the-reset-this-pc-option">Task 1: Use the Reset this PC option</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password of <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>, right-click the desktop, point to <strong>New</strong>, select <strong>Text Document</strong>, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Report</strong> as its name, and then press Enter.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click the <strong>Start</strong> icon, select <strong>Windows Terminal</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Windows PowerShell prompt, type <code>sysdm.cpl</code> and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Verify that the device name is <strong>LON-CL1</strong> and that it is in the <strong>Adatum.com</strong> domain.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong>, select <strong>Update & Security</strong>, and then select <strong>Recovery</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Recovery page, under <strong>Reset this PC</strong>, select <strong>Get started</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Reset this PC dialog box, select <strong>Keep my files</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>When prompted to select where to reinstall Windows from, select <strong>Local reinstall</strong>, and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Ready to reset this PC page, select <strong>View apps that will be removed</strong>. Take note of the apps and then select <strong>Back</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Ready to reset this PC page, select <strong>Reset</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Wait for the reset to complete. It will take a while to complete.</p> <blockquote> <p>Your instructor may choose to continue with the next module while this task completes. Be sure to return to complete Task 2 when the next lab session begins.</p> </blockquote> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-verify-that-reset-this-pc-was-successful">Task 2: Verify that Reset this PC was successful</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password of <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Verify that the file <strong>Report.txt</strong> is still available on the desktop.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the desktop, double-click the <strong>Removed Apps</strong> report and verify the apps that have been removed while resetting the PC.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close Microsoft Edge.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click the <strong>Start</strong> icon, select <strong>Windows Terminal</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Windows PowerShell prompt, type <code>sysdm.cpl</code> and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Verify that the device name is LON-CL1 and that it is in the Adatum.com domain.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close all open windows.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of LON-CL1.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise, you will have successfully recovered LON-CL1 by using Reset This PC.</p> <p><strong>END OF LAB</strong></p> </div> <div class="page" id="page31"> <h1 id="practice-lab-recovering-windows-by-using-a-system-protection-and-a-restore-point">Practice Lab 31: Recovering Windows by using a System Protection and a Restore Point</h1> <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2> <p>During this lab, you will recover a Windows client device by using System Protection and Restore Point.</p> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>A colleague reports that after attempting to install a new printer on LON-CL1, all of the Print drivers are no longer available. You remember that a System Restore Point had been previously created that enables you to return to a previous working state. You decide to use System Protection and restore LON-CL1 to that previous state.</p> <h3 id="task-1-configure-system-protection-and-create-a-restore-point">Task 1: Configure System Protection and Create a Restore Point</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password of <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the taskbar, select <strong>Start</strong> and the type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Printers</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the search results, under <strong>Printers &amp; scanners</strong>, select <strong>Open</strong>. The <strong>Settings</strong> window opens at the <strong>Printers &amp; scanners</strong> page.</p> <blockquote> <p>Notice the four printers that are configured (Fax, Microsoft Print to PDF, Microsoft XPS Document Writer, and OneNote.)</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Settings</strong> window, select <strong>System</strong> and then scroll down and select <strong>About</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under the <strong>Device specifications</strong> section, next to <strong>Related links</strong> select <strong>System protection</strong>. The <strong>System Properties</strong> box opens on the <strong>System Protection</strong> tab.</p> </li> <li> <p>On <strong>System Protection</strong> tab, in the <strong>Protection Settings</strong> section, select <strong>Local Disk (C:) (System)</strong>, select <strong>Configure</strong>, select <strong>Turn on system protection</strong>, move the <strong>Max Usage</strong> slider to <strong>5%</strong>, and then select <strong>OK</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under <strong>Protection Settings</strong>, next to <strong>Create a restore point right now for the drives that have system protection turned on</strong>, select <strong>Create</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Create a restore point</strong> box, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Initial Restore Point</strong>, and then select <strong>Create</strong>.</p> <blockquote> <p>System Protection creates a new restore point.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>When the the System Protection message box is displayed, select <strong>Close</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>System Properties</strong> box, select <strong>OK</strong>, and then close the <strong>Settings</strong> window.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-simulate-the-problem">Task 2: Simulate the Problem</h3> <ol> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong>, open File Explorer, and browse to <strong>E:&bsol;Labfiles&bsol;Mod13</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the Mod13 folder, double-click <strong>scenario1.vbs</strong>. </p> </li> <li> <p>At the Windows Script Host message, select <strong>OK</strong>, and then close File Explorer.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-3-perform-a-system-restore">Task 3: Perform a System Restore</h3> <ol> <li> <p>On the taskbar, select <strong>Start</strong> and the type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Printers</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the search results, under <strong>Printers &amp; scanners</strong>, select <strong>Open</strong>. The <strong>Settings</strong> window opens at the <strong>Printers &amp; scanners</strong> page.</p> <blockquote> <p>Notice that the four printers are no longer available. You will use System Restore to restore LON-CL1 to a previous known good state.)</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Settings</strong> window, select <strong>System</strong> and then scroll down and select <strong>About</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under the <strong>Device specifications</strong> section, next to <strong>Related links</strong> select <strong>System protection</strong>. The <strong>System Properties</strong> box opens on the <strong>System Protection</strong> tab.</p> </li> <li> <p>On <strong>System Protection</strong> tab, under <strong>System Restore</strong>, select <strong>System Restore</strong>. The System Restore wizard starts.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Restore system files and settings</strong> page, select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> <blockquote> <p>Notice the restore points that have been saved on LON-CL1.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Restore your computer to the state it was in before the selected event</strong> page, select <strong>Initial Restore Point</strong>, and then select <strong>Scan for affected programs</strong>.</p> <blockquote> <p>System Restore scans for any affected programs or drivers as a result of reverting to the selected the restore point.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>System Restore</strong> window, confirm that no programs or drivers will be deleted and then select <strong>Close</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Restore your computer to the state it was in before the selected event</strong> page, select <strong>Initial Restore Point</strong>, and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Confirm your restore point</strong> page, confirm the information and then select <strong>Finish</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Warning message, select <strong>Yes</strong>.</p> <blockquote> <p>System restore begins to restore the Initial Restore Point. LON-CL1 will also restart during this process. This will take a few minutes to complete.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password of <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>When the the System Restore message box is displayed, select <strong>Close</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the taskbar, select <strong>Start</strong> and the type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Printers</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the search results, under <strong>Printers &amp; scanners</strong>, select <strong>Open</strong>. The <strong>Settings</strong> window opens at the <strong>Printers &amp; scanners</strong> page.</p> <blockquote> <p>Notice the four printers have been restored to the previous state (Fax, Microsoft Print to PDF, Microsoft XPS Document Writer, and OneNote.)</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>Close the <strong>Settings</strong> window and sign out of LON-CL1.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After completing this exercise, you should have successfully used System Protection and recovered a Windows client to a previous System Restore Point.</p> <p><strong>END OF LAB</strong></p> </div> <div class="page" id="page32"> <h1 id="practice-lab-deploying-windows-desktop-settings-using-a-provisioning-package">Practice Lab 32: Deploying Windows Desktop settings using a provisioning package</h1> <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2> <p>In this lab, you identify the tools included in the Windows ADK, install the Configuration Designer component of the Windows ADK, create a provisioning package, and then deploy the configuration package to a Windows 11 desktop device.</p> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>As part of the Desktop Administration team at Adatum, you have been tasked with deploying new Windows 11 desktop devices to users. The devices have been purchased with Windows 11 pre-installed. You need to use the Configuration Designer to create a provisioning package that applies the following settings on the new devices:</p> <ul> <li>A device name in the format of <strong>LON-CL%RAND:2%</strong>, which specifies LON-CL with two random numbers.</li> <li>Join the device to the Adatum.com Active Directory domain.</li> <li>Create a local administrator account with the name LocalAdmin with the password of Pa55w.rd.</li> <li>Install two applications named PowerToys and Power BI Desktop to the device.</li> </ul> <h3 id="task-1-identify-the-windows-adk-tools">Task 1: Identify the Windows ADK tools</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(1)&quot;).click()">LON-DC1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the taskbar, select <strong>Start</strong> and then select <strong>Control Panel</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Programs</strong>, and then select <strong>Programs and Features</strong>. </p> <blockquote> <p>Notice that the <strong>Windows Assessment and Deployment Kit</strong> and the <strong>Windows Assessment and Deployment Kit Windows Preinstallation Environment Add-ons</strong> programs are installed.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Windows Assessment and Deployment Kit</strong> and then select <strong>Change</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Maintain your Windows Assessment and Deployment Kit features</strong> page, ensure that <strong>Change</strong> is selected and then select <strong>Next</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Notice the features that have been installed on LON-DC1. Features include:</p> <ul> <li> <p>Deployment Tools</p> </li> <li> <p>User State Migration Tool (USMT)</p> </li> <li> <p>Microsoft User Experience Virtualization (UE-V) Template</p> <blockquote> <p>Notice that Configuration Designer is not installed.</p> </blockquote> </li> </ul> </li> <li> <p>Select the check box next to <strong>Configuration Designer</strong>, and then select <strong>Change</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Windows Assessment and Deployment Kit window, select <strong>Close</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close the <strong>Programs and Features</strong> window.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-create-a-provisioning-package">Task 2: Create a provisioning package</h3> <ol> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(1)&quot;).click()">LON-DC1</a></strong>, select <strong>Start</strong>, expand <strong>Windows Kits</strong>, and then select <strong>Windows Imaging and Configuration Designer</strong>. </p> <blockquote> <p>The <strong>Windows Configuration Designer</strong> opens at the <strong>Start page</strong>.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Start page</strong>, select <strong>Provision desktop devices</strong>. The <strong>New project</strong> window opens.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>New project</strong> window, under <strong>Name</strong>, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Windows 11 Provision Package</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under <strong>Description</strong>, type the following:</p> <ul> <li><strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Assigns a device name in the format of LON-CL%RAND:2%. Joins the device to Adatum.com. Creates a local administrator account with the name LocalAdmin with the password of Pa55w.rd, and adds an application named PowerToys to the device.</strong></li> </ul> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Finish</strong>. A new page named <strong>Windows 11 Provision Package</strong> displays with several configuration steps.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Set up Device</strong> step, configure the following setting:</p> <ul> <li>Under <strong>Device name</strong>, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">LON-CL%RAND:2%</strong>.</li> </ul> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Set up network</strong> step, under <strong>Set up network</strong>, disable the <strong>Connect devices to a Wi-Fi network</strong> option. </p> <blockquote> <p>The lab environment does not have Wi-Fi capable virtual machines and will be disabled for this scenario.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Account management</strong> step, configure the following settings:</p> <ul> <li>Enroll into Active Directory: <strong>Selected</strong></li> <li>Domain name: <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum.com</strong></li> <li>User name: <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong></li> <li>User password: <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong></li> <li>Under Optional: Create a local administrator account enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">LocalAdmin</strong> as the User name and <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong> as the Password.</li> </ul> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Add applications</strong> step, select <strong>Add an application</strong> and then configure the following settings:</p> <ul> <li>Application name: <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Power BI Desktop</strong></li> <li>Installer path: <strong>E:&bsol;Labfiles&bsol;Apps&bsol;PowerBI&bsol;PBIDesktop_x64.msi</strong></li> <li>Continue installations after failure: <strong>Yes</strong></li> <li>In the <strong>Command line arguments</strong> box, at the end of the command add <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">ACCEPT_EULA=1</strong> and then select <strong>Add</strong>.</li> </ul> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Add applications</strong> step, select <strong>Add an application</strong> and then configure the following settings:</p> <ul> <li>Application name: <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">PowerToys</strong></li> <li>Installer path: <strong>E:&bsol;Labfiles&bsol;Apps&bsol;PowerToys&bsol;PowerToysSetup-x64.exe</strong></li> <li>In the <strong>Command line arguments</strong> box, at the end of the command add <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">-passive</strong> and then select <strong>Add</strong>. The passive switch allows the display of the installation status, but will not require any input.</li> </ul> </li> <li> <p>Select the <strong>Finish</strong> step and review the <strong>Summary</strong> information.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Summary</strong> page, select <strong>Create</strong>. Take note of the name and saved location of the package which should be:</p> <ul> <li>Name: <strong>Windows 11 Provision Package.ppkg</strong> </li> <li>Saved location: <strong>C:&bsol;Users&bsol;Administrator.ADATUM&bsol;Document&bsol;Windows Imaging and Configuration Designer (WCID)&bsol;Windows 11 Provision Package</strong></li> </ul> </li> <li> <p>Close the Windows Configuration Designer.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-3-deploy-a-provisioning-package-to-a-windows-device">Task 3: Deploy a provisioning package to a Windows device</h3> <ol> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(1)&quot;).click()">LON-DC1</a></strong>, on the taskbar, select <strong>File Explorer</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In <strong>File Explorer</strong>, under <strong>Quick access</strong>, select <strong>Documents</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Documents</strong> folder, open the <strong>Windows Imaging and Configuration Designer (WCID)</strong> folder.</p> </li> <li> <p>From the <strong>Windows Imaging and Configuration Designer (WCID)</strong> folder, select the <strong>Windows 11 Provision Package</strong> folder.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Home</strong> tab, select <strong>Copy</strong> .</p> </li> <li> <p>In the navigation pane, select <strong>Allfiles (E:)</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Open the <strong>Labfiles</strong> folder and then open the <strong>Provisioning</strong> folder.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Home</strong> tab, select <strong>Paste</strong> to copy the <strong>Windows 11 Provision Package</strong> folder to the <strong>Provisioning</strong> folder.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close <strong>File Explorer</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Switch to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> and sign in as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Admin</strong> with the password of <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the taskbar, select <strong>File Explorer</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the address bar, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">&bsol;&bsol;LON-DC1&bsol;Labfiles</strong> and then press Enter.</p> </li> <li> <p>When prompted, in the <strong>Windows Security</strong> box, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password of <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Open the <strong>Provisioning</strong> folder.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select the <strong>Windows 11 Provision Package</strong> folder, and then select <strong>Copy</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the navigation pane, select <strong>Downloads</strong>, and then select <strong>Paste</strong> the <strong>Windows 11 Provision Package</strong> folder to the <strong>Downloads</strong> folder.</p> </li> <li> <p>From the <strong>Downloads</strong> folder, open the <strong>Windows 11 Provision Package</strong> folder and then run the <strong>Windows 11 Provision Package.ppkg</strong> file.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the <strong>User Account Control</strong> box, select <strong>Yes</strong>. A dialog box opens that states <strong>Is this package from a source you trust?</strong> </p> </li> <li> <p>Read the package details and then select <strong>Yes, add it</strong>.</p> <blockquote> <p>In a couple of minutes, the two apps install, followed by a message that Windows will shut down in 1 minute. </p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Close</strong> and then wait until the device restarts.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-4-validate-the-configuration">Task 4: Validate the configuration</h3> <ol> <li> <p>After the device restarts, select <strong>Other user</strong> and sign in as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Jon</strong> with the password of <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>. Wait for the initial profile to be configured.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Start menu, select <strong>Settings</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>System</strong> page, verify that the Computer name is <strong>LON-CL</strong> followed by two random numbers.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Start menu, select <strong>Apps</strong> and then select <strong>Apps &amp; features</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Verify that both <strong>Microsoft Power BI Desktop (x64)</strong> and <strong>PowerToys (Preview) x64</strong> are both listed as installed applications.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close the <strong>Settings</strong> window.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click the Start button, and then select <strong>Computer Management</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In Computer Management, expand <strong>Local Users and Groups</strong>, and then select <strong>Users</strong>. </p> </li> <li> <p>Verify that the <strong>LocalAdmin</strong> user account is configured on the device.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close Computer Management and then sign out of the computer.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After finishing this lab, you will have successfully used Configuration Designer to create a provisioning package. You have also deployed the provisioning package to a Windows 11 device and verifed the changes.</p> <p><strong>END OF LAB</strong></p> </div> <div class="page" id="page33"> <h1 id="practice-lab-provision-a-kiosk-using-configuration-designer">Practice Lab 33: Provision a Kiosk using Configuration Designer</h1> <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2> <p>In this lab, you create a provisioning package to configure a Windows 11 device to run a single application when a specific user account is used to sign in.</p> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>In the reception area at Adatum, it’s necessary to deploy a new Windows 11 computer as a kiosk device. This new device will only run Microsoft News to provide guests the ability to review the latest News events. You need to use the Configuration Designer to create a provisioning package to configure kiosk settings on the device.</p> <h3 id="prerequisites">Prerequisites</h3> <p>The following lab(s) must be completed before this lab:</p> <ul> <li>0101-Deploying Windows Desktop settings using a provisioning package - Install the Configuration Designer from the Windows Assessment and Deployment Kit.</li> </ul> <h3 id="task-1-create-a-provisioning-package">Task 1: Create a provisioning package</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(1)&quot;).click()">LON-DC1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(1)&quot;).click()">LON-DC1</a></strong>, select <strong>Start</strong>, expand <strong>Windows Kits</strong>, and then select <strong>Windows Imaging and Configuration Designer</strong>. </p> <blockquote> <p>The <strong>Windows Configuration Designer</strong> opens at the <strong>Start page</strong>.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Start page</strong>, select <strong>Provision kiosk devices</strong>. The <strong>New project</strong> window opens.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>New project</strong> window, under <strong>Name</strong>, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Kiosk Provision Package</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Under <strong>Description</strong>, type the following:</p> <ul> <li><strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Assigns a device name in the format of Kiosk-%RAND:2%. Joins the device to Adatum.com. Configures the device to run as a Kiosk.</strong></li> </ul> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Finish</strong>. A new page named <strong>Kiosk Provision Package</strong> displays with several configuration steps.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Set up Device</strong> step, configure the following setting:</p> <ul> <li>Under <strong>Device name</strong>, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Kiosk-%RAND:2%</strong>.</li> </ul> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Set up network</strong> step, select the switch to disable this step. </p> <blockquote> <p>The lab environment does not have Wi-Fi capable virtual machines and will be disabled for this scenario.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Account management</strong> step, configure the following settings:</p> <ul> <li>Enroll into Active Directory: <strong>Selected</strong></li> <li>Domain name: <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum.com</strong></li> <li>User name: <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong></li> <li>User password: <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong></li> </ul> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Configure kisok account and app</strong> step, configure the following settings:</p> </li> <li> <p>User name: <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">KioskUser</strong></p> </li> <li>Password: <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong></li> <li>Under <strong>Configure the kiosk mode app</strong>, in the User name box: <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">KioskUser</strong></li> <li>App type: <strong>Universal Windows App</strong></li> <li> <p>Enter the AUMID for the app: <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Microsoft.BingNews_8wekyb3d8bbwe!AppexNews</strong> </p> <blockquote> <p>Note: you can determine the AUMID by running the <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">get-startapps -Name Microsoft News</strong> PowerShell command</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Configure kisok common settings</strong> step, review the settings, but do not change anything.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select the <strong>Finish</strong> step and review the <strong>Summary</strong> information.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Summary</strong> page, select <strong>Create</strong>. Take note of the name and saved location of the package which should be:</p> </li> <li> <p>Name: <strong>Kiosk Provision Package.ppkg</strong> </p> </li> <li> <p>Saved location: <strong>C:&bsol;Users&bsol;Administrator.ADATUM&bsol;Document&bsol;Windows Imaging and Configuration Designer (WCID)&bsol;Kiosk Provision Package</strong></p> </li> <li> <p>Close the Windows Configuration Designer.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-deploy-a-provisioning-package-to-a-windows-device">Task 2: Deploy a provisioning package to a Windows device</h3> <ol> <li> <p>On <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(1)&quot;).click()">LON-DC1</a></strong>, on the taskbar, select <strong>File Explorer</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In <strong>File Explorer</strong>, under <strong>Quick access</strong>, select <strong>Documents</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the <strong>Documents</strong> folder, open the <strong>Windows Imaging and Configuration Designer (WCID)</strong> folder.</p> </li> <li> <p>From the <strong>Windows Imaging and Configuration Designer (WCID)</strong> folder, select the <strong>Kiosk Provision Package</strong> folder.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Home</strong> tab, select <strong>Copy</strong> .</p> </li> <li> <p>In the navigation pane, select <strong>Allfiles (E:)</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Open the <strong>Labfiles</strong> folder and then open the <strong>Provisioning</strong> folder.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the <strong>Home</strong> tab, select <strong>Paste</strong> to copy the <strong>Kiosk Provision Package</strong> folder to the <strong>Provisioning</strong> folder.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close <strong>File Explorer</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Switch to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> and sign in as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Admin</strong> with the password of <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the taskbar, select <strong>File Explorer</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the address bar, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">&bsol;&bsol;LON-DC1&bsol;Labfiles</strong> and then press Enter.</p> </li> <li> <p>When prompted, in the <strong>Windows Security</strong> box, enter <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password of <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Open the <strong>Provisioning</strong> folder.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select the <strong>Kiosk Provision Package</strong> folder, and then select <strong>Copy</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>In the navigation pane, select <strong>Downloads</strong>, and then select <strong>Paste</strong> to copy the <strong>Kiosk Provision Package</strong> folder to the <strong>Downloads</strong> folder.</p> </li> <li> <p>From the <strong>Downloads</strong> folder, open the <strong>Kiosk Provision Package</strong> folder and then run the <strong>Kiosk Provision Package.ppkg</strong> file.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the <strong>User Account Control</strong> box, select <strong>Yes</strong>. A dialog box opens that states <strong>Is this package from a source you trust?</strong> </p> </li> <li> <p>Read the package details and then select <strong>Yes, add it</strong>.</p> <blockquote> <p>In a few moments, a message displays that states that Windows will shut down in 1 minute. </p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Close</strong> and then wait until the device restarts.</p> </li> </ol> <h3 id="task-3-validate-the-configuration">Task 3: Validate the configuration</h3> <ol> <li> <p>After the device restarts, select <strong>Other user</strong> and sign in as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">.&bsol;KioskUser</strong> with the password of <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>. </p> <blockquote> <p>Wait for the initial profile to be configured. After a moment, you are signed in. This verifies that the local account, KioskUser, was created. Microsoft News opens. This verifies that the kiosk application was assigned.</p> </blockquote> </li> <li> <p>To enter administrative mode for the Kiosk, press <strong>Ctrl+Alt+Delete</strong>, select <strong>Other user,</strong> and sign in as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password of <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> <blockquote> <p>Wait for the initial profile to be configured. After a moment, you are signed in. Note that the kiosk mode is only active when KioskUser is signed in. The Adatum&bsol;Administrator account signs in to the standard Windows 11 desktop.</p> </blockquote> </li> </ol> <p><strong>Results</strong>: After finishing this lab, you will have successfully deployed a provisioning package to configure a Windows 11 device as a kiosk to run a single application when a specific user account is used to sign in.</p> <p><strong>END OF LAB</strong></p> </div> <div class="page" id="page34"> <h1 id="practice-lab-migrating-user-state-using-usmt">Practice Lab 34: Migrating user state using USMT</h1> <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2> <p>In this lab you will migrate user state from one computer to another using the User State Migration Tool (USMT).</p> <h3 id="scenario">Scenario</h3> <p>You have deployed a new Windows 11 computer to a user named Ben. The new computer is named LON-CL2. You need to migrate the user state from Ben&#39;s Windows 10 computer named LON-CL1 to LON-CL2. The best way to do so is using the User State Migration Tool (USMT). The USMT install files are located at &bsol;&bsol;LON-DC1&bsol;Labfiles&bsol;Install&bsol;USMT. A location to store migration data has been provided at &bsol;&bsol;LON-DC1&bsol;Labfiles&bsol;Install&bsol;MigrationStore.</p> <h3 id="task-1-prepare-the-source-computer">Task 1: Prepare the source computer</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Ben</strong> with the password of <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click the <strong>desktop</strong>, hover over the <strong>New</strong> menu item, and then select <strong>Text Document</strong>. Type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Demofile</strong> and press <strong>Enter</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Double-click <strong>Demofile.txt</strong> and type some random text and then save the file. There should be several items on the desktop including DemoFile.txt and various desktop icons.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the desktop, right-click <strong>This PC</strong> and then select <strong>Manage</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Expand <strong>Local Users and Groups</strong>, and then select <strong>Users</strong>. Notice the local accounts including Admin, LocalUser1 and LocalUser2.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close <strong>Computer Management</strong> and sign out of LON-CL1.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(2)&quot;).click()">LON-CL1</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password of <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong>, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">cmd</strong> and press Enter. </p> </li> <li> <p>At the command prompt, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>:</p> </li> </ol> <pre> <code>Net Use F: <span class="hljs-symbol">&bsol;&bsol;</span>LON-DC1<span class="hljs-symbol">&bsol;L</span>abfiles<span class="hljs-symbol">&bsol;I</span>nstall<span class="hljs-symbol">&bsol;U</span>SMT /user:Adatum<span class="hljs-symbol">&bsol;A</span>dministrator Pa55w.rd</code> </pre> <ol> <li> <p>At the command prompt, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">F:</strong>, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the command prompt, type the following, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>:</p> </li> </ol> <pre> <code>Scanstate &bsol;&bsol;LON-DC1&bsol;Labfiles&bsol;Install&bsol;MigrationStore&bsol;Win10 /<span class="hljs-selector-tag">i</span>:migapp<span class="hljs-selector-class">.xml</span> /<span class="hljs-selector-tag">i</span>:miguser<span class="hljs-selector-class">.xml</span> /o</code> </pre> <p><em><strong>Note</strong>: This will take several minutes to complete.</em></p> <ol> <li>Close all open windows and sign out of LON-CL1.</li> </ol> <h3 id="task-2-complete-the-migration">Task 2: Complete the migration</h3> <ol> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(3)&quot;).click()">LON-CL2</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Ben</strong> with the password of <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> <p><em>Notice that the desktop icons are not visible and there is no Demofile.txt file on the desktop.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click <strong>Start</strong> and then select <strong>Computer Management</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Expand Local Users and Groups, and then select Users.</p> <p><em>Notice that LocalUser1 and LocalUser2 are not listed.</em></p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of LON-CL2.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(3)&quot;).click()">LON-CL2</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Administrator</strong> with the password of <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Select <strong>Start</strong> and type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">cmd</strong>. Select <strong>Run as administrator</strong>. </p> </li> <li> <p>At the command prompt, type the following command, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>:</p> </li> </ol> <pre> <code>Net Use F: <span class="hljs-symbol">&bsol;&bsol;</span>LON-DC1<span class="hljs-symbol">&bsol;L</span>abfiles<span class="hljs-symbol">&bsol;I</span>nstall<span class="hljs-symbol">&bsol;U</span>SMT /user:Adatum<span class="hljs-symbol">&bsol;A</span>dministrator Pa55w.rd</code> </pre> <ol> <li> <p>At the command prompt, type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">F:</strong>, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>At the command prompt, type the following, and then press <strong>Enter</strong>:</p> </li> </ol> <pre> <code>Loadstate &bsol;&bsol;LON-DC1&bsol;Labfiles&bsol;Install&bsol;MigrationStore&bsol;Win10 /<span class="hljs-selector-tag">i</span>:migapp<span class="hljs-selector-class">.xml</span> /<span class="hljs-selector-tag">i</span>:miguser<span class="hljs-selector-class">.xml</span> /lac:Pa55w<span class="hljs-selector-class">.rd</span> /lae /c</code> </pre> <ol> <li> <p>Type <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">exit</strong> to close the command prompt.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of LON-CL2.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign in to <strong><a href="#" class="selectMachineLink icon-link special-action-link" onclick="$(&quot;#resourcesExtensions > div:nth-child(3)&quot;).click()">LON-CL2</a></strong> as <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Adatum&bsol;Ben</strong> with the password of <strong class="typeText" title="Type Text" tabindex="0" role="button">Pa55w.rd</strong>.</p> </li> <li> <p>Right-click <strong>Start</strong> and then select <strong>Computer Management</strong>. Notice that LocalUser1 and LocalUser2 are both available.</p> </li> <li> <p>Close Computer Management.</p> </li> <li> <p>On the Desktop, notice the DemoFile.txt file which has been migrated from the old computer. Note: the Desktop icon settings will only apply if the client workstation is activated.</p> </li> <li> <p>Sign out of LON-CL2.</p> </li> </ol> <p><strong>END OF LAB</strong></p> </div>');
